summary: Powerful and haunting remake of a beloved song
reviewText: I normally despise remakes of my favorite songs . Invariably , they lose something of the charm of the original and translated to a modern musician 's style . Whether it is Madonna remaking Don McLean 's " American Pie , " Destiny 's Child remaking Roberta Flack 's " Killing Me Softly With His Song , " or the Dixie Chicks ' remaking Fleetwood Mac 's " Landslide , " it always feels to me like the new versions are little more than watered - down copies of the originals , annoying at best and downright soulless at worst . and Garfunkle 's classic " Sound of Silence " being performed by metal / rock band Disturbed began circulating on Facebook , I braced myself for the worst . The only thing worse than a modern remake of " Sound of Silence , " I thought , would be a metal cover of it . No , Disturbed 's version of " Sound of Silence " does not have the same tone and quiet thoughtfulness of Simon But instead of giving us a weak copy , Disturbed gives us something powerful and excellent , even masterful , in its own right . " Sound of Silence " is a slow , melancholy ballad , but while S&G made it thoughtful and wistful , Disturbed infuses it with a great sense of sadness and even rage that slowly builds to an ultimately hopeful crescendo . It makes for a haunting , yet in the end thrilling , listening experience . The singer 's voice struggles a bit with some of the higher notes but otherwise has a rich otherwise has a rich and even gorgeous tone , carrying a great deal of emotion as he sings . And despite Disturbed being mostly known for harder stuff like metal and hard rock , they do not spoil this cover with unnecessary guitar riffs or drum - bashing -- the instrumentation is mostly subdued and provides haunting accompaniment , though it apes the singer by building to a thundering , powerful crescendo in the end . A good song has singer and accompaniment working together rather than fighting one another , Disturbed did not change a single lyric of the song in the process of covering it , which I greatly appreciate . Sometimes covers take advantage of the song they are remaking by altering the lyrics , and this rarely works out for the best in my mind . Disturbed made a good call by keeping all the original lyrics in place -- their message of a society where people are afraid to speak out or listen to the ugly but necessary truth is still resonant today , I still love Simon but Disturbed 's cover is amazing , that I would call just as good as the original . Disturbed takes a well - known and well - loved song and makes it their own without weakening it at all , and I highly recommend it even to those who are not fond of the band or their style of music . You will not be disappointed .

summary: Shaking her Shakira?  Glad she got it out of her system.
reviewText: that I was getting something different with this Jewel ... that work out ? It is most definitely her beautiful voice and flair for some whimsical and fun lyrics that save this album that is musically not in her tone nor fit her style very well . I appreciate Jewel trying something new and I also am glad she got it out of her system and production does not fit her folksy shape and other natural instrumental sounds ; you will not find much of Still , even if the style is beneath her her voice still is as lovely as ever , even beneath 1 ) Stand : it is okay . Starting us off with Jewel 's voice front " Reach " would have been an appropriate title as she is reaching for something different here and this song sets the tone for the album pretty well . YOU : her lovely , soft voice saves a song without musical importance . and some fun namedropping in the lyrics with a buzzy chorus lifts this 4 ) Leave the Lights On : Now here is something that starts off a little more interesting with some brassy woodwinds Unfortunately when Jewel gets to the chorus the song loses steam but this is the most interesting song of the CD so far . 5 ) 2 Find YOU : Weak . 6 ) Fragile Heart : A bit slow with a country guitar twang slowly plucked . Too slow , though . 7 ) Doing Fine : " We are what everyone wants to be . " We are doing fine . Buried in the middle of the record the song is rather okay . 8) 2 Become 1 : The music is much more engaging and natural . This feels like a Jewel song 9 ) Haunted : A seductive and creepy song . Totally cool and kind of sensuous . Jewel 's moaning at the end of the song is ... well , let us just say that I am glad 10 ) Sweet Temptation : Sounding much more like a Shakira pop song this one actually pretty much works and is much better than any of the first three songs . Yes YOU Can : This one might just make you dance . Again , a love and a cautious observation . YOU & Me = Love : Dance pop bubblegum fluff . Overly easy political thoughts are dispensed . It is okay , unless you are tired of hearing popsters Not nearly one of her best social observation songs ( probably 14 ) Becoming : Lyrically well - suited to the empty dance - pop genre , Jewel witnesses her own " becoming " with her heart . that nice . As you might have guessed this is not my favorite Jewel album . But there is at least one gem on here that work . If you are interested in what Jewel has to offer I would highly suggest starting elsewhere ( personally , I would direct you to " This Way " ) and if you like your techno - dance - pop I would look somewhere else too .

I love the friendly chatter that opens this sweet tune . What is Going On was co - written by Renaldo ' Obie ' Benson , a member of the Four Tops , Motown songwriter Al Cleveland , Benson had witnessed police brutality in Berkeley and was really shook up by it . He began to ask himself all sorts of questions , like and why were kids being beaten at home ? why were kids being beaten at home ? Marvin Gaye was asking himself , with all the problems going on in my country , how am I supposed to keep singing love songs ? The song is a plea for people to talk with each other and explore alternatives to war and violence . ' For only love can conquer hate . ' It is amazing to me Will our world ever evolve to the kind of existence that everyone can enjoy ? Musically , I have always loved the drums . Marvin Gaye played a box drum accompaniment to the regular drums , producing this oversized ping pong ball quality . The saxophone opening is a classic . The legendary James Jamerson played the bass while laying on the floor . Excellent string arrangement .

The Theme from Route 66 by Nelson Riddle is now better known than the show for which it was composed and has become a classic . It also has the rare honor of becoming a hit single by public demand , not being released until September of ' 62 , while the show had been on the air since September of ' 60 . It is a remarkable piece , flinging you right into the scene , the bass being the rhythmic feeling of the road itself , the piano the breeze in your hair , the strings your soaring emotions as you cruise down the fabled highway . The middle section suggests night , as the music gets jazzier with a muted trumpet Another aspect of the Theme is it is timing , being popular in the late Fifties and early Sixties , a time of great prosperity and optimism in the country . The Theme is full of confidence that seem , at least in retrospect , to sum up the feeling of a country that for a glorious moment felt it was doing everything right and on top of the world . One of the great road songs ever .

I put this CD on my wish list , not knowing much about the artist . Wow !   I am completely floored by how much I like this CD . It is incredibly strong . " Rattle My Bones " blasts off the set with a tune penned by Brandi Carlisle . Its insistent beat & Laura & Lydia Rogers ' tight harmonies make the track shimmer , " There is no telling what I would do if I could get my hands on you , I want you & do not know But now I know I would like to try . " that has a gorgeous retro - Brill Building-60s feel with a strong melody , pumping beat , and tight harmony , " If you believe me then it is not too late ; And I will be praying all the while I wait , I still belong to you . " who has played with Lucinda Williams and so many other top - notch acts joins the sisters on electric guitar on " I Can not Find A Way " that is sure to bring female Everly Brothers comparisons with the tight harmonies . " Good Luck , Good Night , Goodbye " is another retro - pop gem with its effervescent keyboards sounding like a coffee percolator , " I know it is not a perfect world , but tonight I am the perfect girl , I had a man but he just lied , good luck , good night , goodbye . " While these are my VERY favorites , all of the rest of the tracks are incredibly strong . This set is great from start to finish .

summary: I'm bad for me, I'm bad for you.
reviewText:
and so they dye their hair a dark color and it makes them look odd and it makes them look odd Well , Why does his music sound like it is for kids ? Oh sure , he is adapted , unfortunately he is adapted to Blink 182 , Fall Out Boy , Panic at the Disco , and all the other bland trendy emo / punk bands of the last decade . Now sure , Rick rocks and tries to knock your socks off , but it just comes off like some kind of weird overcompensation . Like someone who is trying really really hard to sound hip And this bothers me . and Bruce Springsteen were also all born in 1949 just like Rick . that they have aged gracefully , doing their own thing , not trying to go with the trends , and sound respectable . But Rick here , well , you see , he is like but pretends to be young and it does not work ( or look quite right ) . My first Springfield cassette was 1984 's " Hard to Hold " , and I have stuck with him ever since . and listened to all of the albums I own leading up to this new release , the one thing I came away with is Every album of his has some really good tracks rounded out with filler . " Songs for the End of the World " is no different . In fact , the strongest songs are at the front with " Wide Awake " , " Our Ship 's Sinking " and " I Hate Myself " being the best songs on the entire disc . I suppose " Gabriel " is decent , I liked " One Way Street " , but all I could think about is how the guitar intro comes dangerously close to The although Rick has updated his sound , he has now churned out the same album at least three times--2004 's " Shock / Denial / Anger / Acceptance " although I have enjoyed Rick 's output since 1999 , the honest truth is ( and you know it is True if you are being honest with yourself here ) that Rick 's best work was with RCA . when he was at his best . From 1999 to 2012 , well I believe Rick has one great album left in him , but will he dispense with this emo / punk / pop sheen that made his 1980s work so good . Obviously Rick still has some rabid fans and it is not the best album of his career . Like most of his recent work it is just good . Also , the gimmick of using your iPhone application to recognize photos on the insert is kind of cheesy . and the extra content did not impress me , I am going to be the lone voice of reason here that it is okay Rick , you can age now , you can give us what we want -- your gray hair that actually sound like you It is okay to show some wrinkles and fat , you have earned it . It is okay to make more than one It is also okay to not make every song sound almost the same as the next , a problem I found with " Songs " . where is the digitally remastered catalog with bonus tracks or bonus discs ? Heck , Terribly hard to find in compact disc except for a few . and " Beautiful Feelings " near impossible to find on compact disc . Will we ever get to hear the original " Beautiful Feelings " Here is how " Songs for the End of the World " compares to Rick 's other works : 

 1972 Beginnings : I have not heard this . 1973 Comic Book Heroes : I have not heard this . 1974 Mission Magic ! : 1978/1984 Beautiful Feelings : I have not heard this . 1982 Success Has not Spoiled Me 1984 Hard to Hold : Two 2004 Shock / Denial / Anger / Acceptance : Two 2009 My Precious Little One : I have not heard this .

summary: Strait's latest hits set has length, depth
reviewText:
Hallelujah ! that is not skimpy ! that were made up of ten prior hits , Latest Greatest Straitest Hits is comprised of fifteen tracks , of While more extensive , this anthology is far from   perfect " Lead On " and " King Of The Mountain " ( the latter barely   scraped into the top 20 ) drag along unmelodically and are slower than   molasses . Some of the other singles seem like rewrites of old Strait hits   ( " I Can Still Make Cheyenne " recalling " Amarillo By Morning " and   " Adalida "   bringing to mind " The Love Bug " ) . With " Carrying Your Love With Me " If you think I am getting too nit - picky about this set , you may be right . The crisp , heartfelt delivery on " You Can not Make A Heart Love Somebody " is   just one example of And as " Blue Clear Sky " and " Round About Way " illustrate , no one   handles a play - on - words more effectively than Strait . You would also be   hard - pressed to find country music more riproaringly enjoyable than " We   Really Should not Be Doing This . Recent chart - topper " The Best Day " is   nice , but it also seems too similar to some old hits ( " Love Without End ,   Amen , " " Check Yes Or No ) . " Here our protagonist progresses through a love   for camping , cars , and finally , his ideal woman . Much better is " Murder On   Music Row , " a duet with Alan Jackson . This mega - event pairing of two of   modern country 's most traditional ( and successful ) artists is an   effectively acidic lament on the predominantly pop sound of today 's   country .... 
  As   noted earlier , Latest Greatest Straitest Hits is not flawless . In light of   its several strong points , however , it has to be recommended as a must buy   for all country music listeners .

UK Indie band Alt - J 's debut " An Awesome Wave " won the 2012 Mercury Music Prize with their inimitable style , a folky electronic rock blend . Their sophomore album " This Is All Yours " opens with " Intro " , a theatrical instrumental garnished with choral flourishes . " Arrival In Nara " has a lovely piano intro that takes up almost half the song before transforming into a cinematic acoustic ballad , while the brilliant ballad " Nara " about a Japanese city with roaming deer has a magical timbre and builds to an incredible crescendo . The last part of the trilogy " Leaving Nara " is a beautiful Sigur Rs - style warble , with a trippy and delightful cover of Bill Withers ' " Lovely Day " tacked on as a hidden track . " Left Hand Free " is a Bluesy rocker with vocalist Joe Newman slipping ( as he often does ) into what sounds like an extra terrestrial language at times , while the tender Falsetto - sung " Choice Kingdom " has an other - worldly aura . The acoustic " Hunger Of The Pine " features a sample of Miley Cyrus repeating " I am a female rebel " , whimsical and absolutely enchanting . The Bon Iver - like " Warm Foothills " features Conor Oberst , Lianne La Havas and Sivu sharply alternating vocals " Bloodflood Pt II " is the sequel to " Bloodflood " from their debut , a mysterious ballad with haunting synths and gently clattering percussion , swelling and ebbing to dramatic effect , an absolute highlight ! With the bar raised this high , it will be interesting to see how Alt - J can follow this up .

Finally free from record companies , contracts , and the like ; Nine Inch Nails mastermind Trent Reznor has unleashed " Ghosts I - IV " , an entire album of instrumental work . As a longtime NIN fan , I personally was a little apprehensive but thankfully , I ended up being pretty satisfied . and 28 in particular are the most memorable moments to be heard here , as there are some great uses of the piano ( ! ) to be heard Although at times " Ghosts " borderlines on self - indulgence , as a whole , the album is a real treat , and is a welcome departure from Nine Inch Nails ' usual brand of discontent . Clocking in at under two hours in length , " Ghosts " moves along without ever really feeling All in all , " Ghosts I - IV " is a more than welcome cry of freedom from Trent Reznor and co. , and with more " Ghosts " promised to be appearing in the future , here is hoping that Nine Inch Nails continue to climb new heights of creativity .

Godmakers Temptation is a classic VP sound , an engaging track , The following song Stone Roses Edge breaks into a gallop early on with some delicious guitars and nice keys surrounding them The first half of this release is pretty solid in fact . The Shakes ' last recording was pretty impressive , and presumably very successful , as the many studio manipulations employed on " Sound and Color " surely made production expensive . At the same time , this talented band cuts through the manipulations here or 4 dynamite songs , a couple with faster tempo , that show the better side of the Shakes , I think . In fact , the second half of the record is better than the first half . and Girls " is pretty organic soul and blues influenced music with a unique Shakes twist , I was really looking forward to this new issue , being a bit disappointed initially . But the essence of this core sound still comes through with patient listening . I would suggest cutting to track 6 a few times that makes the Shakes an exceptional group . and it has to be a challenge to develop a unique sound as a band , and particularly as a blues / rock band , to stay fresh and staid . but after much listening , I would say it is outstanding . So , there is some good stuff on " Sounds and hopefully this daring jump into electronica helps them find more inspiration and helps refine a somewhat different identity that is still a showcase for their talent , and does not sublimate it in a blur of electronic loops I feel no need to have all my favorite bands transition to music from outerspace . and powerful rock and helps keep it turning .

summary: Goofy and over-the-top but epic and entirely enjoyable hit of the '80s
reviewText: I love the music of the ' 80s ... but somehow I was blissfully unaware of this song 's existence until I stumbled upon it in a list from Cracked -- " The Most Terrifyingly Epic Songs of the ' 80s . " but had somehow overlooked this one entirely . Cracked has a sketchy record when it comes to recommendations , in my opinion , that I loved most of the other songs on this particular list ( " Eye of the Tiger , " " Do not Stop Believing , " " Holding Out for a Hero , " " Love is a Battlefield , " etc . ) I will just say ... if you are an unabashed fan of cheesy ' 80s poodle - hair rock , you will love this song . From the triumphant and drum riffs , this song 's instrumentation is the epitome of goofy ' 80s rock . but otherwise defying easy explanation . otherwise defying easy explanation . And the lead singer 's voice is nothing to write home about , though at least he actually tries to carry the tune yet somehow , this all WORKS . It is a goofy song , yes , but it is the kind of goofy that leaves a huge smile on your face . that is completely over - the - top but in the best possible way , and you can not help but want to bang your head but they sure hit a home run with this number . This song has found plenty of new fans thanks to " Arrested Development , " that show , it is almost impossible not to like this song . It is not the greatest hit of the ' 80s , but it sure is one of the most fun ... and yes , one of the most terrifyingly epic .

The Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles were all the rage for a few years although to be fair I did not know they were ninjas until quite some time later , thanks to the busybody interference of the self - appointed guardian of Britains national morals , Mary Whitehouse , that showing children scenes of ninjas doing things with nunchaku would contribute to the decline of a generation . To me they will always be the Teenage Mutant Hero Turtles , and no - one can tell me although looking back I now realize I never was entirely sure how Michelangelo defeated his foes with nothing more dangerous than a slice of pizza . This has been an astonishingly long - lived franchise   with the world having already been exposed to three separate animated TV series , a Japanese anime , a live - action TV series , we are now on our fifth movie based on the characters originally created by Kevin Eastman and Peter Laird in 1984 , following the original three movies in 1990 , 1991 and the 2007 CGI flop TMNT . The music of the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles films does not have the most distinguished history ; Monty Python music maestro John Du Prez scored the first three films , and Klaus Badelt wrote a decent Enter Brian Tyler ; having become Marvels go - to guy for music , with the scores for Iron Man 3 and Thor : The Dark World already under his belt , yet to come , Tyler looks set to challenge Hans Zimmer for the title of King of All Super - Heroes , and his score for the Turtles continues the trend of him writing strong , powerful , thematic orchestral scores in the grandest symphonic traditions . Brian Tyler has been writing wonderful music for Jonathan Liebesmans films for over a decade , ever since he scored the directors feature debut , Darkness Falls , in 2003 , or five years will know exactly what to expect : a large orchestra , a large choir , a strong main theme , lots of complicated action writing , and reprised fully in the conclusive TMNT March , is a belter : brass - heavy , powerful , heroic , It has a few superficial similarities to his themes from both Thor : The Dark World but on the whole this is immaterial . Tyler is pretty much the only guy writing memorable , recurring themes for super hero movies these days , and we need to be thankful for that fact alone . that fact alone . and large , is fast , dense , and lots of fun . Cues like the astonishing Splinter vs. Shredder , Turtles United , Shellacked , Shortcut , Cowabunga , and the enormously exciting Adrenaline are barnstormers . Most of them feature strong performances of the main theme , and Shortcut are especially noteworthy , with their chanted choral parts , back - and - forth brass writing , furiously slashing string runs , complicated rhythmic elements , and general sense of epic grandeur . and The Amazing Spider - Man , while some of horn / flute trills recall Michael Giacchinos Star Trek music . Similarly , the penultimate cue Buck Buck has a touch of the best parts of Hans Zimmers Man of Steel about it ; to be clear , all of these things are good things . and immense taiko drums underpinning several tracks . and Shredder play up this aspect of the score , that is very appealing . If Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles has a downside , its its total and utter lack of subtlety . that a comic book film about crime fighting amphibians requires the restraint but Tyler scores almost every scene in the film with apocalyptic bombast , as though every moment is the most important moment of the story , and by the end of the 70 - minute album I can anticipate some listeners will find the whole thing a little overwhelming . There Is very little sense of anticipation , build - up Adolescent Genetically Altered Shinobi Terrapins has some soothing choral work , an intimate piano element , and a mystery - shrouded little cello figure reminiscent of Tia Dalmas theme from the third Pirates of the Caribbean film . Later , Origins features some lovely harp glissandi , Brotherhood features an emotional string - that is quite exquisite , and Rise of the Four revisits the emotional choral panache heard during the opening moments of the first cue , before segueing into Finally , at the very end of Buck Buck a soothing electronic guitar element comes to take center stage , providing a sentimental , but defiantly contemporary coda to all the chaos . that in terms of sheer entertainment value , Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles is one of the most enjoyable scores of 2014 for me so far . which kick ass while wearing their hearts on their sleeves are hard to come by these days ; too many scores , especially in the super hero genre , have begun take themselves far too seriously , eschewing escapist entertainment in favor of tortured , dark tales of retribution and twisted morality . and entertaining does not mean sacrificing musical creativity which Tyler once again proves he has in spades .

summary: Does justice to the Dead's best, most consistent latter-day tour
reviewText: For much of my 17 years of Grateful Dead fandom I was , admittedly , what Deadheads refer to as a 60 's & 70 's snob . and Dick 's Picks , only a handful were from the Brent Mydland years of ' 79-'90 or six years back--1990 's ' Without A Net , ' with it is excellent versions of " Bird Song " Through Archive.org , I have now come to appreciate every era of the Dead , and I believe the Spring 1990 tour to be their most consistently stellar since ' 77 . and it is virtually guaranteed to be a winner . So Glad You Made It'--a compilation whittled down from the 18 - disc box set released last month -- is an excellent companion piece to the aforementioned ' Without A Net , ' featuring highlights from six of the best shows in March . We finally get an official release of the legendary Albany " Loser " from March 24th , and the Brent Mydland - sung " Blow Away " from March 16th in Landover , MD . Brent , without a doubt , had the best pure singing voice of anyone in the Dead at this point , and its a shame he died a few scant months after these shows . Even though he was their longest tenured keyboardist , I would love to have heard more from him , considering the band were in the middle of a live mini - renaissance beginning the year prior , which was unfortunately cut short by his untimely death . He is one of the most talented backing keyboardists of all - time , i am going to , even if it did take me a while to get used to the ( at times ) " carnival - ish " sound of his keys . that rival ' Without a Net 's . ' I know it is hard to top Branford Marsalis 's sax - laden version of " Eyes , " but I almost prefer this one , as Jerry 's precise noodling comes through more , along with the interweaving of the various instruments . Then again I could just be burnt out on the other due to a ridiculous amount of repeated listens . The " Jack - a - Roe " is one of the best electric versions I have heard , and Bob sounds positively possessed on one of the more exploratory latter - day " Estimated Prophet"s . Also included is one of the most powerful , heartfelt " Morning Dew"s of the era , which slowly builds and every verse until the song erupts into all - out bliss . The only negative for me is that the sound - quality is a little underwhelming -- with less clarity and less " oomph " in the bass compared with other releases -- though it is still loads better than any soundboard tape you can get from this tour . It is just weird to me that I have many 40 year - old , 2 - track live recordings of the Dead that sound crisper than these 22 year - old shows . and 90 's shows straight to cassette as opposed to reel to reel , which affected the sound - quality in some cases . I am not sure if but it is still just a minor complaint , as it is definitely better than most live albums by other bands from this era . So Glad You Made It ' is absolutely essential for Deadheads , and for fans of just - plain great music in general . You get the best of both worlds here -- from upbeat , head - bobbin ' numbers to deeper , more tripped - out jams -- and therefore it would serve as a great introduction to later - period Dead , if you are ( like I once was ) hesitant to explore this era . therefore it would serve as a great introduction to later - period Dead , if you are ( like I once was ) hesitant to explore this era . that , with the wealth of live material released year after year by this band , that there are still these amazing gems And I have a feeling but ... thank God for the Grateful " goshdarn " Dead .

summary: How Do You Prefer Your Jewel?
reviewText: Enough with the negative reviews on this cd . It is too different for the hardcore fans , etc . , etc . It is too much like Christina Aguilera and receive accolades instead of dismissals . that is a sign of talent , not selling out . Sure , Jewel is finely airbrushed on the cover , the titles are written like Prince tunes ( YOU & Me= Love , Run 2 YOU , Yes YOU Can ) , and the songs are polished to fine pop bliss . I , for one , find this cd to be one of Jewel 's finest . She forgoes all the pseudo - serious folk preaching and gets down to business with a cd filled with upbeat tracks instead of her serious ballads . However , she is still writing about serious topics such as social issues in " Stand " and " America " along with other familiar themes of love such as " Run 2 YOU " , " Fragile Heart " which probably flew over most Jewel fans ' heads . She even deals with lust on " Sweet Temptation " , " YOU & Me= Love " and " Yes YOU Can " . In fact , there are a number of hits on this disc : " Stand " , " Run 2 YOU " , " Intuition " , " Leave The Lights On " , " 2 Find YOU " , " Fragile Heart " , " Sweet Temptation " , " Yes YOU Can " , " America " & " Becoming " . The only True miss is the overlong " Haunted " , This new direction is great -- a breath of fresh air for Jewel . She sounds like she is having fun that spirit . Too many reviewers are taking this cd too seriously . This could be Jewel 's " Thriller " or " Hysteria " or " No Jacket Required " . If you are looking for intelligent pop ( and Spears are not ) , then pick this up ( also if you like the 80 's ) .

summary: Not very well known, but it should be
reviewText: Sleeze Beez were another in the long list of decent bands from the late 80's / early 90 's that never achieved the success they deserved . While they had everything needed to succeed , for whatever reason , they just never got there . " Insanity Beach " is Sleeze Beez 's third With the release of " Insanity Beach " , Sleeze Beez took a more harder rocking approach than with their previous releases . and in it is place is a more modern hard rock sound . Now do not get me wrong , this album still has that over - the - top catchiness that " Screwed , Blued & Tattoed " but the good far outweighed the bad . My favorite tracks from the album are " Tell It To The Judge " , " The Long Goodbye " , " Save Myself " , " Scream " and " Gun Culture " . The worst thing about this album is , it is almost non - existent for some reason . Thankfully Amazon.com has it for download for a reasonable price , otherwise most people would never get to hear this great record .

summary: A Christmas song by Lady GaGa?  It can't be...
reviewText: How funny is this , I downloaded this a few days before it was offered in the 25 Days Of Free thinking it seemed very odd for Lady GaGa to be doing " O Christmas Tree " Then I got so wrapped up in protesting the listing of " Slower Than Christmas " Surprise surprise , it is not " O Christmas Tree " after all , Setting the gross inappropriateness of this song aside for a moment , this is a weak song musically . If I am not mistaken , there are two lines in the entire song , maybe three . It makes a strange shift in the middle to Space Cowboy rapping the same line , then shifts back to GaGa , The backing music is a choppy , repetitive bed of electronic harmony which has nothing exciting to offer . Coming from a former burlesque dancer , this seems no surprise . That Amazon wants to advertise it as part of the 25 Days Of Free would be surprising if it were not a part of a disturbing trend this year . Amazon is trying very hard to push the " edgy " envelope I think it would be more understandable if the edgy songs in question were particularly good , This song brought to mind a song they sometimes play on Bob that song is FUNNY , this is not . This song is blatantly irresponsible in that bracket I have no issue with , Singing this kind of innuendo to middle schoolers is just plain wrong . With the setup of getting this song off a Christmas recommendation list and an innocuous title that can easily be mistaken for an age old Christmas carol , I am sure this will lead to many kids getting their hands on this right under their parents ' unsuspecting noses . AMAZON PLEASE PAY CLOSE ATTENTION ! ! ! YOU ARE GOING TO START LOSING CUSTOMERS IF YOU DO NOT SHAPE UP YOUR ACT HERE ! One slip - up in the 25 day cycle could be forgiven , and people are getting offended . 25 Days Of Free is looked at as a platform for holiday friendly , family friendly music . A nice way to get some songs to add to the playlist Stop wasting slots on songs Stop trying to pitch to the 5 to 10 people who like raunchy instead of the 100 's that do not want it !

Ride The Lightning is one of the best albums of the thrash / speed metal genre and along with their next album Master of Puppets is Metallica 's best work . While their first album Kill Them All relied more on speed metal , Ride The Lightning showed the band expanding their musical horizons and their songwriting abilities , which would lead to their breakthrough in America . Every track here is very strong with many of them becoming metal classics . The band wrote some of their best lyrics here as many of the tracks deal with personal issues such as drugs , death , and the struggle within . There is much diversity to be found here whether it is the excellent speed metal of " Fight Fire With Fire " and " Trapped Under Ice " and the awesome " Creeping Death . " The menacing " For Whom The Bell Tolls " and " Escape " are also very strong tracks . Then there is " Fade To Black " , the best track the band has ever recorded , and is to heavy metal what " Stairway To Heaven " is to classic rock . This is simply an incredible song , between its several different movements which tell of a man contemplating suicide . The guitar solo from Kirk Hammett during the song 's outro is one of the best ever of the genre . Simply one of the best albums ever recorded in heavy metal . Highly recommended .

summary: Review excerpt from Music and Media Focus
reviewText: Being a new age music journalist for over 30 years as well as a music producer myself who has worked on a number of guided meditation recordings , I can say that , in my experience , Meditations2Go are some of the best I have heard . The series is the work of Rob Brookler , who has been a meditation teacher in the Los Angeles area for 28 years Having worked with many groups and has created a practical approach to not only focusing the mind , but on gaining insight into many of the issues In addition to the audio meditations , his website also offers a wealth of well - written articles that offer guidance for a variety of personal challenges and embody many of the principles found within , they can be quite helpful in their own right , that they are available to read free of charge speaks to the positive intention and goodwill of Rob that impressed me the most about Meditations2Go is how well produced A standout feature for me is Rob 's voice . and timbre , as well as his pacing and cadence are about as perfect as you could want for something of this nature . He also has a wonderful ear for the kind of music that is best suited for each topic , and will even spend time in the studio with the soundtrack producer during the recording process to help tailor it for the particular meditation . Needless to say , I am very impressed with Meditations2Go and am greatly enjoying and benefiting from integrating their soothing ambience and insightful narratives into my life .

where the country group has achieved the most success . The album 's first single " Pontoon " reached # 1 on the country charts . The second single , " Tornado " , had entered the top 10 . " Pontoon " is a catchy little song about having fun of a boat , complete with a double - entendre ( " Mmmm , motorboatin ' ! ) . There is not a weak track on the entire album . The lyrics throughout the album are strong . That is especially True for " Tornado " ( the title track ) . Like a few other tracks , it is about forlorn love . There are a lot of classic rock , soul , For instance , " Leavin ' In Your Eyes " sounds like something Fleetwood Mac could have done in the late 70s . " Front Porch Thing " has some gospel harmonies at the beginning . The members of Little Big Town often harmonize their voice together , something uncommon in new country music . Every member of the band is a strong vocalist , and they harmonize very well . On " Can not Go Back " , the entire track is harmonizing . " Sober " is an excellent country pop ballad that highlights the lead vocalist 's talents . I could see Taylor Swift performing it . I would recommend this album not only to country fans , but also fans of soulful rock .

summary: Nice reissue of Cale's album--no bonus tracks, no liner notes but strong material with a solid band.
reviewText: that John Cale has for Honi Soit a blistering set of rock tunes played by a killer band . and sensibility , it remains a classic slice of Cale with blistering lyrics or shrill depending on what emotion he is trying to convey . Mind you , shrill for Cale can be a good thing -- it matches the music here in many cases . and remastered ) edition of Honi Soit has a much stronger bass than the original CD -- it is not bloated at least to my ears and attack to the music . The original German pressing has a lighter touch to be sure . The comparison for me is a cool side walk perfectly uniform and fairly smooth while this reminds me more of a recently paved road on a hot day -- you can feel the gravel under your feed but it is not unpleasant . This reissue ( an import from Holland ) does not have any extensive liner notes discussing the making of the album just features credits ( no re - mastering credit though ) for the musicians with photos on a two page spread who played what instrument . that Cale probably is not completely happy with Pretending they do not exist does not mean they do not and should be available on CD This remains a worthy reissue and essential album for Cale fans . Even lesser gems and allow fans to appreciate Cale as imperfect art can sometimes be more interesting than a perfect masterpiece . Cale has always been a challenging and innovative musician . I would love to see him work with Brian Eno once again as they struck gold in the past with their collaboration on " Wrong Way Up " .

that Grunge was well and truly selling billions of CDs worldwide , US Heavy Metal legends Manowar released their seventh full - length studio album   1992s The Triumph Of Steel . It must have been no easy task following up their immensely popular and loyally beloved 1988 release Kings Of Metal , nor must it have been easy having to train up a new drummer and guitarist after losing Scott Columbus In fact , nor can it have been fun trying to promote an album of blistering , powerful , OTT Heavy Metal after Man In The Box and Smells Like Teen Spirit changed what must have felt like every journalist on earths priorities in the pre - internet culture of the day . that was going against them , Manowar released what must surely be one of their greatest ever albums ( certainly its my personal favourite at any rate ) . or call it arrogance , A song with a bass solo , a drum solo so indulgent and for the drums , two minutes of somber guitar violining all telling the story of Achillies The world wanted Touch Me I Am Sick Manowar gave them Achilles , Agony and Ecstasy in Eight Parts . Despite how easy it is to skip a twenty - minute album opener with three solos in it , the song is not poor . In fact , some sections of it are absolute genius , such as the furious Thrashy Death Hectors Reward part , which feels like the musical equivalent of being battered upside the head . Metal Warriors is the most perfectly - pitched , sing - along tribute to Heavy Metal Ludicrous to the point of featuring the lyric If you are not into Metal you are not my friend Its some kind of supercharged version of Kiss I Love It Loud filled with Painkiller screams , mountain - top chants and the screech of guitars There Is more blistering speed , in the sword - and incredibly catchy chorus . The band then take a different tack , choosing to sing about Native Americans in a surprisingly tasteful way , in an interesting mid - paced affair but does not loose Maybe they were jealous of Anthrax ? Who cares but it works , really well ! Then they follow it up with another mid - paced track called Burning which you would imagine might be a momentum killer , but is actually one of the more interesting compositions in the bands catalogue . or blistering speed . Its a nice change of pace . Sort of experimental , with a lot of emphasis on dynamics If you wonder if the band are for you , this is one of the tracks you should use to decide . that is great about the band in spades . Its so powerful , OTT and fun . Its beyond catchy , the solo is awesome , there is slow bits , fast bits that the band aspire to . With this one song , you get a good musical , technical and lyrical picture of Manowar oh , and by the way its a great song too ! Even if the last one felt good enough to be an album closer , it does not stop there . A robust , interesting track which is half crushing Sabbath - inspired Doom and half double - kick Thrash attack , almost - ending the album with a jarring reverse - whiplash effect as the too - slow doom accelerates out of control to the tune off way - too - loud whip samples . It all closes with the grand , cinematic , vocally - impressive Master Of The Wind which kind of evokes Greg Lake - era King Crimson with its chiming bells , big reverb , dynamic production and haunting singing . Its probably the best ballad / orchestral - track but a genuine album highlight in itself . Overall ; Triumph Of Steel is a really diverse and almost strange album . Despite its seeming lack of focus , it really feels like Manowar just doing everything they could think of to absolute perfection . Fast bits   nailed . Slow bits   nailed . Keeping True to what makes Manowar , Manowar   nailed . but for my money this album is a straight up - and - down masterpiece that shows what superb musicians , performers Highly Recommended !

summary: A Brahms First to carry you through a lifetime
reviewText: when they call Bruno Walter the most eminent interpreter of Brahms in the twentieth century , but here is a conductor , still capable of making this powerful Brahms First in 1959 , when the composer died . He learned his Brahms fro no less than Hans von Bulow and was too ill to travel ( Walter 's mentor Gustav Mahler made the journey to Sichl , and found the old man melancholy yet from a modern perspective , Brahms was hardly elderly at 64 ) . There is no need for me to heap my praise on so many others ' . I only want to recount my surprise , after an absence of ten years and finding it   so dynamic and alert . Waning energies were attributed to Walter 's troubles with heart disease , and it has some rough edges , too . that might be the influence of Toscanini ; there was enormous pressure in America for every conductor to ape Toscanini or fall under his shadow . but with a core of relaxed enjoyment in music - making . He is just a master of the traditional Romantic style that nurtured him in the nineteenth century .   without being personal , he is authentic . The orchestra can be criticized for imbalances due to an under - powered string body , Walter is also more modest and lyrical than either Furtwangler It has Walter 's famous singing quality and strength of purpose , too . and Academic Festival Over . and authority . For once , the overture actually feels festive with the extra snap Walter gives it .

Wow ! That was my first impression after taking a listen to this album but is just catching on after Sturgill was nominated for two Grammy Awards ( including Album of the Year ) . He won one Grammy for Best Country Album . and this album is HOT ! HOT ! HOT ! and in my mind should have won Album of the Year but of course Adele " 25 " won , which itself is an excellent album - but " A Sailor 's Guide To Earth " is far more diverse , versatile and overall a much stronger album than " 25 . " 

 Sturgill Simpson shows bits of David Gray , Alex Clare , Van Morrison He writes songs with the wisdom of a sailor who has sailed the seas of life for twice the amount of decades of his actual age . and rock music charts as well as # 1 on the folk music charts . It has also reached # 3 on billboard 's Top 200 albums chart . Though categorized as a country music album it is far more versatile than simply a country album . This is quite simply one of the most intriguing albums of the past 20 years . This album is full of introspection , joy and great guitar and Sturgill wrote all the songs to boot ( except the cover of Nirvana 's " In Bloom " ) . and the beautiful tinkling of keyboards . " Welcome To Earth " sounds like a refreshing ocean morning relaxing in the mist of the ocean air . Three minutes in the song turns into a surprising upbeat Motown flavored experience with horns As a matter of fact The Dap - Kings ( famous for playing behind Sharon Jones ) are the credited horn section on this song The otherworldly " Breakers Roar " is soothingly beautiful accented with country tinged steel guitars bringing out an ethereal sound This song screams David Gray and beauty . that breaks out with a high - stepping brass section very reminiscent of 1979 era Ronnie Milsap . The song features some hot licking slide guitar and awesome electric guitar . " In Bloom " is the only song not written by Sturgill Simpson . " In Bloom " was written by Kurt Cobain and made it all his own with an intense delicate power working into a storm of emotion Brace For Impact ( Live A Little ) " is my favorite song from the album for many reasons . I love the David Gilmour style guitar chords and the music video is eerie and amazing . and intensity like no other singer of this decade . that sounds like it could have been written for a Pink Floyd album all the while maintaining it is country music influence . " Brace For Impact " is a song about death Sturgill 's dark guitars that should not be missed . " All Around You " is a great 1950s blues style country song while " Oh Sarah " is that country song filled with hurt , pain and joy . The album closes with one of it is strongest songs . The bag pipes add this unusual sort of ocean sound to the song - it works quite well . Quickly the song turns funky with R&B honky tonk horns that makes the song feel like something you might have heard in the explosive 1980 film " The Blues Brothers . " Let me tell you the guitar work in this song is absolutely killer . I am a huge fan of the guitar and Sturgill ranks right up there with the best of the best . that has surprises around each corner . and best of all Sturgill Simpson is a really great singer . I highly recommend this album to anyone that is an avid fan of diversity in music .

The 80 's was the decade of great Christian music . Stryper led the way Barren Cross , Bloodgood , Holy Soldier , and gave musical hope for a multitude of young people who grew tired of what passed for " music " in What made this band special was their no - nonsense lyrics that confronted listeners with the biblical gospel . They were never afraid of confronting sin and speaking plainly about the problem of evil . SW eventually broke up Almost thirty years later , Sacred Warrior has returned with a new lead singer and a fresh , updated sound . Their new album , Waiting in Darkness has all of the features described above . The only difference is this : The music is faster It should come as no surprise Each song on the album is a testimony to the gospel of grace . Track by Track : 

 The album begins by addressing the problem of evil and the reality of redemption : 

 Desperately wicked we are born Corrupted seeds This stronghold grips humanity The curse of sin 

 Flesh and spirit raging on the war within or death cursed or blessed the choice is given In the perfect sacrifice a hope remains Redemption by shedding of blood love overcame 

 The title track , Waiting in Darkness is a heavy metal exposition of spiritual warfare : 

 Through your anger they fuel the fire 
  Feeding off of your flesh 's sinful desires Lies and confusion your faith put to the test Focusing in on all of your weaknesses We must be vigilant to thwart their evil plight Be strong in the lord Be prepared for war 

 In Dust and Ashes is a Job - like lament written in the first person that is sure to grip the attention of anyone who is enduring a dark night of the soul : Oh lord hear my cry I am a man with many troubles In the regions dark This world lies heavy on me 

 Your steadfast love remains Even though I feel abandoned Break the chains of doubt and sorrow 

 Skin for skin all Will bless your name in you remain 

 In dust Resolved to make you my content In dust and ashes I confess My love for you within this test 

 Fear Me is a bold declaration of the sovereignty of God . sovereign over all   Wisdom begins All authority is mine and I will put an end to evil 's reign For vengeance is mine says the lord 

 Fear me like you would fear a raging fire Respect keeps you from the pain Or the raging of the ocean and sink to your grave Fear me 

 To deny Suppress the truth for a lie professing to be wise The wrath I hold will be revealed This world I will destroy who reject my name 

 Fans of A.W. Pink will immediately wonder if the guys in Sacred Warrior have been meditating on the classic , The Sovereignty of God ! Long Live the King continues to confront the listener with the sovereignty of God over all things . and his love will never die Lift up your voice unto the sky shout the battle cry 

 Long live the king , Long live the king 

 Jealous Love is a ballad that glories in the Cross of Christ . and is rerecorded from their first studio album , Rebellion . This is the kind of music Fans of Sacred Warrior will only be encouraged by their latest record . The music is tight , sounds current , best of all - exalts the Lord Jesus Christ !

summary: Thanks for gettin' yourself back on track, Brian. YOUR REAL FANS AND FOLLOWERS APPRECIATE IT FOR ONCE!!!
reviewText: Sounds like Brian 's finally snapping out of that 20 - year commercial " haze " which very nearly swallowed whatever remained of his credibility as a legit multi - talented recording artist . ' Better ' ( going by the audio samples here ) feels like the kind of album that particular album focused primarily on the piano - heavy ballads , ' Better ' effectively showcases a more energetic , uptempo side of Brian that he struggled to master a bit earlier on in his career . The production also stands out as well ( best since 2005 's solid yet largely uneven ' Gemini ' ) , with polished LIVE musicianship and arrangements galore . but it really did not deter from the overall flow of the album that Brian definitely has learned his lesson in terms of not letting " trendy " guest artists ( rappers ESPECIALLY ) overtake his studio projects . I do like his reggae - inspired collaboration with native Hawaiian singer Kimie Miner , but it was a most welcome surprise indeed ! Hopefully , this newfound sense of musical versatility will continue for Brian as he takes on further projects in the not - too - distant future . From my honest perspective , the man certainly needs to make up for lost time after giving much of his core fanbase three decades worth of watered - down compromises that served him well financially

summary: A diverse collection of powerful songs from a great band
reviewText: Like many , I was introduced to Imagine Dragons by their hit " Radioactive , " which proved popular enough and parodied by " Weird Al " Yankovic . At first I thought it would be a case of " I just like one song by this group , " but when I listened to their song " Warriors , " I knew I would like this band . when I listened to their song " Warriors , " I knew I would like this band . I am normally not a fan of modern rock , but Imagine Dragons is quickly proving to be the exception , and their album " Night Visions " has really grown on me . and " On Top of the World " would have to be my favorite songs . but strangely hopeful despite the dystopian , post - apocalyptic theme of it . " On Top of the World " is quite different , a livelier and upbeat number but still powerful emotions every time I listen to them . Other favorites on this album include the pop - flavored " Tip Toe , " the powerful " Demons , " and the more subdued but still thoughtful and pleasant " Amsterdam . " Other songs , such as " Underdog " and " Bleeding Out , " are not necessarily bad , they just were not my favorites of the album . Still , overall this album has far more hits than misses for me . Imagine Dragons has a powerful sound to it that can be raw , melancholy , upbeat , or mellow as they see fit , and they have certainly proven to be a great band with this album . If you like bands such as Linkin Park or Dashboard Confessional , you will probably enjoy " Night Visions . "

summary: PETTY PROVES HE BELIEVES IN ROCK AND ROLL
reviewText: and who played on the individual tracks . who played on the individual tracks . There is an introduction written by Petty about the making of this box set . The sound ( newly mixed),from various venues across 30 years , is uniformly good . The retro style packaging is perfectly in keeping with Petty 's approach to music - when a well made and assembled vinyl album   made a True r&are   statement for an entire ( including Petty ) generation of listeners . and age of over - priced " deluxe " releases / re - releases , even of admittedly great r&r , this collection stands apart . Not only are all the tracks heard here chosen by Petty , guitarist Mike Campbell , and their producer , the tracks cover 30 years of TOM PETTY AND THE HEARTBREAKERS in concert . Great music , nice packaging , and a low price make this worth owning . Petty and his band are one of the few groups still playing music that   matters . and you will have all the proof you need , no matter if the song is well known , that is what gives their music backbone . On these tracks the band effortlessly switches across musical styles , from originals to covers , all with that sound they have played from the beginning . Long time listeners of the band will need little proof of the great music here . and want a lot of their greatest songs ( " Breakdown","Refugee","American Girl",etc.),along with some great covers ( THUNDERCLAP NEWMAN 's " Something In The Air",BOOKER T. Arguably some listeners will wish a certain song was included ( personally I would like to hear more Dylan / BYRDS covers),but overall , this is an outstanding overview from one of the few long time bands that still matters . that is important , but more importantly , exciting and that guarantees a good time , this is the set to get . that guarantees a good time , this is the set to get . Still , listening to this great music makes you wonder - what more great music is still left on the reels ? But this collection goes a long way in satisfying that craving ( like mine ) for a generous overview of TOM PETTY AND THE HEARTBREAKERS doing what they do best - performing great r&r in front of an audience . that inimitable sound the band has built on all these years , you get the feeling and redemption of basic r&r . This set is even better than the 2 CD set released by Immortal , taken from a concert in 2003,in Chicago . Do your head a favor and purchase this wonderful collection soon . and purchase this wonderful collection soon .

summary: Kid Rock improves from the last album, but only just.
reviewText: I hated to rate Kid Rock 's last album " Born Free " so low , that would be a classic , it may have gone to # 1 in the US and done fairly well around the world , but that was fans anticipation that was fans anticipation that Kid 's latest album would be great , but the proof is seen in how many songs you remember now , how many have radio play , how many clips I am glad Kid Rock abandoned using Rick Ruban 's help to produce this album , as it does sound a bit more like Kid Rock now . However , I was excited to not only hear but that Kid wanted this album to be something more like " Cocky " that Kid wanted this album to be something more like " Cocky " which to me is one of his best albums yet where I enjoy listening to where I enjoy listening to But what has been the outcome here on " Rebel Soul " has been rather disappointing for me . The opening song " Chickens In The Pen " is not a strong opener , nor is it a great song . but like on " Born Free " the first track here made my heart sink that this album was not going to put Kid back on top of his game . The lyrics are too weird for me to even understand what Kid was going for on this track . I just expect better from Kid Rock . The song is just too stupid to be good if you ask me . Let Us Ride - it sounds like Kid has taken a real liking to the 60 's and 70 's sound of Rock N roll bands like ' The It is certainly not a bad thing at all , however the song comes off sounding pretty average for it is genre . Catt Boogie - About the same as " Let Us Ride " , its decent , that memorable . Detroit Michigan - OK , KID . BUT PLEASE , PLEASE , PLEASE stop singing about it . The lyrics sound good , the melody is pretty good , up until the chorus , it just does not sit right in the song . that could have been good , but he does a better job with this type of thing later on the album . Rebel Soul - I expected a title like this to be southern rock , Kid 's done some great country songs , but this song here to me is not worthy of naming the whole album after . Definitely a filler sounding track . God Save Rock N Roll - What is Kid thinking these days ? First Rebel Soul is not southern rock , Happy New Year - It is pretty simple lyrics , and i am convinced Kid can do much better then this . I was surprised to see this song was leading the votes of favorite song from this album on Kid 's website ... Celebrate - Not a bad song , but like track 2 and 3 , it is easy to forget , but amongst the rest of this album , it is one of the better ones on here . The Mirror - I absolutely hate auto - tuners . and ruined what could have been a decent slow song had he not used those annoying stupid auto - tuners that should be banned from anyone being able to record with . that effect ever again , it sounds horrible . Mr Rock N Roll - I was losing faith and brightened my day . It is my favorite track on this album , and easy to get into The lyrics are great , has a lot of familiar names of classic songs in it , and is worthy of Kid adding this track to his live shows . Cucci Galore - At first I thought , WTF is this $ # ! % ? lyrics spewing out of " My names Cucci , Cucci , Cucci galore " Then a screaming rock chorus of " Do you want to go down " ... the song makes little sense to me other than it is a typical Kid Rock bragging about having money , fame , women and hot tubs etc ... but as weird as the lyrics are , and a WTF imprint it left after the first listen ... for some reason , it is not a bad track , as much as it makes little sense , it is catchy .. that has any boom bass in it , where as most of the other songs on here are classic rock Weirdly , this track grew on me ! Redneck Paradise - Euhhh , seems like Kid has done this song before . I would rather better red neck songs about drinking or " Born To Be a Hick " over this feel good attempt at a trailer park sing - along filler . when they rock , this one is just a filler for boredom . Midnight Ferry - I was so sick of hearing halleluiah preachy songs by this point Not a good way to close the album . Kid has said he wants this song played at his funeral , I would take " Only God Knows Just to be clear , no , I am not a rap or hip hop fan , so with those sounds being absent here have not left me bitter , but I do miss the heavier sound of songs like " So Hott " , " American Baddass " I do miss The Twisted Brown Trucker Band ... plus , what I would have loved to hear was songs like on " Cocky " that started off slow , then rocked your @$$ off by the end . Hopefully Kid Rock will return to But even so , the songs on here , there are a few decent tracks , or two worthy of being included during live shows , but only barely worthy of being called a hit song ... not something I would be disappointed by if they did not appear on a greatest hits album in future ... but compared to Kid 's best stuff , really only Mr Rock N Roll would be worthy of standing next to them ... but again , not hard to understand if it was passed by as a greatest hits selection .

summary: WIth shoes like that you'll be single for a long time
reviewText: " A Single Man " by Elton John is a hard one to evaluate . On the one hand , the songs are mostly good ones ; and the production is super sweet ! Very soft But Elton 's vocals are mostly dis - engaged and generally charmless . " Return to Paradise " might just be ; what with those beautiful Falsetto vocals , " Georgia " might   be an under - rated one of those Southern Anthems But , for me , the real nuggets are the final three songs " Madness " , " Reverie " which all sit well together , kind of a trio of darkness , really ; " Madness " is a spine chilling disco - prog - rocker with lots of haunting piano chords ; " Reverie " is brief but effective , and " Song for Guy " is suitably melancholy The vocal part is particularly evocative . The other songs are not bad . " I do not care " is a fun rocker in the style of his earlier ones , but the vocals do not relay the fun . " Part - time love " is the best of the rest , a pumpy little tune with a big production . Not a bad album , Rating * * 1/4

summary: Mining the depths of "experience Hendrix" with only a few nuggets to show...but good for a short live album.
reviewText: This is a review of " Miami pop festival " the Jimi Hendrix experience . I liberated a copy of this CD from a local big box store tonight , before it is True release . There is some interesting banter which showcases just how novel these large festivals were in the late 60s . This particular festival was set in May of 1968 and promoted by Michael Lang , of pre - Woodstock fame . The first track is a funny little whimsical 60s back Track two opens with a cool jam intro with punching kick drums from Mitch Mitchell and phased out feedback laden guitar from Jimi- just before launching into a nicely rearranged introduction of " hey Joe . " One nice aspect is The next song " Tax - free " is a nice jam with some heavy crybaby floating throughout . Noel Redding 's bass guitar is right up there in the mix in the correct place , sonically speaking . Mitch has a cool tempo altering drum solo that really starts swinging as Jimmy comes back in with some blistering wah - wah guitar . and off mic banter is amusing and entertaining , as it shows just how novel and inexperienced the promoters and the sound technicians were at setting up these kinds of shows in the early , nascent   stages of festival going . I will avoid the common bashing of Janie Hendrix that so many complain about . There is very limited material that Mr. Hendrix produced while he was alive . We are scraping the bottom of the barrel , of course , ending up with products like " Valleys of Neptune " which was decent and acceptable and overall a good listen . that said , this is a decent product . In fact it is rather good for a live recording . The only problem is the lack of material . that two songs are repeated is troubling . that show Jimmy with his Olympic white Fender Strat are very nice and well done . The packaging is actually quite nice as well . So for $ 10 , this is a marginal three - star buy . Put some other records ahead of it in your musical shopping list , like Paul McCartney 's new album or even some of those dreaded repackagings of prior releases that I loathe . The only one I would say to avoid at all costs is The Band at the Academy of Arts ( aka " Rock of Aged " ) . That one is a great example of a lame cash grab . Sad for such an amazing group . I Have heard NOTHING good about it ! PS - I would listen to this a million times before ever suffering through friggin ' ARCADE FIRE and their Ambien - rock - electronic crap that Rolling Stone seems to love so much .

summary: NOT the genre-defining masterpiece it's made out to be...
reviewText: but it is still excellent throughout , though just SLIGHTLY overrated . How could a four - star disc be overrated , you ask ? Well , I do not hear the voice of God in every track . but a couple in the end kind of bored me - On a Plain sounded much better Unplugged , and there is just no saving tripe like Territorial Pissings , Lounge Act Now , let us get to the GOOD stuff ! Yeah , there is plenty of For starters is the deserved smash Smells Like Teen Spirit - heavy yet melodic , hard - rocking yet vunerable , with one of the best guitar riffs of the ' 90 's , yadda yadda yadda . All the praise you have heard about it is True . Even better is Lithium , disturbing yet unforgettable lyrics and a stick - in - your - mind , Dazed and Confused - esque descending bassline . Which is one reason I love Nirvana - Cobain 's melodies were exquisite . Come As You Are is higlighted by a downright unforgettable ringing riff , In Bloom by a strong drum track Polly deals with rape in a disturbingly stark way , drawing you in while scaring you off . and Drain You are some pretty raw , rockin ' stuff , the kind of song the group did best . that insane hidden track , Endless Nameless or whatever ... whoa . Pure craziness . Not the best record of the ' 90 's ( Dirt ) , or even the best Nirvana album ( In Utero ) . I say screw all the angsty alt - rockers Kurt really was an alienated guy ( he did not WANT to be famous , for the love of Buddha ! ) , and was communicating genuine emotions . As opposed to all these other morons , who whine about being " misunderstood " simply to make money . and Pearl Jam , and the rest of them ) came just in time , justly knocking those stupid hair - metal bands off the charts and replacing them with a new golden age for rock rivaling the creatively fertile 1965 - 1975 period . It is a shame that , after this , crap groups like Green Day ( who were essentially riding Nirvana 's coattails ) , Oasis , MCR and Slipknot became popular ...
The band can still churn out some great songs like this . This might be my favorite .

summary: Almost immediately, something feels off about Better Nature. A misguided effort from one of my favorite bands.
reviewText: This was a hard one to write . As as huge fan of the Silversun Pickups , I have seen them in concert twice and have loved much of their body of work . They are a band that manages to create music that manages to create music that is both beautiful and heavy at the same time , with each of their albums featuring no shortage of standout moments and True emotion . Better Nature , though , sees the Pickups choosing to hide their musical talents behind a wall of synth , releasing an album that is more electronic than instrumental , that as a result lacks much of what makes this band so great . From the start , something does not feel right . The opening track Cradle sounds like it was intended to be a heavy one , from the vocals to the structure , and speed , leading to a track And as I listened to Better Nature for the first time , I felt my mind wandering that the problem was the lack of guitar ... or really , any instrument , throughout ; Better Nature sees electronics You can hear electronic noise Much of Better Nature sounds like the soundtrack to a video game , and not a bad one , necessarily , It is tough for me to get into synth . that in the 80s it was big , ( Latchkey Kids sounds almost like a throwback to but my problem with seeing rock groups attempting to do this today ( Linkin Park tried a similar style with Living Things , and Broken Bells with After the Disco ) is that electronics , no matter how cool they can sound in their own genre , just can not achieve the dynamic feel to me of real instruments . when listening to Better Nature , moments that were meant to be beautiful and emotional , moments that can be catchy , that anything on Better Nature even comes close to matching the best work on their previous records . that is good . The two best songs on the CD ( Nightlight and Circadian Rhythm ) are strong tracks , though sadly , being the two singles , I would already heard them before the album came out . that it is almost hard to believe . And even they do not get by unscathed , as the album version of Nightlight loses entirely the very cool and ominous buildup featured in the music video version of the song , something that makes this version decidedly inferior . and Cradle , would I am sure sound incredible with real instrumentation . Still , even as presented here , these are good songs , and catchy , to varying degrees , but it does not sound like Silversun Pickups . and Nikki Monninger give incredible vocal performances throughout ) but musically it sounds like someone doing electronic covers of Pickups songs , something that no matter how hard I try , I just can not get past . Better Nature was a bummer for me . that I feared Neck of the Woods would be Neck of the Woods , though , while it featured an increased use of electronics , was still definitely a Pickups album . Better Nature , though , just comes across as a synth album with Brian singing . Going by interviews the band has given , they seem very happy with the final product , and while I am happy for them , I really hope They are such a great band ,

summary: A Terrific, Definitive Early Dose of Jackson Browne's Music!
reviewText: This is an album for ` everyman " , the definitive statement by Jackson Browne of his disturbing and apocalyptic view of contemporary society , and his hopes and fears for its future . It is also a lovely , stirring , and   evocative song cycle and   instrumental arrangements , and sends one running for the door to buy more   of the albums of the early " JB " variety . My personal favorites on this   wonderful album are " Our Lady of the Well " , a interesting and political concerns blended with a   celebration of the common rural peasantry of Latin America , " Take It Easy "   written with Glenn Frye of the Eagles and the   Eagles , " These Times You have Come " about an old pair of lovers who still see   each other romantically after parting , which like " The Deluge " on   another album , sets out Browne 's fear of a pending eco - disaster and   apocalypse . Browne is still around , still creative , but this is one of his best early albums , when   he was one of the most talented and creative young folk - rock luminaries on   the popular scene , a superstar a long time in the making . This is a   ` must - have ' album for any real fan of Browne 's music and for anyone just   interested in top - shelf folk - rock music by one of the seventies and   eighties greatest popular artists .

reviewText: Unlike some high profile R&B artist , I will never get tired of buying a Musiq album . It is perfect that he has decided to drop another album to kick off the summer . It may seem like boring news , In are producers like August Rigo , The Element & Jesse Wilson . The problem with working with new producers is it takes time to gel . " Lovecontract " has a weird Rapheal Saadiq sound . The lead single " Anything " gets the party started . This album is less on the slow jams ( There are none ) " Waitingstill " is the closest to a slow song . The Jesse Wilson produced , " Donthaveto " is the gem of this album . It starts a trio of no skip songs including the beautifully written " Bestfriend " and " Yes " . Musiq has always has always been able to find a good medium between slow grooves The lack of slow jams makes this album not as good as his last two . As a long time Musiq fan , I enjoyed this album . A couple of his classic slow songs would have been nice . But overall I am not disappointed . I think there is no doubt that Musiq has been the most consistent male R&B artist over the past 10 years .

summary: From Illinois She Came: Margo Price With One Of The Best Albums Of 2016
reviewText: but brewing just underneath the surface of Nashvilles obsession with the tailgates , trucks , dirt roads , hot chicks , and its various offshoots ) , there has been a slow but sure resurfacing of country music rooted in both traditional and progressive values . Guys like Chris Stapleton , Jason Isbell , or less leading this charge , Enter Illinois native Margo Price with her album MIDWEST FARMERS DAUGHTER , one of the great albums of any genre by anybody in the year 2016 . Much like Canadian gal Lindi Ortega had done in 2015 with FADED GLORYVILLE , Margo has done with this album , by mixing in a variety of styles , rooted in classic 1960s/1970s country , of the Bakersfield honky - tonk variety , but including a fair amount of Memphis / Muscle Shoals R&B and old - school country - rock of the Linda Ronstadt / Emmylou Harris variety as well . Margo has had a fairly rough life up to this point ( even seeing the wrong side of a jail cell ) , one that screams the story of a great C&W song , but being the survivor she is , of both jail and heartbreaks galore , she brings that to vivid life . where Elvis made his groundbreaking recordings that would help set the tone for American popular music in the second half of the 20th century , and this more than explains the musical mixings she engages in . Songs like About To Find Out and Since You Put Me Down are classic - sounding honky - tonk material in a modern context . Meanwhile , Weekender is a perfectly dissolute song about her time in jail , while Hurtin ( On The Bottle ) , a co - write of Margos with the aforementioned Caitlin Rose , is another honky - tonk C&W masterpiece . Other songs like Four Years Of Chances have a Southern R&B feel to them . While there are no F - bombs dropped , there is a little bit of language in some of the songs lyrics and pedal steel guitar , a hallmark of classic 1960s and 1970s L.A. country - rock , must by now sound alien to people blinded by the processed junk of Jason Aldean , Luke Bryan , Still , all in all , thanks to Margos authenticity It is essential listening , whether you are a fan of traditional country , a fan of progressive country ,

It shows the band is not willing to just settle and is willing to take risks still . Upon first listen this release will be a bit jarring for some , but I strongly urge those fans to give it many listens before passing final judgement .

Then , unlike the first track , the composers do not go completely silent , that break , the music comes back with a heroic feeling of determination , like an army fighting against powerful odds . I love piano music , and to me , it is like a violin , bringing out feelings of love and tenderness . Track 3 starts out with just the piano playing a theme that denotes sadness , like someone may have just died , After this , a female voice begins the lament ; powerful drums with a driving beat then pick up the pace . Then , the musical journey begins over mountains , fording rivers , through dark valleys to reach the end of their quest for peace and some kind of meaning out of the sorrows of life . Each tack is wonderful to listen to , and it transports you wherever you let your imagination go .   Enjoy !

summary: Melancholy but thoughtful and lovely number
reviewText: With a title like " Fast Car , " one would probably expect an upbeat , blood - pounding song in the vein of " Shut Up One certainly would not expect a poignant , even melancholy ballad about escaping the drudgery of life ... only to find oneself back when I stopped and listened to the lyrics I was shocked at just how sad this song was ... and yet was captivated by the unflinching portrait Tracy Chapman had painted of a young woman seeking the trap of her old life yet was captivated by the unflinching portrait Tracy Chapman had painted of a young woman seeking the trap of her old life It is not a happy song ... yet Tracy Chapman sings it so beautifully . or melodramatic , conveying just the right amount of emotion to fit the theme of the song . And the simple instrumentation keeps the song appropriately low - key . Sometimes a beautiful song is spoiled by being overproduced and it was nice to see the singer that temptation here . While a melancholy song , " Fast Car " is still lovely to listen to , and certainly more thoughtful than the endless parade of love songs that make up popular music nowadays . If you like James Taylor , you might also enjoy " Fast Car . "

This is one of my favorite trip hop albums . The first four tracks are just amazing , The songs respectively are   " Angel , " " Risingson , " " Teardrop , " and " Inertia Creeps " . " Angel " has a stark production featuring pointed beats and a distorted bassline and a two - minute flame - out with raging guitars . " Risingson " is a dense , dark sounding song with a ton of dub throughout . " Teardrop " is an awesome song " Inertia Creeps " is a highlight with an atmospheric sound , fuzz - tone guitars , and a wealth of effects , the song could well be the best production from the best team of producers the electronic world had ever seen . These songs are definately the highlight , and the other songs are still good , just not as good as these four in my opinion . Overall an awesome album

summary: Good for the Manfred, the Orchestral Suites and the Piano Trio.........but not much else.
reviewText: This is a decent mp3 set of various works by Tchaikovsky , heavy on works for orchestra . The best parts here are the less frequently heard works , such as the Orchestral Suites 2 & 4 , the Piano Trio in A minor , The Seasons , the Danish Festival Overture The version of the Manfred Symphony is really good , and it has been for a long time one of my favorite lesser known Tchaikovsky works . However , on the down side , the more familiar pieces in this set just do not seem to be very good performances . The numbered symphonies all sound bland and lifeless.(BY THE WAY - and lifeless.(BY THE WAY - where is the Symphony No . 3 , the Polish ? and leave out one of the earlier ones . ) and violin concertos also sound barely decent . The ballets are a strange mixture . You get the complete Nutcracker , ( though split up over several tracks in a very frustrating way ) seven and a single excerpt from Sleeping Beauty . The suite from each one would have sufficed , if The chamber pieces were decent , though it would have been nice to see the sextet version of Souvenier de Florence instead of the string orchestra version . and are not too picky on the quality of the performances , you might want to try this out . At 99 cents it is not terrible . -------------PEACE
