This is still the lushest of all the Bee Gees ' albums , unless you count the late , great CUCUMBER CASTLE . That alone makes it worth hearing a few hundred times I do not know what the rift was over the band 's direction that temporarily broke them up ( a family affair , you see ) , and created one of the finest records of the glorious , inglorious Sixties . and everything they would done previous to it , great as it may have been , was merely prelude . In England ODESSA was released as a red - velvet two - LP box set ; in the States as a red - velvet double LP with a remarkably green disaster - at - sea insert . or you could lie back Okay , but ODESSA contains some of the Brothers ' finest compositions , ranging from the story - telling prog - rock of the title track ( the cello solo is an ingenious touch ) to the lighter - than - air , lovely ' Melody Fair ' to the oboe - chugged , acoustic ' Suddenly ' ( Maurice was always the underappreciated contributor ) to the desperately haunted ' Sound Of Love ' . Heck , they even included an international anthem that actually sounds like one , the prescient globalists ! ! You want goofy instead ? Okay , ' Give Your Best ' , These guys are awesome ! Now , stop me before I start raving about how incredible CUCUMBER CASTLE is ! !

reviewText:
It is a myth At least half a myth In the 1960s , it was True . when Stevie Wonder released Music Of My Mind in early 1972 , he proved soul LPs could work as cohesively as any rock LP . Playing the singles on AM was AM 's gain and lack of FM airplay was FMs loss . The Spinners , the album , does not have a concept like the O'Jays Back Stabbers If love and passion can be a concept , it is best illustrated on this album 

 There is the Philly Sound , there is ........ well , easy there , let us climb one mountain at a time . The lush horns , strings , vibes , and master vocals are wound into one massive , wonderful silk sheet of sound . Wagner would be proud 

 " I will Be Around , " " Could It Be I am Falling In Love , " " One Of A Kind Love Affair . " and do you believe how stupid some of us were ? We heard this music next to Daddy Dewdrop 's " Chick - A - Boom , " and quickly ran to our King Crimson albums , unable to separate the prime rib from the beef jerky . The best soul from the worst pop . Wagner would NOT approve . Yeah , sure . Play part of Coltrane 's Love Supreme next to Bobby Goldsboro 's " Honey , " The blimp has crashed . and then go into " One Of A Kind Love Affair , " and it will be the start of a one of a kind love affair -- for you . Check out the third track , " Do not Let The Green Grass Fool You " I need not go into this , but it proves my point . summary: First Class Had To Be Very Cheap (Rating: 4 out of 10- -2.0 stars)
reviewText: Wiz Khalifa 's latest album is nothing more than a huge dissapointment . With NUMEROUS pushbacks in the late 2012 you would think it was to make the product much better . that seems to be the problem here . If you want to know how much money Wiz has and how much weed he smokes , just listen to this album . His colab with Snoop Dogg on Mac & Devin Go to High School was a slight step in the right direction . In First Class / One Night In First Class ) is the worst of all . And one would expect this to be good after the mixtape Taylor Allerdice , which was good as well . Production heren is good . that have the nice long vibing sounds , The best songs on here are the ones he colabs with other artists . " The Bluff " has Cam'ron spitting a good verse . Even 2 Chainz sounds refreshing on " Its Nothin " . And his Taylor Gang crew members sound better than him on " The Plan " The single " Remember You " with The Weeknd sounds good , but having Abel lead off the song and has Wiz rhyme about something totally different makes the song almost a waste . There are a small number of solo songs O.N.I.F.C. had the potential to be a good album . I for one is very dissapointed after all the pushbacks and delays , this is the best we as fans can get . summary: At Long Last, a New Batch of Cat Originals
reviewText: Like so many , I had a feverish reaction to Chan " Cat Power " Marshall 's breakthrough opus , 1998 's Moon Pix . In those days Marshall could only sort of play guitar and kind of sing , In the years since , Marshall has become a competent - and even creative - guitarist , a very good songwriter Marshall 's last album - full of originals , 2006 's The Greatest , pushed the artist to another level . No longer was she the shy indie rock pixie with boyish good looks and ninth overall ) , takes a step back from the big box checkout line , offering up Marshall 's most artsy batch of tunage since the beloved Moon Pix . Despite not having the clearest , most approachable sound , I think Sun is most definitely an accessible , confident even poppy record . Its language is not nearly as universal as the soul sound of The Greatest , We hear drum machines contrasted against gritty licks , the focus always on Marshall 's voice , Where The Greatest was bombastic in its straight - forward style , Sun is a minimalist exercise in labored detail , the Cat having clearly spent much time hunched over the keyboards The result is a stylistically challenging listen that , while more instantly accessible than it sounds , rewards familiarity with the kind of tasteful , timeless , hip detail Marshall has long been known for . that first helped me to understand this anew Cat , feels , at first , like a modern - era pop mess . otherwise a straightforward pop song that reminds me , in sprit at least , of Marah 's Float Away with the Friday Night Gods , a very hated , highly misunderstood attempt at big pop appeal . and my aesthetic impression moved from Float Away to U2 's Pop , a similarly modern and gutsy stab at high - production pop rock . Fun , strange , challenging rides , both . Why release an artsy , challenging , possibly off - putting pop record after achieving breakthrough status with a loyal genre record like The Greatest ? A Bowie - inspired creative spirit who prefers the thrill of creative challenge to the comfort of strategic art . that spirit , that freedom , on every track . The biggest achievement here is how Marshall has managed to form her sprawling ideas about modern pop - and classical songwriter style - in a cohesive piece . that , despite being maybe her most catchy batch of tunes , the record will endure as a deep catalog treasure amongst Cat Power enthusiasts . A side note favorite , loved for its strong personality and creative bravery . To me , Sun is not just one of the year 's most interesting and accomplished listens , but also the second best Cat Power disc yet , stuck only behind 2003 's tremendous You Are Free . and film - focused writing at ZeCatalist.com .

Pet Shop Boys ' last album , Yes , was rather lackluster . It had some good moments , that , Fundamental was pretty good yet still failed to live up to the truly great albums like Very , Behaviour , So it was with a cautious ear I am pleased to report that this album redeems all past mistakes . PSB has crafted a truly blissful offering filled with intelligent and mature electropop . The most striking aspect of Elysium and mid - tempo gems , This is not a bad thing ... as PSB seems to really nail it and it seems many were disappointed because they were expecting something more upbeat . But if one listens without expectations , they will be pleasantly surprised . that I want to skip , which is nice as the last album was so sketchy . The best tracks on here are definitely " Leaving " , which has some really chic arrangement , " Invisible " is melodic and heartfelt , " Breathing Space " is like a more accessible version of Release 's " Birthday Boy " , " Ego Music " is erratic but still works wonderfully here . Mixing broadway - style numbers like " Hold On " with the gloriously dark Truly mesmerizing stuff ! This is truly the Pet Shop Boys ' most beautiful and lush album to date . I truly hope the people giving it negative reviews will click to this album . It truly can not be missed .

Whether he is fronting Gov't Mule , playing with the Allman Brothers or the Dead , that he has ability to enter almost any musical situation and create something wonderful . His recording career has focused almost solely on the electric side of his playing , but as he has shown at many festivals and on his Live at Bonaroo album , Haynes is no slouch with the acoustic guitar . and Dust , are more in the " singer / songwriter " vein than the " crank up the Les Paul " vein , and Haynes finds himself right at home telling stories accompanied by an acoustic guitar . One of the complaints I always had with Haynes ' solo acoustic work was that , even though it was well done , it sounded as though there was something missing . That " something " it turns out was a group of equally talented musicians to accompany him . and Dust , he chose Railroad Earth Railroad Earth are every bit as talented on their respective instruments as Haynes is on the guitar , and the results of the collaboration are as warm and inviting as anything The songs are beautiful , the playing is top notch , and I have no doubt Ashes and Dust will bring Haynes and Co. numerous accolades . Highly recommended .

Her angelic voice is strong but soft , sentimental without being overemotional . Her first album was a walk through the grass , barefoot on a sunny day . Her follow up , was dark like waiting for a storm to pass . which for CBR fans feels like a lifetime . Last we saw Corinne , she was washing her pain away in the sea . She had just lost her husband and her life had hit a standstill . and her life had hit a standstill . and is happy as evident throughout The Heart Speaks in Whispers . She is clearly in love again with heartfelt songs like Horse Print Dress , Been to the Moon She opens up on Hey , I Will Not Break Your Heart . and Night have lyrics like a young Stevie Wonder . The deluxe edition has four more songs including the sultry In The Dark , the best ballad of the album High , the disappointing Ice Cream Colours , and the standout Push On For the Dream . It is good to see CBR happy again . Its easy to forget about Corinne Bailey Rae being Such an absence could have been a risk to her career , and maybe it did hold her back from superstardom after such a hot start ; She does not waste time with metaphorical tales of hypothetical situations . Whatever she is feeling at the time , whether happy , sad or angry , Core fans can appreciate this because she continues to put out consistent , quality work . While she may not gain new fans with The Heart Speaks in Whispers , Corinne Bailey Rae continues to build an extraordinary body of work as the most underrated , underappreciated , Top 5 : Push On For The Dream

summary: "But I can fly through the heavens on the power of my heart/ And thread my way through a string of stars"
reviewText: I would heard some good and great reviews of Toad 's new release and I am agreeing . This is more than a solid from the Wet Sprocket boys . It comes across as mature and self - assured . or adventurous here , but it is melodically solid and enjoyable . Even the slower moments serve the sake of the song 's mood and they seem to have tracked the album to break up the slower numbers ( like " Golden Age " ) with peppier numbers ( like the following " Get What You Want " ) . I hear a bit of a Joe Henry vibe on songs like " The Moment " and " Golden Age " . " California Wasted " has an almost alt - country Wallflowers flavor and opener " New Constellation " drops us into a lighthearted up tempo moment and opener " New Constellation " drops us into a lighthearted up tempo moment but , for my money , album closer " Enough " ( about end of life decisions from someone dying from cancer I think ) is the strongest overall track ; smartly produced , a sad song and yet completely sympathetic yet completely sympathetic and conveying a feeling of strength it ends on an oddly triumphant note . Now I mark this as pure emotion and am not necessarily agreeing ( or disagreeing ) with statements of belief but I can tell you I really appreciate the thoughtful lyrics and not just love pop fluff . Good stuff .

Ever since he started recording these abysmal theme records nearly a decade ago , Rod Stewart has been more about surface appearance than sound . Unfortunately , donning a snazzy suit and ripped jeans makes one Joey Ramone or sporting a soulful swoon makes one Al Green . In the world of Rod Stewart image is consistently at the forefront , especially on this disc , While his voice has coolly mellowed , not every show biz veteran emanates nostalgic gold on cue . or Ke$ha , with little to no soul , substance who know this material is " good for them " but do not have the energy , drive or impetus to locate performances of these songs from better , more suitable vocal interpreters . and nicely orchestrated , and Stewart usually sounds like he is supplying differing emotions as he moves in and these are , after all , some of the best songs ever written . Even a minimum of competence as a singer can make the likes of " What a Difference a Day Makes " and " I have Got the World on a String " sound fine . Stewart displays a minimum of enthusiasm for the material and his job as singer , so it all does sound " fine " - not transcendent , not brilliant , not particularly soulful , rich or stirring - in other words , not good enough . where we , by some wonderful luck , still have Tony Bennett regularly touring and hitting the backs of concert halls , unmiked , with his rendition of Bart Howard 's " Fly Me to the Moon , " there is simply no need to hear Rod Stewart sleepwalk his way through it . It is redundant , reductive , excessive and unwholesome all at once , much like the experience of Michael Buble performing Sinatra bastardization in a predictable suit Go to the nearest jazz hole in the wall you can find if music really matters to you . You are guaranteed to have a more genuine experience than you would have playing this CD or seeing one of Mr. Stewart 's overpriced concerts . that is out of reach , try any album by Madeleine Peyroux .

Teena Marie 's excellent " Beautiful " is the final musical work of " the Ivory Queen of Soul " Recorded in her home studio , it was brought to completion after her passing by her talented daughter Alia Rose and almost sounds like she was looking back with " Wild Horses " from the Passion Play CD and " Beautiful " , all showing she was at the top of her singing , musician , and songwriting abilities . At age 54 many singers are reminiscing with their ' greatest hits ' , but Teena had already ' reloaded ' with " Beautiful " . And it is full of smoking soul , hip R&B , beautiful ballads , that show off her crystal clear , multi - range voice . The ' best of the best ' begins with classic - sounding , multi - tracked " Love Letter " , the mellow " Carte Blanche " , and the latin - tinged swinging ballad " Definition of Down " , while the hip ' spoken word ' intro to the intense ballad " The Long Play " will tug at the heartstrings of long - time Teena Marie fans . The swirling " Maria Bonita " brings to mind her fabulous " Portuguese Love " from her It Must Be Magic career phase . Curtis Mayfield 's SuperFly movie classic " Give Me Your Love " with Alia Rose is lovely This surprise recording caught nearly everyone off guard and it is a timeless " Beautiful " musical posthumous gift from Teena Marie , produced through a labor of love by Alia Rose . My Highest Recommendation . Some MP3 downloads have a bonus track of a great Teena version of Smokey Robinson 's " OOO Baby Baby " . )

Death discs were an important part of pop music in the 1950s One of the most memorable was " Tell Laura I Love Her " in which a teenage driver had a fatal accident in the stock car race he had entered to win cash to buy a wedding ring . The tale was all the more effective for being sung in an angelic high tenor by Ray Peterson . Ray Peterson was born in Denton , TX on April 23 , 1935 . which required lengthy hospitalization . He had several modest hits and then in June of 1960 RCA released " Tell Laura I Love Her " written by Jeff Barry It would become a Top Ten hit . This is the original hit recording you would remember from the radio .

New life has been breathed into the art of contemporary instrumental guitar with the first solo album of original material from veteran guitarist ( Shambhu has a long list of impressive credits , having performed with Narada Michael Walden , Carlos Santana , Sacred Love is one of the most beautiful and most impressive guitar albums I have ever had the pleasure of listening to . One of the photographs on the CD , of Shambhu smiling meekly with his hand over his heart , might lead listeners to think that they are about to hear a collection of ponderous instrumental musings typically associated with New Age music . that there is anything wrong with ( Incidentally , the photograph is appropriate in The CD is brimming with masterfully played , boundary - crossing tunes touching everything from New Age and smooth jazz . In fact , several cuts are radio - friendly and would be right at home on commercial jazz stations . and plays acoustic He also plays electric sitar , This Southeast Asian influence is also reflected in the guitarist 's name , a Sanskrit word meaning " source of happiness , " which is an apt description of his music as well . and Larry Carlton , as well as fellow independent newcomers such as Devin Rice and Erin Aas . The rich , full sound of the CD is fleshed out by an amazing lineup of musicians , among them - to name just a very few - Tony Levin ( John Lennon , Peter Gabriel , King Crimson , Andy Summers ) on bass , Jeff Haynes ( Pat Metheny ) on percussion , Jeff Oster on flugelhorn , and Charlie Bisharat on violin , with enchanting wordless vocals provided by Claytoven Richardson and Private Music fame also lends his guitar and piano talents separately to a couple of tracks . Sacred Love is an album that will satisfy many musical palates , not just those of guitar music fans . Hopefully this is the first of many more wonderful new albums to emerge from his creative vision .

summary: This incomplete and rushed sophomore CD is just OK.
reviewText: I have uneven feelings about Jazmine Sullivan 's sophomore effort , Love Me Back . when paired with Sullivan 's superior vocal ability . A live studio recording session with real musicians seems more suited for   her misguided and under - used talents . Just on the heels of her 2009 CD Fearless , this release is a rushed ill - conceived effort . It pales in comparison to her CD debut . I think more time should have been devoted in the development of this project . Seconds " are the best   tracks . I also favor " Redemption " for its ' vocal arrangement But , Sullivan 's duet with the popular Ne - Yo is likely to be the third single to garner heavy rotation radio airplay . That song really gets on " my damn nerves , damn nerves " ! Too often today 's music results in good voice presented with bad material . I hope Sullivan 's future projects will be more creative with time invested . This incomplete and rushed sophomore CD could have been great . But , it is just OK .

summary: A Nerd Anthem by the Nerd Minstrel
reviewText: Like most people , I discovered this song while watching the show Code Monkeys . that whole show , I got a little interested in the song , Even though I loved the show , I can tell you that Jonathan Coulton 's song has now become the much more important to me . I love it for a couple of reasons . First , it is a tremendously catchy song . It is well played and sung , with a great pop - rock chorus . Second , it is actually sort of a meaningful song , at least to me . but there is not doubt that I am a nerd , the proverbial nice - guy and can not get the pretty receptionist to pay any attention to me , who works hard in a job that is boring and unappreciated . Goodness , I even like to drink Tab I am not the only person like this . So , I just love it for being a good song acknowledging my experience of the world , while being funny and hopeful , too . It is a great song that I have found myself passing along to my nerd friends who love it , too .

They sound like 50s cocktail music sometimes and like 90s jazz sometimes . The two lead members both went to Harvard and the composer / pianist is a musical genius . The only way to really explain them is to play a few tracks from their CDs .. or better I was anxiously awaiting this disc and am not disappointed ! ( Well , maybe All the elements of their previous albums are there from the multi - lingual songs crafted by either lead singer China Forbes who is responsible for 5 of the 13 songs here ) to the great arrangements by co - leader Thomas Lauderdale . I really hated to drop my rating to a 4 It was great that they got the staff in their office to join in on the track " Sing " ( the Sesame Street / Carpenters song ) , that even PM can not make it palatable on repeated listening . that does not work as well is " Piensa en m " , where 90 year old Mexican singer Chavela Vargas ( artist Frida Kahlo 's lover ) provides the vocals . Her aged voice is a far cry from the dulcet tones of China Forbes and the musical flow stops All is well , though when the lyrically brief ( just two verses ) " New Amsterdam " closes out the disc , before a reprise of the lead off " Ninna nanna " . Though not my favorite PM CD , its heads above much of the other music out there . Pink Martini fans will definitely want this disc ( while waiting anxiously for the next ) , and it is a good intro to those yet to discover the " musical magic " of the band .

When it has came down to what Ed Sheeran has tried to show in his music , has been more hip hop - based than what his natural beauty in his heart . He had some really great songs before and Sing from the X album , I was thinking he had lost his beloved heart . But his latest song does take him back on solid ground . Thinking Out Loud , the third single from the X album does work better with his simplicity and natural beauty . The song definitely is a much better song than what he had lately came out with . The song is a better download than his past few songs were . Hopefully , there will be more joy and natural beauty with his work soon .

Two words only are needed to sum up this soundtrack , Simply Beautiful . Bjork is such a musical genius , she is up in another league of women musicians , shared by only a select few . But what makes Bjork such a wonderful musician is how she creates the most un believeable songs , whether it is an orchestral masterpiece ( as shown on this album ) or a sweeping ballad with a huge choir , Bjork has done She is in fact the most inventive musician there ever has been that good and this album proves it . The first track to start this album is " Overture " , well named as it is the overture to the film . and works its way into a fully rounded orchestral masterpiece . Bjork is well known for her use of orchestras in her music and this fully orchestra track is well worth the listen , because I do not really like classical music I was really ominous about this track , this is actually my favourite classical music piece ever . "Cvalda " is a really weird song , it starts off with about 1 minutes worth of machine and factory sounds the finally -Clatter , crash , clack , racket , bang , thump- and sonically loud . Catherine Denevue makes a worthy appearance on this song and adds to the excitement and energy . On the next track Bjork ropes in another musical genius , Thom Yorke of Radiohead to create quite simply the most moving track the album along with -New World- . that is credited with me first getting into Bjork . and I instantly went searching for it . This song is so amazingly beautiful . and Bjork work so well on this duet . but well worth the listen and it has the most wonderful electronic programming in it . and how -you are going to have to find out for yourself- quite a lyrical muddle but it is very well written . " In The Musicals " is a very good song that starts off with a basketball like sound . The irony is It is strangely empowering and encouraging . and Bjork cooing every random number and everything goes fantastic . Again she ropes in another beautiful guest to accompany her . although this album is short it is well worth the listen . This track is AMAZING and I did not realise it was this wonderful for a while , a great example of how songs can come to grow on you . but every track is fantastic . I thoroughly recommend this to anyone , of any age .

summary: I like it, like it, yes I do
reviewText: This scarcely needs a review or not they like the Stones and most people considering this collection will know all the tracks on it very well indeed . It is worth saying , though , that this is a great collection . Obviously , any compilation like this will have some tracks you love and some you do not like so much , and some of your favourites will be missing ( What - no Sister Morphine but as a " Best Of " collection I do not think you can do better . It is well selected and sounds fantastic : the digital transfers of the early stuff are particularly good and bring real life to the tracks without interfering with their original sound . I suspect and for me this was a good way of getting some of the best of it on CD . You certainly get plenty of great stuff , and personally I found listening to this was like running my life on fast forward from the age of about 10 , with pretty well every track conjuring up It is also great to hear the evolution of the band from the early covers , through finding their distinctive identity around the time of Satisfaction Although I have not always liked the direction they have taken , this is a reminder that the Rolling Stones really are one of the finest bands of the last 50 years and Richards are a truly great songwriting team . The full range of classics is here , from the storming rockers like Jumpin ' Jack Flash through to the hauntingly beautiful Angie . Also included is their new ( November 2012 ) single Doom And Gloom which I think is excellent - a real Stones belter and one of their best tracks in ages . The question , of course , is " Do I need another Stones Greatest Hits album ? " For me it is a great summary of their career containing some of my favourite ever tracks , and has made them available to me in CD format . If you want a good , well put - together collection of The Rolling Stones , you can not go wrong with this set .

summary: What a Beautiful World We Live In
reviewText:
After pounding out an R.E.M. sound - alike in 2011 in the form of " The King Is Dead , " The Decemberists back up a bit for the more middle of the road " What A Terrible World , What A Wonderful World . " There are some subtle changes , like heavier strings which are good . where the band apologizes for making a commercial for Axe Shampoo ( " The Singer Addresses His Audience " ) . They know they are not the same band that cut the masterful " The Crane Wife , " that cut the masterful " The Crane Wife , " and openly admit such . What they are for " What a Terrible World ... " are a crafter of songs . They have found a sweet spot between the ornate structure of those early albums to a sense of pop melody . It makes a love song like " Philomenia " all the more jaunty The band also sound more integrated this time around , where " The King Is Dead " was a showcase for Chris Funk , here , piano dominates many of the songs . I kind of like that folk vein , as one of my favorites here Colin Malloy almost making a sea shanty song out of " Better Not Wake The Baby . " 

 " What a Terrible World ... " will probably polarize fans As for me , I can respect Maybe they still aspire to be R.E.M. or even 10,000 Maniacs ( some of the poetic lyrics recall the Maniacs ' ) . What ever direction they travel , I am happy to follow as long as the music is this good .

summary: Evolution of the Classical Era Violin Concerto
reviewText: A member of one of the most famous families from Bohemia , Franz Benda ( 1709 - 1789 ) entered into the service of Frederick the Great in 1732 . As a violin master , he played some 50,000 performances over a forty year period . and string dominated orchestral support . As a transitional work from the Baroque , it contains more interplay between the single violin Smoothly flowing , Bendas writing for the solo string is virtuosic without being showy , letting the melodic lines develop naturally . In the minor keyed Largo , the sweep of the orchestral accompaniment lends a somber weight to the throbbing vibrato of Gabriela Demeterova . With a dramatic pathos in the uppermost register , she brings a sorrowful sweetness in her tone that set apart Bendas adagio playing . Horns appear for the brisk finale , a bright Allegro with bravura fiddling as the single violin drifts high on the E string . and theology in Prague before accepting a musical directorship in Milan . and died while playing a violin concerto at the Lobkowitz Palace . 3 , No . 1 opens with a marching Allegro sostenuto , clipped and precise . While still employing the harpsichord as continuo , the writing finds even greater collaboration between the soloist and orchestra , engaging in extensive rhythmic interactions and trading melodic ideas , including one haunting echo in minor . A minor keyed charmer , the following Adagio finds striking support in the lower strings with a lovely countermelody while the ethereal vibrato of the solo sounds so much like the beating of angel wings . Ending the 2nd movement on an open cadence sets up a smooth transition as the resolution occurs in the sweetly pure tones from the violin , the very first notes of the concluding Rondo . Interrupting the relentless drive in the lower strings , a brief passage in minor offers a dark interlude in an otherwise cheery finale . Renowned as a teacher and violin virtuoso , Antonin Vranicky ( 1761 - 1820 ) composed some outstanding chamber music and challenging concertos , one of and winds to create a broader palette of orchestral colors , the work begins with a bold Allegro giusto . Amid a longer , more extensive development section , the soloist shines in the fiendishly difficult passage work while in the reverential Adagio that follows , the writing stretches the upper reaches of the instruments register . After a chorale like start , the weeping violin carries the movement until gentle horns lead to a serene close . Marked Alla Pollacca- Allegretto , the finale is a frisky Polish folk dance . With an appealing stutter step in the rhythm , this 3rd movement features a brief mournful interlude , dazzling flourishes from the violin The original recording from 1995 from Supraphon is fine , placing the solo violin close enough for the intimate slower sections to be sharp and clear . Under the able artistic direction of Milan Lajcik , the Prague Chamber Orchestra brings an accomplished reading to their fellow countrymens concertos . But the spotlight rightfully belongs to the exquisite work of Gabriela Demeterova . This fine traversal of the development of the Viennese violin concerto is testimony to her artistry . Please note that the 2008 edition includes a video bonus track of the bold Allegro giusto from Vranickys concerto in C Major .

This has been a rather prolific year for The Roots as they released " How I got over " earlier in the year . Both were inspired by the 2008 United States presidential election and chose songs they felt were obscure . The album has a loose live - jam feel to it with the only Hip Hop infusion being sporadic rapping by Black Thought The lone original composition is the church piano - driven " Shine " . " Humanity ( Love the way it should be ) " is horn - sprinkled Reggae . They eschew the popular songs on Marvin Gaye 's " What is going on " going for " Wholy holy " . Lead - off single " Wake up everybody " features Common " Hard times " and " Compared to what " ( with an incredibly groovy bassline and funky horns ) are Funk / Soul , " Little ghetto boy " an airy organ - driven Jazz / Soul ballad , while " I can not write left handed " is a sprawling 12 minute epic , an anti - war lament originally done by Bill Whithers telling the story of a wounded war veteran writing a letter to his mother . and what prevents the album from being too depressing and preachy are the excellent vocals and superb musicianship .

summary: A perfect choice for The Piano Guys if there ever was one.
reviewText: They have done Star Wars , Twilight , Lord of the Rings , ... It seems appropriate that the " greatest movie song of all time " gets the Piano Guys treatment . that easily converts to a classical piece . It has all the elements to become a powerful , emotional song . that sounds like it could be played with a ukulele . Steven 's ability to manipulate cellos to get the right sound for the song never ceases to amaze me . And Jon 's familiarity with the piano gives the impression he is not only playing the piano , but " playing " with it ; like a childhood toy . that throws the song into the majestic finale . and the first half is right on the beach ; the waves , literally , splashing at their heels as they play on the sand , rocks , The key - change shifts to a ridiculously green valley surrounded by equally green mountains ; the planners and ( piano ) movers making the shift from one location to the other look effortless . As " overplayed " as the original can be , I can listen to this version over P. S.   If you are fortunate enough to get a hold of their concert DVD from Public Broadcasting , " Live at Red Butte Garden " , they perform this song with lyrics sung by the One Voice Childrens Choir . It is beautifully performed and I hope an Mp3 or CD version will be available in the future . Once heard with the choir it is almost missed -P. P. S. Bravo to those kids for singing so well that night ; it was quite cold and I am sure it took effort to stand out there in the wind and still keep a smile .

Lianne La Havas Is Your Love Big Enough is the one I actually learned about Is Your Love Big Enough while looking at the best of 2012 list compiled by an on - line magazine that I respect   Pop Matters . Is Your Love Big Enough landed at number two on Pop Matters best R&B list . That piqued my curiosity However , I did not listen right away . In many ways LaHavas is a fusion of the many of the female singers from Great Britain who have achieved varying levels of success in America over the last five years . Acoustic tunes such as Tease Me , Age   a witty tune in which the 23 - year old singer / songwriter tells a tale of falling for a much older man and the duet No Room For Doubt place La Havas in and R&B fusion occupied by singer / songwriters such as the tragically overlooked Rachael Bell . 

 Tracks such as the sparse and melancholy Gone allow LaHavas to display vocal range . that gives the artist free range to showcase her powerful and soulful vocal instrument , and might remind listeners of power ballads rendered by Adele on her instant classic 21 . La Havas occupies her own space on the percussive Forget , a tune the singer wrote after a break - up . The track is a high - energy amalgamation of funk which La Havas showcases her deft fingering on her constantly present guitar . where she yells fooorgeeet / all the words the let you break my heart combine the assertiveness of rock with one the one bounce of funk . Recorded at a couple of pit stops in Germany , the Netherlands , Glasgow Scotland , Paris , Oslo , Stockholm , Denmark , Ireland , and Donington ) , the first live release from NOLA - based sludge / doom metal supergroup Down is spread out over the course of sixteen tracks that is for sure , but also one extremely satisfying and enjoyable one , that is overflowing with the good stuff : Great riffs , solos , and frontman Phil Anselmo 's household wail . And 2010 's " Diary Of A Mad Band " is also sparked with an excellent , palpable , and inescapable live energy , though each and every one of these songs is also flawlessly performed . Tracks like the opening " Losing All " are fat with big , beefy , grinding riffage but are also peppered with a good batch of unorthodoxly ripping guitar soloing . This number is also of note for featuring quite a bit of crowd interaction , because it is an up - tempo , deeply grooving riff - fest with plenty of noteworthy , wah - tinged lead / solo work to go along with its brutal guitar licks and cool , shrieking vocals . And later cuts like " Rehab , " that it has crashing cymbal rides in place of vocal shrieks . but are you having a good time ? ! " And really , it is almost impossible not to have one once you have heard this tune 's serrated , grinding riffs , and the Down frontman 's glorious , household wailing / screaming . but once it dissolves into a white - hot ball of buzzsaw riffing and ripping soloing , it becomes very clear that it is another big standout . " Learn From This Mistake " is a slow - burning , low - key , and very brooding doom metal dirge peppered with some wailing , and totally air - guitar - able leads thus making it another standout ; and " Hail The Leaf , " which is stuffed to the gills with chunky , chugging guitar licks , is another . that Down had not played live in a long time , Moving along , the first disc closes with one of its biggest highlights in " New Orleans Is A Dying Ho , " which again overflows with pounding doom riffs , whammy - bar - inflected leads , and fiery , inspiring solos . The second disc opens on a misleading note , with " Lies , I Do not Know What They Say , But ... " being backed by an ominous , bass - driven plod . But immediately following it , we are introduced to the big , fat , chugging riffage , grinding rhythms , pounding skins of the brutal bruiser A noteworthy solo also comes ripping through , here , too . that he demands to " see this place go berserk , " an easy task , too , when considering this up - tempo fist pumper features lots of excellent riffs that is immediately offset by an ensuing brutal , and booming riff - fest in " Stone The Crows " ; and the set closer , " Bury Me In Smoke . " This one begins on a mildly comical note , as it is introduced with the joke because it , too , just oozes with amazing , serrated sludge / doom metal riffing . " Diary Of A Mad Band " serves as a great companion release to Down 's excellent 2007 release , " Over The Under , " and a satisfying snack for you to listen to while the band is on one of its inexplicably extensive hiatuses . So even though it can not be said to be a mandatory purchase , it is a worthwhile one for all hardcore fans of the band .

Where GB is deep voiced , political , a touch crude , Iris is girlish , sincere , that throwback , red - dirt - girl kind of way . Her voice is so distinctive It is so evocative of rural Arkansas Clearly she takes her time , thinks very carefully about what she wants to say and how to say it best . This album is quite special and echoes the theme of Infamous Angel from 1992 : and like a good daughter showing the wisdom of her mother 's life lessons . The record is truly a family affair . and has worked on everyone is albums . Pieta gets the photo credits for the album , including the classic cover photo . but I like to imagine they are like family to Iris . Fittingly , the album is dedicated to Dasha , the Russian - born daughter she that she thanked Greg " for never losing faith in me . " I imagine the harder battle for this humble and talented woman is not to lose faith in herself . I found myself unexpectedly moved to tears by Before the Colors Fade . Another high point :   Mama Was Always Tellin ' Her Truth . But really , there is not a weak song on this album . Maybe not too surprising if you figure she is been working on this one since her last album 16 years ago . and I want to hear every bit of it . Update 9/9/13 - It is almost too embarrassing to admit , but I was enjoying this album again over the weekend It is so fine . that is Iris herself playing This is a very special album .

summary: WELCOME TO THE MANY SOUNDS AND STYLES OF ABiCA
reviewText: but it is with this release " Numb " " Numb " If you thought you knew ABiCA with their previous releases then this album is going to hit you hard as it is a giant leap in quality . who are the two mcs / vocalists in ABiCA have a great interplay style , it helps and do not sound like each other . The album opens with the soft sound of piano keys on title track " Numb " before the vocals kick in , it is a brave move for a band to start a debut album on such a quiet note , in reality it is just easing you into the next 55 minutes of varying styles . " Turn Me On " has a great interplay of vocals which features former memeber Can not on vocals , the track is a hip hop delight and will keep longtime ABiCA fans happy . The track features a cool loop throughout the track . " The Pursuit " sounds like vintage " Licensed To Ill " Beastie Boys . " Take This Away " starts with a haunting piano and has Hash delivering some heavy lines as Tac sings in the background , it is a perfect example of both members varying styles working rally well . who has mixed many a Nine Inch nails song himself , his production qualities really shine on the track . Former member Can not appears again on " Blurry " . The final track " What You See " is a rock stomper with Tac leading the vocal duties , it is a great way to finish off the album . The only complaint you can really level at the album is With " Numb " ABiCA have set the mark high for their next album , which should be ready to go by late 2011 early 2012 . It is amazing to think the Tac and released their own album , the sound quality is great as good as you would get on any major record label release , the artwork is cool with detailed information on and engineered what as well as what the guest performers roll in each track was . and the Beastie Boys , for me they sound a bit like Pop Will Eat Itself " Dos Dedos Mis Amigos " era a former English band who featured Black Swan composer Clint Mansell on Vocals . ABiCA are determined to get their name out there , and even on Hash 's album notes he encourages you to share the album with other people . ABiCA " Numb " deserves to be heard by a wide audience ! !

I was a slow comer to Linkin Park . I figured they were another flash in the pan , one hit wonder . I was wrong . One thing they have proven throughout the course of their career is reliability in good song writing , and impressive chemistry as bandmates . The Hunting Party lacks gimmickry , that feels like it is just a band playing together . No loops , no electronica , no excessive polish . It all sounds like a band got together in a room and knocked out some killer , high energy tunes . The Hunting Party has the best of Linkin Park - Big , hooky singalong choruses , rap / singing structures , and a new innovation for them ... raw , unvarnished grit . This here is straight forward , blast the stereo speakers RAWK . Perhaps the biggest letdown is the instrumental track with Tom Morello , that was Tom Morello playing if it were not for the liner notes . Small gripe . Linkin Park has served up a refreshing nugget of pure rock , filling a void in a genre gasping for relevance . Hats off to them for the risky move with a big payoff .

I eagerly bought They were different than everything else on the radio ; True , he was pretty much following the formula set down by Waylon Jennings ( but it was still a nice change from the regular mainstream pace . And then Bentley kind of petered out ; MODERN DAY DRIFTER and LONG TRIP ALONE just were not as good as his debut , even if they featured a handful of amazing songs . why I did not really pay attention when Bentley released a new album ( I completely ignored his last couple ) . I am all for mainstream singers cutting loose Nashville 's chains and doing what they want ( I am waiting for the day Toby Keith decides to give radio the finger ... still waiting ... I should probably give up ... ) . ON THE RIDGE is , at its heart , a bluegrass concept album , filled with minor - key songs about love Some have decidedly upbeat lyrics ( " Fiddlin ' Around " ) , and some use up - tempo melodies to convey not - so - happy lyrics ( " You are Dead to Me " and " Bad Angel " ) . Yet this is not a feel - good album ; it is an album by a man not quite happy with his musical surroundings ( Bentley has not had a genuine hit in a few years , I do not think ) , who has decided to play outside radio . RIDGE will not have much radio success ; in this day and age of hick anthems , blindly patriotic lyrics , So be it ; quite a few of us do not even bother turning the radio on anymore ( God bless satellite radio , though ) . Bentley is joined by a few compatriots , notably from outside mainstream country : Del McCoury , Chris Thile , the Punch Brothers , Jamey Johnson , Miranda Lambert , Kris Kristofferson , Vince Gill , Some of the material here is top notch : Bentley shines on Kristofferson 's darkly humorous " From the Battle to the Bottom , " even if he does not capture the original 's whimsy ( and Kristofferson , unfortunately , is not in top form voice - wise , though he is still a welcome addition ) ; " Down in the Mine " is a hauntingly beautiful tune ; " Bad Angel " features engaging performances by Lambert Some other songs are solid , if not among Bentley 's best , and while Bob Dylan 's " Senor " is a wonderful skeptic 's tune , it does not quite fit Bentley Overall , UP ON THE RIDGE is a solid album from a man who is finally doing what he wants ( again ; I still say his debut album was a fine example of classic - style country music ) . It will not sell as well as his previous records , and it will not overwhelm radio with any hits , and casual fans who appreciate high - caliber music with genuine soul , music that is never mined out , will rejoice at the album . It is not a classic , and it has its weak spots , but it is still a fine return to form for Dierks Bentley , who is still one of the more promising country artists out there .

For example , really memorable , Sabbath - inspired guitar riffing , good solos , prominent , grumbling bass lines , Peter Steele 's masculine that is so deep , it almost matches his bass sound ) , both humorous and depressing lyrics , creepy keyboards , well - written melodies , bullying grooves , gothic overtones , occasional psychedelic sounds , and solid drumming are all definitely very much apart of the band 's famous arsenal . and feeling of greatness present on 2007 's " Dead Again , " making it easily their finest release since 1996 's iconic " October Rust . " For one , there should be absolutely no question as to if Type O are just phoning it in and/or recycling old material ( that some fans believed to be the case on 1999 's " World Coming Down " and 2003 's " Life Is Killing Me " ) , because they now sound as inspired , energetic , and all - around strong as ever ! but thanks to the rather broad and sophisticated songwriting on display here , these 10 songs do possess a fairly refreshing and unpredictable quality . and genres , including really heavy doom metal , sludge , thrash ( and progressive and frequently quite fast , yet ( in True T.O.N. style ) , it also retains a certain level of control Suffice it to say , this is one very rewarding , well - rounded , In addition , at 77 minutes in length ( ! ) , it should be more than long enough to satiate all fans ' appetites for the foreseeable future . The terrifically ominous and choir - abetted intro of the title track begins thins on a creepy note . It then segues into propulsive speed metal territory -- a rollicking groove , strong bass work throughout , " Tripping A Blind Man " works similarly : An old - school Black Sabbath - meets - Eighties thrash ( i.e. , say , Megadeth ) piece with a neat gothic keyboard beginning before suddenly becoming almost crushing when blazing tempos , fast guitar leads , and an exceptional solo ( near the end ) slam onto the scene . " The Profits Of Doom " falls somewhere between My Dying Bride , Crowbar , Acid Bath , Deep Purple , It is a slow and extremely progressive , slow - burning , brooding , that weigh a ton , a beefy bottom - end completed by noteworthy , and dirty , grungy - sounding bass lines , that trade - off between growling , eerie spoken - words , and impressive , proper singing . On the flip side , " September Sun " is a very pretty , somber , textured , tranquil , that is peppered with cool piano keys , melodic strings , and warm and powerful crooning . The lyrics are also worth mentioning here , because they are so sad and dark that it would not be surprising if they leave a lump in the listener 's throat . Next up , " Halloween In Heaven " is much catchier and more accessible than usual . Here , a memorable , driving , stoner metal - ish main riff is accented nicely by soaring , clean backing female vocals . and - a - half - minutes long , song number six , " These Three Things , " takes the cake for being the set 's pinnacle and is possibly the biggest highlight to be found here . It is an extremely dark , goth - y , and stormy piece based primarily on droning guitars and muscular bass work , but it also makes sure to include numerous different facets , and lots of nice subtleties , atmosphere , and mood - enhancers . 

 Taking a break from their more experimental side , " She Burned Me Down " is more proof when they want to , Type O Negative can always kick out pure doom metal with the best of them , and is highlighted by excellent , mesmerizing riffage , emotional vocals , and a fiery " Some Stupid Tomorrow " again takes things into an up - tempo pace ; in fact , one could argue it sounds kind of like a Motorhead tune . and sometimes almost punk - y ) drumming ( including a few bass kicks ) , call - and a steadfastly meaty The curiously entitled " An Ode To Locksmiths " boasts a leather - clad rock ` n ' roll vibe , tasty , crunchy , lumbering guitars , and Ozzy Osbourne - inspired singing . Finally , the closing " Hail And Farewell To Britain " once again downshifts into depressive doom territory , with a bass - heavy mix , big , fat , chugging guitar riffs , lock - step - unison rhythms , and a great keyboard solo . Cutting to the chase , " Dead Again " is , quite simply , one very amazing album , And it is the sound of a band that is easily firing on all cylinders ; hence , contrary to its misleading title , it is also proof that is easily firing on all cylinders ; hence , contrary to its misleading title , it is also proof that this band has never sounded more alive / lively . However , in an oh - so - cruel twist - of - fate , Peter Steele passed away from heart failure in April 2010 , at the age of 48 . But even if we are faced with the sad truth that we will now never again hear anything new from T.O.N. , at least fans can take solace in the fact that the frontman lead a remarkable career , and unquestionably went out on the absolute top . R.I.P. Peter , you will be missed .

Shonen Knife has been around since 1981 and are well known for their poppy take on rock and early punk rock acts . " Rock N Roll High School " is a track from their latest album ' Osaka Romones - Tribute To The Ramones ' ( available only in MP3 format currently ) . It is a cheerful version rather than the angrier original and sounds like something you might hear while watching ' Teen Titans ' or some other modern kids cartoon . They in fact have done soundtrack work and are on the Powerpuff Girls soundtrack ' Heroes and Villains ' . So I am not saying their rendition is bad ... just different . I like the song well enough , but it is not something I would play every day . The rest of ' Osaka Romones ' sounds much the same , so if you like enjoy Shonen Knife 's take on " Rock N Roll High School " and J - Pop in general , then you might want to add it to your Cloud Player and jam out with the three girls from Osaka .

Emmylou 's " Hard Bargain " unfolds with grace as she spreads her wings as a songwriter . that opens the set has grown on me with repeated listenings with the sonic landscape broad & expansive , " I come down from the mountain ; I come walkin ' in your shoes ; I was taken for a gambler when I had no more to lose . " It is exquisite . Emmylou tackles the death of Emmett Till , a martyr for the Harris ' sense of humor comes to the fore on the loping " Big Black Dog . " The melodic title track evokes sadness and anticipation , " Each time I am headin ' for nowhere , doomed & determined to go there . " " Darlin ' Kate " is a lovely elegy , I assume for Kate McGarrigle . The set concludes with the tantalizing " Cross Yourself " and blooms like a gentle caress . " Hard Bargain " is not flashy , but it is deep , heartfelt and has some passionate and emotional vocals by one of our master musicians . Enjoy !

I can not imagine Green Day playing these tracks live a whole bunch in the future . My guess is they have pulled out two albums worth of tracks The problem here is most of what is been served up does not cut it . Brutal Love is the highlight of the album . It is almost a straight rip off of several other songs including The Beatles ' Oh Darling . Also close to the formula of Oh Love ( including the ` copy the tune ' guitar solo ) I like it though , Missing You is OK but only good filler Drama Queen is a slower number one of the better tracks though perhaps a tad disturbing ... ( B+ ) - X - Kid is the best of the ` rockers ' and a definite highlight and Violence is a bit of nothing It is no Amy ( C ) - Dirty Rotten Bastards surely can not be taken seriously . Just too many rip - offs of other songs for me to like this one . Identical start to Lazy Bones The Forgotten is OK ( there is a lot of just OK stuff here ) but not up there with their best ballads . It does not really go anywhere 

 So unfortunately , at the end of the three albums my fears have been realised - that there is only really one album worth of great material . You could argue two good albums worth of tracks but the three has not really cut it . Good on them for having a go and I doubt many others could have done better .

summary: WIth shoes like that you'll be single for a long time
reviewText: " A Single Man " by Elton John is a hard one to evaluate . On the one hand , the songs are mostly good ones ; and the production is super sweet ! Very soft But Elton 's vocals are mostly dis - engaged and generally charmless . " Return to Paradise " might just be ; what with those beautiful Falsetto vocals , " Georgia " might   be an under - rated one of those Southern Anthems But , for me , the real nuggets are the final three songs " Madness " , " Reverie " which all sit well together , kind of a trio of darkness , really ; " Madness " is a spine chilling disco - prog - rocker with lots of haunting piano chords ; " Reverie " is brief but effective , and " Song for Guy " is suitably melancholy The vocal part is particularly evocative . The other songs are not bad . " I do not care " is a fun rocker in the style of his earlier ones , but the vocals do not relay the fun . " Part - time love " is the best of the rest , a pumpy little tune with a big production . Not a bad album , Rating * * 1/4

The pointblank outpouring of the feminine soul - in a state of anguish & mourning - receives its full measure in this exceptional classic " Un - break My Heart " ; sung with truly unique voice inflections & intonations by Toni Braxton ; composed & written by Diane Eve Warren . We hear our heroine pleading for and commanding her deceased or departed lover to return to her immediately to assauge her loss and hurt , " Do not leave me in all this pain , Do not leave me out in the rain ... " The use of the imperative is so forceful Braxton 's soft , silky utterances easily immerse the listener in the strength when she pours it on , " Say you will love me again , Undo this hurt you caused When you walked out the door And walked out of my life ; Un - cry these tears , I cried so many nights ... Un - break my heart ! " And walked out of my life ; Un - cry these tears , I cried so many nights ... Un - break my heart ! " The excellent video for this song with its dramatic intensity lifts this rendition into being scene- and plot - driven , like " Mourning Becomes Electra " with the lights turned down . This in turn builds plot and ' grief ' motif within ' surround sound ' orchestration . Braxton 's intensity , her passionate request for her lover to return - becomes one of the more powerful crescendos in pop music . This would not be so - if her lips were sealed - they had to be un - sealed - her depth of expression from deep within her soul - may cause us to grieve ( our catharsis , her purge of emotion ) . and empathize with her loss . It is quite satisfying if not exhausting . We hope to be drenched in her emotional denouement upon re - playing this cinematic song . It is yours to enjoy when the mood is right . summary: Well Conceived and Crafted Rap Album
reviewText: or semi - veteran ) in the rap game considering the number of albums 2012's The Stoned Immaculate , despite his previous releases , is his debut effort on major label Warner Bros. The results are nothing short of positive as the MC delivers strongly throughout the course of The Stoned Immaculate . There are no overt misses , though the greatest cuts do overshadow the lesser ones . " What It Look Like " featuring Wale is a soulful , lush way to open the effort . that made Wale 's own Ambition enjoyable , " What It Look Like " combines two MC 's with solid skills that contrast each others respective styles . Wale 's flow is agile while Curren$y allows for his southern drawl and lazier style to ` go to work . ' All is anchored in Wale 's simple , though smart and addictive hook : " Look , what it look like/ my n --- s , fly n----s , this is Jet Life ... " " Privacy Glass " may have a hard act to follow , and strings with ease . His flow is casual , but he sells this clever cut well - after all he " ... usually does not ride like this / privacy tinted , professionally driven . The production is a bit odd , but certainly enjoyable with its speaker - rattling bass . " Armoire " is not quite as elite as " What It Look Like " Young Roddy & Trademark deliver a sound enough hook while Curren$y handles the verses . who give off a ` chill ' sound . Ambrosius vocals suit the cut , though she is not given much chance to ad lib on the simple hook : " Bright lights , big city / big cars ... so baby you can roll with me / I will show you how it is supposed to be . " While " Take You There " is good , it is not quite to the level of its predecessors . " Showroom " also falls into this boat , delivering a sound cut , though not the ` best of the best . and - coming 2 Chainz restores any conceded momentum or energy . Both MC 's deliver strong verses in this five - minute plus ditty , which features superb old - school , soulful production . that ` shapes ' the overall cut . While minimal might be the approach , the end results are ` excellence . ' The hook is none too shabby either : " And my reputation precedes me , they already know / I keep it capital G apostrophe D / Going hard , making it look easy / when I do what it do , I do it like I am doing it for TV . " " No Squares " claims valedictory honors with its slow , grinding tempo and lazy , inherently southern production . and proves the perfect collaborator for Curren$y - " I am rolling up an insane amount of smoke / diamonds all up in the chain around my throat ... " he boasts at the beginning of his verse . The hook is killer : " No square shall enter in the circle of winners ... are not been like none of them n --- s as far as I can remember ... " " Sunroof , " featuring Corner Boy P brings the effort back to earth after its lofty ascent , but still remains strong . The use of 808 complements the other drum programming well here , adding some extra ` punctuation . ' " Chasin ' Papers " ` brings back ' the swagger of " No Squares " delivering an odd - ball collaboration with Pharrell Williams ( The Neptunes produce ) . Pharrell 's somewhat weak , though distinct voice works perfectly here to deliver one of the more left - brain hooks : " I know I was there so I seen that you scared and the girls want to Not to be outdone by Pharrell , Estelle delivers grace and excellence on the more romantic " which she proudly sings " ... you are everything thing ... see On the bridge , unlike with Marsha Ambrosius on " Take You There , " Estelle is given breathing room to ` shine ' . " Chandelier " features those good ole soulful , dusty beats and bass line , though at over five minutes unlike the other ` fivers , ' it lacks the substance to be as effective . " Fast Cars Faster Women " featuring and produced by Daz Dillinger works well , with its soulful production . Curren$y is definitely in his zone as is Dillinger 's clearer , contrasting rap vocals on verse two . It does not end the album with the zest that " What It Look Like " opens it with , but at this point , Curen$y has already proven himself . A solid album, The Stoned Immaculate has no major flaws . but there are no qualms with quality overall . Solid effort .

It is absolutely so sad whenever someone young and talented dies early & before their time . With the shocking news of the passing of Chris Cornell of Soundgarden , it is just another tragic reminder of Rock & Roll excess from drugs , alcohol and depression . summary: "Light" Made Brighter Through Stories of Pain
reviewText:
Prime Cuts :   The Power of a Prayer , Hello My Name Is , Forgiveness 

 Quipped with memorable lines , stocked with engaging stories , and imbued with life transforming Biblical truths , these are ingredients that make these 12 new cuts from West 's new CD so alluring . After dabbling his toes last year in the festive waters with the release of his first ever Christmas release last year , " Into the Light " is West 's newest effort following the hugely successful " The Story of Your Life . " Save for the title cut " Into the Light " being co - written by West This should not come as a surprise as West is one of the most sought after writers in Nashville , having written cuts for Rascal Flatts , Mandisa , Point of Grace , Billy Ray Cyrus , Natalie Grant Shortly after the release of " Story , " West collected over 10,000 personal stories from his fans and their struggles with God and the Christian faith . West needs to be applauded for sermonising these testimonies for us in interweaving the penetrating pain , frustrations and disappointments of these protagonists with heart wrenching Scriptural truths and profoundly thought out faith statements . Again this album is choke full songs of songs with soaring hooks including the lilting title cut " Into the Light . " With the repetitive chant " Come on ! Come On ! " inviting us to leave our sinful lives to follow after Christ 's light , this is the Gospel call made irresistibly indelible . Nestled in the soft stirring of strings , " Forgiveness " is a Godly response towards a lady by the name of Renee who lost her 20 - year - old daughter when she was hit by a drunken driver . when West warmly nudges , " So let it ( the hurt ) go and be amazed / By what you see through the eyes of grace / The prisoner that it really frees is you . " Ultimately our pains can only be put down via the power of prayer , Somehow one would wish West would somehow include more piano ballads as he truly does them with utmost beauty . West is not afraid to be creative in his story telling . where Job would quiz God about his sufferings , " Moved by Mercy " finds West and response between God and a fellow sufferer . While the perennial struggle of listening to voices of regret and defeat over anchoring our identity in Christ is the theme of the invigorating " Hello My Name Is . " The crisp guitars , the assertive piano chops and the gutsy lyrics certainly make this one of West 's ever cuts . " Do Something " is a Godly kick in the face of any couch potato complainer who is frustrated that God has done enough for humanity Despite the rollicking fun in this track , it never should crib us from the theological truth that we are God 's change agents . With his high energy performance and the propulsive nature of these pop songs , by the middle of the album one would wish for a quieter ( and tiresome especially towards the latter half of the disc . or two outside songs might easily simply elevate this problem . Other than this quibble , " Into the Light " is one of West 's best records to date . West never hides away from the brokenness of sin . But it is in the valley of our hurts , West brings us via these songs to appreciate how beautiful and high the mountains of God 's love are .

I will let everyone else debate the merits of the album . This review is for those eager to buy the album AND you are just a casual fan - I would go download . It is an incredible deal . The one thing the regular edition of the CD has going for it is the traditional jewel case . An easier to access CD that will not get worn down too easily . The Deluxe edition is in an annoying DigiPak - the type where you need to seriously wrestle with it to remove the disc without snapping it in half . The colorful booklet is stitched into the digipak case , which looks lovely , In an odd move , the side pocket Clearly , they are going after the tween girl demographic with this move , The main reason to go Deluxe is the 4 bonus tracks . You get " The Clock Was Ticking " - a Grand Ole Opry country romp that also recalls the lyrical pace of The Nails ' " 88 Lines for 44 Women " Who Died . " " Jacksonville " is an album highlight - a trippy number with a slinky beat and a chilling woven bass guitar line . " I Came Here To Get Over You " almost sounds like a great lost Weezer song and " Right Behind You " brings the album to a proper close with heavy wet synths . Overall - this album , even more than the b - sides comp " Sawdust " feels like a full - fledged Killers album . but were so sterile they left me little inspiration for repeat listens . Flamingo is much more warm and inviting , like Las Vegas luring headlights down Highway 15 in the dead of night .

summary: Another great album by Nikki Sixx and his Crue !!
reviewText: " This is going to hurt " is the second , brand new album by " Sixx A.M. " , the band of " Motley Crue " mastermind Much like its predecessor " The heroin diaries " , the new album is based on the auto - biographical book of the same name . On this second studio effort Nikki reunites with lead guitarist James Michael and lead singer DJ Ashba With a stable line up you can rightfully expect the same musical recipe of the debut . For that matter you get a rather modern version of Sleaze metal emphasizing instrumental melodies that matter you get a rather modern version of Sleaze metal emphasizing instrumental melodies and vocal harmonies with intriguing arrangements , often adding orchestral parts , acoustic backing instruments Above all , the end result is incredibly catchy , offering some of the most memorable hooks . Favourite tracks include " Help is on the way " , " This is going to hurt " , " Lies of the beautiful people " , " Live forever " and " Goodbye my dear friends " . Indeed " This is going to hurt " is another well arranged offering from Sixx 's band that definitely stands on its own regardless of whether the listener has actually read the book counterpart . that definitely stands on its own regardless of whether the listener has actually read the book counterpart . that makes the album an enjoyably listen from start to finish ; perhaps making one wish " This is going to hurt " is a must for any fan of Sleaze metal , " Motley Crue " , " Bad City "

summary: Slightly underwhelming debut album from a great talent.
reviewText: Ever since the release of the ultra - successful The Emancipation of MiMi , by Mariah Carey , it seems as though record labels are constantly overthinking things in order to get hits , especially who is truly talented on their hands , like Jennifer Hudson . why the best song Jennifer Hudson has ever recorded , the lovely " Stand Up , " is nowhere to be found here . Quite honestly , this is not the classic album I was expecting from such a talented woman . Still , there are some nice songs . " Spotlight " is probably the best thing on here ; it is light , but forceful , and its sparse production leaves ample room for Jennifer 's powerful The Timbaland - produced " Pocketbook " is pretty much the only moment on the album where she does not take herself so seriously , which makes it refreshing . and silly ( " do not make me hit you with my pocketbook " ) , but the track is almost ruined by Ludacris ' unnecessarily nasty rap . The Robin Thicke - penned " Giving Myself , " a simple and beautiful ballad , was a nice choice . The piano - laden " My Heart " is very catchy and an overall nice mid - tempo . " I am His Only Woman , " a duet with Fantasia , pays homage to Stax - era soul . " We Gon ' Fight " is standard Tank fare , but it is enjoyable . And the closer , a rendition of the gospel traditional " Jesus Promised Me A Home Over There , " shows her vocals at their best . The rest of the songs , I am afraid , are anything but satisfying and many of them are extremely trendy , meaning Luckily , Hudson 's voice elevates all of these from being embarrassingly bad , except on the biggest monstrosity : the duet with ... T - Pain , " What is Wrong ( Go Away ) . " " If This Is not Love " is a bit too pop for my tastes . Anyways , her addition , " You Pulled me Through " is pretty uninspiring . " Can not Stop the Rain " has a generally nice melody but the production is very stale . " Invisible " is not very exciting , either , And I am Telling You I am Not Going " was pretty unnecessary in my eyes , especially since I -- and probably the rest of America -- had grown tired of it by the time the Academy Awards came around . Contrary to what other reviewers are saying , " All Dressed Up In Love " is not included as a bonus track on the standard edition . As I said before , all this material is made better due to the simple fact or seven good tracks . and Clive Davis could have formulated a great tracklist . If you want an excellent new female R&B album , buy Jazmine Sullivan 's Fearless , because this just is not cutting it for me .

Ah , the Supreme Warbler ! She is to popular music what Florence Foster Jenkins was to classical . Were they parody ? Or unfortunate victims of a cruel and greedy commercial machine that used them up like oil There were , after all , musical satirists like Anna Russell who reeked havoc with their sonic exploits , but I only discovered them many years after I fell in love with Mrs. Miller . The former act was , in case some readers do not know it already , a gifted piano player / bandleader Paul Weston , and a supreme vocal stylist known in popular vocalist circles as a singer 's singer , Jo Stafford . They were best known as themselves , but forged a separate career in musical parody . What made me convulse with laughter when I was in the mood to listen to these two cutting up vinyl was the knowledge that bad singing is not easy , and Jo did it by singing sharp .   Try it . and sounds even more horrible ) . but it may help me to explain the appeal of Mrs. Miller to so many people . where I worked to Jonathan that is not funny . " You see I had previously turned him on to the giddy delights of Mrs. Miller . In prying my friend for answers as to and Darlene NOT funny , and Mrs. Miller roll - on - the - floor hysterical , I got an unexpected response . No , he said Mrs. Miller is like your grandmother singing your favorite popular songs to you , and maybe even some songs you hate . Somehow , she is innocent , charming , and yes , very , very funny . Whatever the True story , and you will read of several in these Amazon reviews , what the person called Mrs. Miller left us was a small body of crystalline comedic treasures . or may not have been exploited , or she may have exploited herself , who became immortal . Just listen to these miracles of concise humor and comic mistiming . How can you not laugh and love this woman all at the same time ? who is going to take " Sweet Pea , " " Catch A Falling Star " and " I have Got A Tiger By the Tail " seriously , anyway ? This music was ripe for a little destructive reinterpreting . Sorry , Nancy , Mrs. Miller 's is The Definitive Version . My one , small criticism of this nearly complete compilation is the omission of " Up , Up ( If you are a Mrs. Miller fan already , and Away , " you owe it to yourself to hunt down this delightful rarity ) . But perhaps the best moment on this particular collection is that high note in " Lover 's Concerto . " and as comedians , that they had a goof , enjoyed it , made some money , I do think they are funny , but in a very different way from how Mrs. Miller is funny . My coworker was right about one thing :   Mrs. Miller was Grandma . And you might laugh WITH her but never would you sneer at her face to face . No , you want to give her a hug , because somehow these crazy , one - of - a - kind creations exemplify the best that comedy has to offer . I completely disagree with those that laughing at Mrs. Miller 's music is cruel . I think Mrs. Miller might have understood , had she lived to witness her digital revival , that she had created something entertaining Nothing to be ashamed of there , and if her life was in some ways tragic , its legacy is not the least bit sad .

summary: THIS DESERVES ONE THOUSAND STARS--BRAVO, DAVID ARCHULETA !!!
reviewText:
There is no doubt in my mind that David Archuleta has lots of professional talent and this album stuns me with its high quality control holiday music ; David never misses a beat and that is wonderful . that is wonderful . and soul into this holiday album and it is very clear when I listen to this ; his ability to sing and express the complete range of human emotions is outstanding . The quality of the sound on this CD is excellent and I like the artwork as well . The album starts with " Joy to the World ; " David sings this with panache and the arrangement plays with the tempo and the keys to let David put his own stamp on this classic ballad ! that sounds like that of a much more seasoned entertainer ; his talent is quite natural and he also has the ability to go much , much further in his chosen profession which is truly exciting . " Angels We Have Heard on High " has a lush musical arrangement and David makes this shine with his fantastic singing . " O Come All Ye Faithful " has always been a favorite holiday tune of mine ; David Archuleta performs this with panache and he never let us go of a single superfluous note ! I love it . " Silent Night " gets a most sensitive treatment from David who delivers this to perfection -- " Silent Night " is definitely a highlight of this album ; and listen for David to do a superb job on " The First Noel . " " The First Noel " charms me with its natural beauty and David 's voice sounds like a finely tuned instrument as he sings this faultlessly . Charice Pempengco joins David for " Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas ; " this was first performed by Judy Garland in " Meet Me in Saint Louis . " and Charice make this ballad an outstanding highlight of the album . The somewhat jazzy arrangement fits perfectly with their vocals and I really like their rendition of " Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas . " It is heaven . " I will Be Home for Christmas " was my mother 's favorite holiday song ; and David does this justice ! He sings this passionately " Pat - A - Pan " is thrown in for a good effect ; David performs this very well and it is a good number . " What Child Is This " is another charmer that David aces as effortlessly as if it were mere breathing -- that easy . David 's talent carries him through . " Ave Maria " sounds just perfect ; and the album ends so well with David Archuleta performing " Melodies of Christmas . " " Melodies of Christmas " is a strong ending number for the album and it certainly leaves me wanting more ! 

 David Archuleta delivers on this holiday album and I am fantastically impressed . This is a must - have for David 's fans and it makes a great CD to add to any holiday music collection .

When the members of Baroness were involved in a serious tour bus accident in 2012 , it seemed like music would be the least of their concerns for a while . But just as time heals all wounds , so too does music . and in doing so , hunkered down with a new line - up of musicians to create a very personal comeback album . that spirit , " Purple " is indeed a re - birth for the band . While it still sounds unmistakingly Baroness - ish , there is a newfound sense of confidence that even the lofty heights of 2012 's ambitious double album , " Yellow & Green " did not quite capture , even if the band 's full capabilities are not fully explored . Truth be told , " Purple " sounds like the it belongs right in the middle of " Blue " ( their transitionary record ) and " Yellow & Green " ( their real breakthrough ) , and that is not a bad place to be . that is not a bad place to be . Injecting a bit more ruggedness into his delivery than on the last album , Baizley is at his most passionate and urgent and thankfully , the band -- rounded out by newcomers Nick Jost ( bass ) The album opens with the blistering " Morningstar , " bringing the band back to its roots . and complex slab of heavy rock , the tone for the rest of the album is set . The pace keeps chugging along with the emotionally charged " Shock Me , " a strong contender for the most powerful rock single released this ( past ) year . From there it gets a little spacier , with " Try To Disappear " starting with some sparse electronics that sound as if they were recorded underwater before rushing to the surface mid - way to show off an explosive rhythm section . The weight of the album culminates in its closing number , " If I Have to Wake Up ( Would You Stop the Rain ? ) , " a haunting semi - ballad sums up the album and the band 's experiences over the past three years in a nice and neat bow . With only nine proper tracks , " Purple " packs quite a wallop in such a short amount of time . that may bruise the Baroness faithful is the fact It is really just a powerful re - affirmation that end , it is certainly a satisfying listen even if it does not quite break new ground . The streamlined delivery ( not to mention the running time clocking in at just over 40 minutes ) makes it a powerful Considering these guys could very well have quit music altogether after all they have experienced these last couple of years , it is a miracle and still sounding this good . Here is hoping they keep it just as colorful from here on out .
