summary: Alabama Shakes present a more commerical outing with "Sound & Color"
reviewText: The state of Alabama has long been known as a hotbed of musical talent . Though most of Alabama 's talent tend to lend more toward country In recent years , there is been three American Idol contestants ( Ruben Studdard , Bo Bice , Taylor Hicks ) , Brent Hinds of the heavy metal act Mastodon The quartet is fronted by lead singer whose voice owes a huge debt to singers like Janis Joplin One member was asked to join while working at a local music store After working with a local record producer , they released an EP , played at a festival and even earned the band a Gold certification from the RIAA . but still remain True to their sound . They also took a   more direct approach to making a radio friendly record , which actually sounds better than their debut . where they are content with having a peace of mind . On the uptempo " Do not Want To Fight " , the song centers around a woman who wants to extend an olive branch to her partner to avoid their constant bickering . They think about the deceased on " Future People " , while Brittany sings of wanting to love someone dealing with personal issues on the first single " Give Me All Your Love " . They are content with having an ally on " This Feeling " , while being unsure about her feelings toward an ex on the ballad " Miss You " . Being optimistic toward a new relationship is the theme of the song " Gemini " , while they end the album with the ambient ballad " Over My Head " . " Sound & Color " is a great album by Alabama Shakes . Though it is radically different from its predecessor , it is a step forward from a band that seems to like making music their way . that seems to like making music their way . that frame of mind , expect to hear more great things from them in the near future .

It is a myth At least half a myth In the 1960s , it was True . when Stevie Wonder released Music Of My Mind in early 1972 , he proved soul LPs could work as cohesively as any rock LP .  There is the Philly Sound , there is ........ well , easy there , let us climb one mountain at a time . The lush horns , strings , vibes , and master vocals are wound into one massive , wonderful silk sheet of sound . Wagner would be proud

We heard this music next to Daddy Dewdrop 's " Chick - A - Boom , " and quickly ran to our King Crimson albums , unable to separate the prime rib from the beef jerky . Play part of Coltrane 's Love Supreme next to Bobby Goldsboro 's " Honey , " The blimp has crashed . and then go into " One Of A Kind Love Affair , " and it will be the start of a one of a kind love affair -- for you . Check out the third track , " Do not Let The Green Grass Fool You " I need not go into this , but it proves my point . Wow ! There is sooooo ... much to like in this album it is amazing . The music is mostly upbeat & very catchy -- making you want to ( & will if no one 's around ) sing along . The lyrics are fine , meaningful , & personally touching -- about life which is getting faster & faster in the contemporary world , while people are still people with hopes , feelings , needs , desires , & all the rest of what makes people human . The lead singer , Jennifer Nettles is powerful yet gifted with a sweet voice ( though a bit twangy in style ) . She grabs you quickly for a wild ride -- immersing the listener in the musical story she is telling . Then I heard Sugarland on the CMA show -- winning awards as they so deserve . The range & variety of the songs on the album are good too -- from sweet & poignant ballads to wild & spicy soaring . Virtually all of the songs are well worth listening to & the majority could become successful singles . Yes , the style is their own mixture of influences -- the 3 artists come from different musical backgrounds , which makes their wonderful blending are the more impressive . I wonder if they are unique ? Well , they are unique even if not in that respect -- how many bands include a mandolin ? . Of course , country purists may not be happy with them , This has become one of my favorite albums , at the speed of sound . IMHO , it is terrific .

summary: Very satisfied with the order and product
reviewText: Very satisfied with the order
Great

For such a " much anticipated " return to the recording studio by this legendary superband which dominated the radio in the 70 's which dominated the radio in the 70 's and 80 's , this effort falls short of expectations . While there are a number of highlight moments on this CD , including an energetic " 90 Degrees and Freezing " , a Motown - inspired , horn driven " Come to Me Do " and a catchy and powerful pop gem " Feel " ( all penned by all - time great songwriter Robert Lamm ) , the record suffers from an over - abundance of ballads and sorry , over - blown production . but I know what sounds good to my ears . but the ones on this Chicago album , the first recording of all - original material in 15 years , are simply not good , whether from a songwriting but will cite " King of Might Have Been " as an example of bassist Jason Scheff 's mostly able tenor painfully straining to hit notes out of his range . but the end result is a lot of tracks sounding like his own band , Rascal Flatts . No more to say as this speaks for itself . As confirmed by the band , DeMarcus was also responsible for choosing the material for the recording , and pushed aside many songs written by the band members in favor of the mostly trite fare and Bill Champlin have proven they can still pen solid pop / rock / R&B songs as found on their string of solo recordings , a CD of Chicago - only songs would , undoubtably been more listenable and a more worthy end product than what we hear on " XXX " . Finally , DeMarcus uses an army of studio musicians in place of the actual band members , thereby destroying any integrity this album would have had at least as a document of a Chicago band performance . " Chicago XXX " " could have been a contender " with a different approach to the CD 's production .

that the Spinners finally got the chance to breakthrough to a wide audience after years on Motown without any huge success . and a deal on Atlantic , they Spinners ' hard work finally paid off after years . This joint is surely a winner , with some heavy hitting mid - tempo soul jams . This one contains some legendary jams like the rolling funk of " I will Be Around " and " Could It Be I am Falling in Love " heavily laden with strings , a staple of Philly Soul . " I will Be Around " is one of my favorite soul jams of all time , and loving it in junior high school ( in the mid 90 's ) Rapper Rappin ' 4 - Tay also made his own version of it in 1994 , a wonderful hip - hop jam which took the funky rolling music Another one of my favorites here is " Just Me and You Baby , " a slower , ballad type jam with heavenly harmony . " Ghetto Child " is heavy mid - tempo jam exploring the bad side of growing up in the ` hood , very sad " How Could I Let You Get Away " is a sadder lyrically rich song laden with sitars later in the song . Phillipe Wynne , Bobbie Smith ( great singers ) , and company surely deliver a rich album full of lush Thom Bell production and sweet harmony and melody ; the transition from Detroit to Philly surely was a lucrative one . 1974 's Mighty Love is another wonderful soulful album as is 1975 's Pick of the Litter . The Spinners are definitely essential listening in order to truly experience what Philly Soul has to offer .

" that the group 's singer / songriter Ryan Bouvier had writer 's block . because Britney Spears ' songwriting team was brought in to write several songs , making Simple Plan sound like a boy band . when they try to rock out , the production is so overdone that the guitars seem distorted I think any trace of the faux - punk label they were slapped with after their first two albums , which were decent efforts packed with pop - punk hooks , can permanently be removed now . summary: The Long Lost Stevie Album That Never Was
reviewText:
" 24 Karat Gold ~ Songs From the Vault " is a newly recorded album by Stevie Nicks , however if you did not know better you would easily think this was a long lost album from Stevie . when Stevie was working on her " In Your Dreams " album she discovered one her lost demos , " Secret Love " , on YouTube . and she discovered lots more of her lost demos on YouTube As a long time fan , I have had these demos in my collection for years , when I heard what her plan was , I was skeptical . but the results have not always been great . Listen to her original demo for " Smile At You " , then check out the watered down released version on Fleetwood Mac 's " Say You Will " . Would she be able to recapture the magic in these original demos , or would the suffer the same fate of " Smile At You " and the inspiration behind the song is long forgotten . Another concern was her voice , it is aged a lot since the recording of the demos . but in nearly every case , outshine the demos . Among the highlights , the album kicks off with " Starshine " , this is a fun rocker that is a great album opener and would also be a killer opening song on stage . and the recording of the " Bella Donna " album right down to the organ solo . " Mabel Normand " is one of her more rare demos , the song tells the tale of the long forgotten actress and like " Thousand Days " that is not a bad thing . The album 's title " 24 Karat Gold " was a demo From the opening lone bass riff , One of my favorites from the album , " Belle Fleur " is another of the demos but once again , Stevie has transformed the song into a gem . that hooks you just before the song has it is proper start . I also like the banjo heard throughout the song . " All The Beautiful Worlds " is a great song period . It is got a haunting tone that has a very definite late 70's / early 80 's feel to it . Again here Stevie 's vocals sound as strong and vibrant as they did in the 80 's . and Lori providing their background vocals , the song is classic Stevie . 
  " Lady " was known for years among fans as " Knocking On Doors " . Her voice has aged to perfection here . With " I Do not Care " Stevie rocks out . The music track was written by Tom Petty guitarist Mike Campbell Stevie has said the end of the song lyrically was made up on the spot , honestly the whole song lyrically sounds improvised , but it works . " Watch Chain " written about Mick Fleetwood in the late 70 's has retained much of the feel of the original demo . I have always liked this one " Hard Advice " is the sister song to 2001 's " That Made Me Stronger " , two songs written about the same conversation . In this case a conversation Stevie had with Tom Petty . This is a beautiful track . because it was one of Stevie 's late mother 's favorites . " Blue Water " is something of holy grail song among fans , written by Stevie with Sharon Celani back in the late 70 's . I never cared for the demo , but once again the song has come alive here . She is helped out on this one with Lady Antebellum . As with " I Do not Care " Stevie musically is trading new ground here , the song is given a jazzy treatment along with dixieland horns . Yes , it works . " The Dealer " has long been one of my favorites , one can assume it was one of Stevie 's favorites as well , as she has recorded several demos of this . This version is slowed down a bit from the 1970 's demo , and some of the excitement from the original demo is missing . However if you have never heard the demo , then there is much to like here . Closing out the album is " She Loves Him Still " , another track she is attempted a few times . Some do not like the woodwind on this , I think it fits the song . and she has moved on from whatever inspired her , but yet she sings it as if it was inspired just yesterday . yet she sings it as if it was inspired just yesterday . She is right , she is moved on In every way though these are classic Stevie songs . This is very much the most pure Stevie album we have ever gotten . Looking back on these songs now , the heartbreak that inspired them has healed and now the songs are allowed to shine . In some ways this does not feel like a new album at all , it seems almost like a greatest hits album . At the same time it IS a new album filled with classic Stevie moments .
A classic that ages well !

The Dead returned from Egypt and played five nights at Winterland Arena . and I Need A Miracle give the hometown crowd a preview of two new songs . I Got My Mojo Working is a good version coming out of space with War 's Lee Oscar filling in on harp . The Other One is massive before flowing into one of the best Stella Blues out there . Sugar Magnolia is a nice set ender following on the heels of Stella while YOU.S. Blues is a fitting encore . The second disc recorded on the 22nd , features Egyptian percussionist Hamza El Din and his choir on Ollin Arageed before leading into Deal . Next up is a sweet Peggy - O followed by a hot Jack Straw . The Scarlet Begonias->Fire On The Mountain is hot followed by an equally impressive Not Fade Away->Going Down The Road Feeling Bad with legendary guitarist John Cipollina guesting on the last half of the release . The bonus disc is made up of four songs from the 21st with the last two from 10 - 17 - 78 .

summary: Surprisingly Good Performances At An Unbeatable Price
reviewText: and it was well worth it . The main attraction here are the symphonies . Recorded by BIS in exceptional sound , and featuring the Swedish Chamber Orchestra under Thomas Dausgaard , this is one of the liveliest Schumann cycles one could ever hope to hear . The tempos are swift throughout , but the playing is crystal clear Personally , I like an even - weightier account of this music . I like my brass to sound regal , rather than punchy . But one can not deny that the orchestral playing is super , that the choirs are all well balanced , that the voicings are superb and that the musical gestures one expects are made , if at a quicker tempo than one is used to hearing . that the musical gestures one expects are made , if at a quicker tempo than one is used to hearing . This is a great cycle for those who find Schumann to be lugubrious and a MUCH cheaper way to acquire the cycle than through buying it on CD at $ 14 a pop . Major piano pieces are also included , also in excellent sound . The rest of the set is good , though I wonder Highly recommended at 10 times the price .

Jazmine Sullivan returns with her sophomore album Love Me Back and it is an outstanding effort . With a voice reminiscent of Mary J. Blige in terms of pure passion It is arguably her greatest song to date . When she is singing about pain such as the second single 10 Seconds , she has She is easily one of the most soulful artists to emerge in the past 5 years . True soul music . that premise with song after song of great arrangements , soulful singing , and great lyrics . and Ne - Yo serves as the only guest on the duet YOU Get On My Nerves . The only songs I am not really feeling are Love You Long Time & Redemption , not because they are horrible songs it is just that I am not really feeling their vibe . Jazmine Sullivan comes through with another solid effort that showcases her talents and is thoroughly enjoyable . She is a True talent in music and this album is worth a purchase as it has powerful songs with plenty of replay value . Then there is that jewel written by Doyle Lawson , Charlie Waller That song alone is worth the price of this reasonably priced three CD pack . This remains one of my favorite bluegrass songs ever . I have Emmy singing it solo , Garrison Keillor and the Hopeful Gospel Quartets version and the Hopeful Gospel Quartets version My vote for best arrangement will always be the one by the San Francisco group Chanticleer . This a cappella group of twelve men do something magic with this song for almost seven ethereal minutes . The trios version ( a cappella of course ) certainly is a close second . summary: John Fogerty re-revisits his musical roots
reviewText: When John Fogerty cut the original Blue Ridge Rangers LP in 1973 , it stood firmly as a work separated from his run with Creedence Clearwater Revival . A year from the band 's breakup , Fogerty immersed himself in musical roots with an album of covers , mostly country and gospel , played Even the album 's cover echoed the solo theme , with Fogerty silhouetted as each of the fictional group 's five members . which many of his own songs were built , could not help but point to his previous work . More importantly , rather than layering his own instrumental and vocal performances in the studio , Fogerty 's put together an actual Blue Ridge Rangers with the talents of guitarist Buddy Miller , steel / mandolin / dobro player Greg Leisz , drummer Kenny Aranoff He is also chosen to share the microphone with Eagles Don Henley and Timothy B. Schmit on Rick Nelson 's " Garden Party , " When Will I Be Loved . that drops the unfortunate mid-80s production of Eye of the Zombie 's original . There are classic country tunes from Ray Price , Buck Owens but Fogerty also reaches to fellow singer - songwriters John Prine , Rick Nelson and favorites from Delaney & Bonnie , Pat Boone and the 1964 Jumpin ' Gene Simmons R&B novelty , " Haunted House . " that is adds a bit of Neil Young - like reediness to the original . Fogerty sounds relaxed and the husk of his voice adds an element of solemn pain and earthen soul to Pat Boone 's melodramatic death ballad , " Moody River . " When Will I Be Loved " Though it is more of a lark than an artistic summit , it is great to hear two modern icons wailing away at their shared roots . That really sums up Fogerty 's decision to bring the Blue Ridge Rangers back to life , as it is an opportunity for a great artist to revel in his equally great influences .

The first new studio album in five years from Grammy Award - winning Texas guitar hero Eric Johnson has finally arrived , and well worth the wait . Like his other CDs a mix of instrumentals and showcasing his unique virtuosity on the electric guitar , Up Close includes some of the best work The album is dripping with crackling guitars . If a guitar died and went to heaven , this is what heaven would sound like . Johnson is on fire , effortlessly weaving incredible , sparkling solos in and out of both the instrumental The vocal songs range from energetic blues and rock numbers to gorgeous , heartfelt ballads . Inspired like never before , Johnson plays and sings with a fervor not present in his previous work . Perhaps Johnson is like a fine vintage wine , improving with age . That was the year Johnson , then 36 years old , released his breakthrough second album , Ah Via Musicom , which achieved the distinction of having three instrumental songs reach the American Top Ten . As accomplished and groundbreaking as Ah Via Musicom and sonically more expansive 1996 follow - up , Venus Isle , are , Johnson has really poured his living , breathing essence into Up Close . The result is the best guitar - based album of the last several years , and one of the best guitar - based With Up Close , Johnson is at the top of his game as a guitarist , composer , He has created a masterwork of soulful jazz / pop / rock fusion that exudes passion , especially through his trademark virtuosic guitar sound . and Sonny Landreth , the album is clearly all Eric Johnson up close front

summary: Evolution of the Classical Era Violin Concerto
reviewText: A member of one of the most famous families from Bohemia , Franz Benda ( 1709 - 1789 ) entered into the service of Frederick the Great in 1732 . As a violin master , he played some 50,000 performances over a forty year period . and string dominated orchestral support . As a transitional work from the Baroque , it contains more interplay between the single violin Smoothly flowing , Bendas writing for the solo string is virtuosic without being showy , letting the melodic lines develop naturally . In the minor keyed Largo , the sweep of the orchestral accompaniment lends a somber weight to the throbbing vibrato of Gabriela Demeterova . With a dramatic pathos in the uppermost register , she brings a sorrowful sweetness in her tone that set apart Bendas adagio playing . Horns appear for the brisk finale , a bright Allegro with bravura fiddling as the single violin drifts high on the E string . and theology in Prague before accepting a musical directorship in Milan . and died while playing a violin concerto at the Lobkowitz Palace . 3 , No . 1 opens with a marching Allegro sostenuto , clipped and precise . While still employing the harpsichord as continuo , the writing finds even greater collaboration between the soloist and orchestra , engaging in extensive rhythmic interactions and trading melodic ideas , including one haunting echo in minor . A minor keyed charmer , the following Adagio finds striking support in the lower strings with a lovely countermelody while the ethereal vibrato of the solo sounds so much like the beating of angel wings . Ending the 2nd movement on an open cadence sets up a smooth transition as the resolution occurs in the sweetly pure tones from the violin , the very first notes of the concluding Rondo . Interrupting the relentless drive in the lower strings , a brief passage in minor offers a dark interlude in an otherwise cheery finale . Renowned as a teacher and violin virtuoso , Antonin Vranicky ( 1761 - 1820 ) composed some outstanding chamber music and challenging concertos , one of and winds to create a broader palette of orchestral colors , the work begins with a bold Allegro giusto . Amid a longer , more extensive development section , the soloist shines in the fiendishly difficult passage work while in the reverential Adagio that follows , the writing stretches the upper reaches of the instruments register . After a chorale like start , the weeping violin carries the movement until gentle horns lead to a serene close . Marked Alla Pollacca- Allegretto , the finale is a frisky Polish folk dance . With an appealing stutter step in the rhythm , this 3rd movement features a brief mournful interlude , dazzling flourishes from the violin The original recording from 1995 from Supraphon is fine , placing the solo violin close enough for the intimate slower sections to be sharp and clear . Under the able artistic direction of Milan Lajcik , the Prague Chamber Orchestra brings an accomplished reading to their fellow countrymens concertos . But the spotlight rightfully belongs to the exquisite work of Gabriela Demeterova . This fine traversal of the development of the Viennese violin concerto is testimony to her artistry .

The album starts off fine with " Good As Gone . " This song , while drowning in commercial pop country lyrics , stands apart from most modern country due to the nice four - part harmony of the group . Another standout from this album is their other radio release , " Bring It On Home . " In fact , this is probably the strongest song on the album . " Wounded " has a nice sound as well .   Songs like " Bones , " " A Little More You , " and " Looking For A Reason , " are good , The only glaring downfall in this album is the hokey , pop country drivel , " Welcome To The Family . " It falls into the same category as other silly tunes like " American Honky Tonk Bar Association , " that the songwriter tries too hard to make a cheesy country tune . If you enjoy earthy , mostly acoustic four - part harmony , you will enjoy this album . who likes glitzier country groups like Rascal Flatts will probably like this , though it is quite a bit grittier than the bland Flatts sound . Fans of bluegrass - tinged groups such as Diamond Rio and even the Nitty Gritty Dirt Band will probably enjoy this much more . Overall , a highly recommended album , though Little Big Town has not quite set themselves apart from the crowd .

summary: Easily a 5-star album... one of the best of 2002 no question
reviewText: ' The Soul Purpose ' was an exceptionally good release from 7L & Eso that was really unfairly hated upon . It was a 20 track CD filled with a lot of good songs ( " Speaking Real Words " " Jealous Over Nothing " , accompanied by some average tracks ( " You Know The Concept " " Mic Mastery " ) , that well ( " Guestlist " ) ... It probably was hated upon because of Eso 's previous cyborg - android scientific type of material switched over to a cocky arrogant battler with simpler rhyming schemes . Where ever there were mistakes on ' The Soul Purpose ' , ' Dangerous Connection ' not only corrects them , but PERFECTS everything on the album ! 7L 's mediocre production has improved exponentially and Esoteric 's flow just compliments the beats even more . that there was too much battle type of material on the last album , ' Dangerous Connection ' comes with a bunch of good conceptual songs ... " Terrorist 's Cell " - first off ANYTHING produced by Stoupe ( jedi mind tricks ) will have an off the wall type of beat . Esoteric 's lyrics explain the mind of a 9/11 terrorist going through with his crusade ... This is not only a controversial song , but it is executed INCREDIBLY well ( the re - play button will be on this for a few times ) ... " Word Association " - another creative track where Esoteric raps about being a psychotic patient rapping ' word association ' with a doctor . A very humorous track ... " Stalker " - a hilarious tale about a guy that he has fantasies of ... this runs along the same type of humor " Jealous over Nothing " had ... and Nelly fans , herbs are something else I detest . Esoteric arrogantly defines the term herb all throughout the track ... " Rest In Peace " - a clever concept song and how there are album profit problems among his family and friends ... And the rest of the tracks are the usual Esoteric battle / android type of material ... NOTHING on this material is WEAK by any means ( there are no blunders like Guestlist ) ... that annoyed me about this CD is that it was kind of short in comparison with Soul Purpose . But the REALLY hot beats support underground hiphop

summary: Review excerpt from Music and Media Focus
reviewText: Tim 's music is something he characterizes as " instrumental pop , " which reflects influences from new age , rock , popular , Right from the opening track , a blend of distinctive melody and impressive technique is evident . Although the track , entitled " What Will I Be , " is barely over 2 minutes long , it feels like a complete composition and exhibits a surprising dynamic range in its brief lifespan . but like a buffet of extremely rich food , small portions are just right . By the end you certainly feel like you have had a very full listening experience , given the intricacy Although the piano is the centerpiece of the album , lush orchestration tastefully compliments the compositions . and rock influences combine on " Awaken The Dawn , " in a virtuoso high velocity piece that brought to mind the keyboard wizardry of progressive rockers like Rick Wakeman of Yes , A nice contrast to this style is a tune called " Hopefaith , " which showcases the more gentle side of Tim 's playing , yet also exhibits his dynamic range within the boundaries of a song . I was impressed with Tim 's abilities as a composer and arranger , as well as with how much detail and complexity he was able to imbue in some of his relatively compact compositions . A song entitled " Hide And Seek " is built on a simple descending motif , providing a platform for lavish orchestration to add to the cinematic air . I appreciated that Tim chose to end the album with one of his most sensitive compositions , " Stratford Road . " This was the perfect one to provide closure after a CD 's worth of intricate , and often intense piano virtuosity . This piece had a pleasant pastoral quality that I found emotionally evocative . In general , the music on this album lends itself more to active listening , than background ambience . Timothy Crane has crafted a spirited mlange of diverse ingredients

George Benson 's Breezin ' was a landmark album in jazz music . that made it appealing to a mass audience who necessarily did not like the genre . The album hit number one on the Top 200 & r&b charts and stayed at number one on the jazz charts for over a year . The album was spurred on by Mr. Benson 's smooth and elegant cover of " This Masquerade " which peaked at number 10 and went on to win the 1976 Grammy for Record of the Year . that great track , the album had five other gems including the appropriately titled title track which has a light , airy Latin vibe , the straight jazz of " Six To Four " The remastered version contains three additional tracks including a great song , " Shark Bite "

summary: unearthed a vein of musicology that revealed to the world undiscovered works by great composers, and new scholarship about the w
reviewText: Even for the most ardent and knowledgeable fan of the Bach Guild / Vanguard catalog , this collection might be a bit of a surprise . Certainly this collection shows the trademarks of the early 1950s era Bach Guild catalog , as the repertoire leans toward the baroque and classical masters . that kept a small classical label alive . and winds came as a small surprise although it started as a tribute to a forgotten corner of the catalog . Some history   the post World War II time frame for The Bach Guild chronicles a richly fertile artistic period , The scholarly rage that followed the end of the war , that had been off limits for over twenty years , unearthed a vein of musicology that revealed to the world undiscovered works by great composers , and new scholarship about the works once thought well known . and the difficult post - war conditions gave them inexpensive access to musicians in one of the great music cities in the world . and local scholars eager to test their new discoveries and a city of starving musicians , The Bach Guild produced a vault of recordings of considerable artistic breadth . And with a city of fine musicians all looking for work , performing this repertoire was not difficult , as any combination of instruments could be matched easily and asked to create Austro - Vanguard , and make a guaranteed number of recordings . From existing letters , neither brother was very excited by the idea , as they did not want the issues that came with running a studio thousands of miles away ( they did not want own their own studio in the US either ) , and they figured they could work something out to get just what they wanted instead of a flood of recordings and the Viennese recording team was free to make recordings at their own , and Vanguard would have rights of refusal . Thus were made many Vienna State Opera Orchestra recordings , as well as the early recordings of the Concentus Musicus Wien . That defines a large number of recordings in the Vanguard catalog . In order to exploit this wide array , the Solomons hit on the idea of the Virtuoso series , So the Vanguard catalog has a series of Virtuoso recordings : Trumpet ( 3 volumes ) , Oboe ( 4 volumes and an orphan ) ; Flute ( 3 recordings ) ; Guitar ( 2 recordings but that was not part of the original series . that was not part of the original series . We Have combined recordings from trumpet , oboe , clarinet and recorder , as well as some other recordings featuring the horn but in the attempt to create a box that did not tilt too heavily in the direction of the reed instruments ( yes , four oboe recordings , with almost 4 hours of oboe repertoire seems a bit much for one box ) , we shaved a few recordings off this list , that we have included are making their digital debut and most of them have gone unheard for a while   Vanguard collectors will remember a bad attempt at lifestyle compilations called Music for People and most of them have gone unheard for a while   Vanguard collectors will remember a bad attempt at lifestyle compilations called Music for People Who Hate Opera that included the romantic era oboe recordings as well as the Wagner clarinet work ( see belowhint : there is been a bit of a change regarding that work ) . But all of the trumpet and recorder works are getting their digital debuts with this release . Most of the trumpet repertoire was released on CD A few points   at the request of some of our Facebook friends , we have included the recording of the Haydn oboe concerto , that because scholarship has cast some doubt on whether this piece is by Haydn . because scholarship has cast some doubt on whether this piece is by Haydn . because it certain does feature the oboe . Also , the well - regarded Virtuoso Clarinet recording featuring Jack Brymer is included here , And this leaves us with the embarrassment of riches problem   this box could have been three hours longer ! Thank you Vienna ! Thank you !

I was fortunate to receive an advanced copy of Fly from Here the new album by Yes , and it is a masterpiece ! and is a pleasure to listen to . Trevor Horn ex - lead singer for Yes is once again with the band as strictly a producer / cowriter , and the product is brilliant . Note : ( Trevor Horn replaced Jon Anderson as lead vocalists in the band for the Drama album exclusively , as well as the tour in support of the album ) . This release also marks the debut of Benot David the new lead singer for Yes , and I have to say I am extremely impressed with his vocals . David appears to sometimes sound a bit like Anderson , but more like Horn , so much so That in fact is not far from the truth , as the title track " Fly from Here " an epic six part piece is based on a demo from 1980 entitled " We Can Fly from Here " . Having expanded the demo track into the epic it now is was a fantastic idea , and it works mainly due to Benot David 's vocal similarity to Trevor Horn . The other five tracks are primarily stand - alone tunes and are beautifully written Rejoining Yes for Fly from Here is and Geoff is at the top of his game , and is refreshing to hear performing at his progressive rock peak . Yes members Chris Squire , Alan White , This album signifies a new beginning for Yes , and brings us some closure from the days of Drama ( one of my favorite albums ) , as well as opening the future for the band building on the Drama sound that we as Yes fans never got , and although many fans may refuse to accept any other singer then Jon Anderson , get over it ! although many fans may refuse to accept any other singer then Jon Anderson , get over it ! Change can be a good thing , and in the case of Fly from Here an exceptional musical experience !

Excellent followup for Robert Randolph and the Family Band 's underground classic " Live at the Wetlands . " who liked that CD will be pleased with this one . that this excellent group has been performing live over the last year , like " Run For Your Life , " " Good Times , " Once again , John Ginty plays the heck out of his organ and Danyel Morgan in fine support ( though it would be nice if this one had more of Danyel 's soaring vocals ) . Overall , this is good stuff , particularly the songs and go music with a positive energy not often found in tunes of recent times . " Soul Refershing " is simply beautiful and " Smile " is interesting ( Robert 's sister Lenesha does the vocals here ) . " Calypso " ( not to be confused with the Harry belafonte tune of the same name ) is an interesting novelty . A few of the songs ( like " I Need More Love " ) are somewhat lacking in the right mix of melody and energy but a so - so song from these guys are better than the best of a lot of what is out there now ! who may be interested in this start with " Live at the Wetlands " before going on to " Unclassified . " That will give you a better preperation for this . and   you will have hope for the future of American popular music .

Yes , this has already been covered by numerous other reviewers here , but I truly believe ' Confident ' is Demi Lovato 's best work to date ! On her 5th album , Lovato reveals a sexy side unheard of / unseen on her previous records . On ' Confident ' , Demi struts her stuff in these playful , care - free ( yet more mature ) tracks . Needless to say , she does not give a rat 's a-- what people think of her . Reviewer Justin Alvis wrote : " I am glad she finally made an explicit album too ( it was about time haha ) " [ original review posted October 19 , 2015 ] ... Yes , an explicit album from Lovato has been long overdue (: So glad to see she is finally broken away from the Disney mold for good ! 

 Tracklist / notable things : 

 1 . Confident - Great album opener ! The use of horns give the song a nice touch . ok , do not ask (:   Lovato taunts the double entendre : " It is time to get the chains out / Cool For The Summer - critics have compared this song to Katy Perry 's " I Kissed A Girl " ( not just in theme , but song structure as well ) . True , while " CFTS " is basically Katy 's song in a different key , that does not make " Summer " bad ... nice to see Lovato returning to her pop - rock roots w/ this one . 3 . Old Ways - interesting beats For You - sounds like an update of Miley Cyrus ' " Wreckingball " 

 5 . Stone Cold - shows off Lovato 's arresting vocals ... good Lord , the girl has some serious pipes ! 6 . Kingdom Come ( feat . Iggy Azalea ) - some stated this as the album 's worst track ... but it is my favorite ! Perhaps Iggy 's presence caused dislike ? This Lovato / Azalea collaboration turned out very ... interesting . I like it ! Hope it is a single ! Waitin For You ( feat . Sirah ) - a supposed - Miley Cyrus diss track . Loving the chorus ! 8 . Wildfire - beautiful song ! whom I assume Lovato shared a close bond with ) Unfortunately , it is the album 's weakest track . Demi 's vocals sound strained here ; pushing her voice too hard / over singing . This song could have been so much more ... unfortunately , Lovato 's boisterous vocal delivery falls flat . Yes - gorgeous mid - tempo gospel - tinged tune 

 11 . An emotional song that finds Lovato reflecting on her rocky relationship with her estranged [ now late ] biological father . A beautiful album closer . It is ok . Nothing special though 

 13 . that recalls Lovato 's own " Behind Enemy Lines " ( bonus track off her debut ) . Cool For The Summer ( Jump Smokers Remix ) Cool For The Summer ( Suraci Remix )

Sultry soulful UK singer / songwriter / guitarist Lianne La Havas released her critically acclaimed debut " Is Your Love Big Enough " in 2012 . Since then , she is become friends with , Her new album " Blood " appears largely unaffected by Opening cut " Unstoppable " sets the tone for much of the album , a slice of dewy Marvin Gaye - esque soul . And Gold " , lyrics that touch on the confusion her mixed heritage brought while growing up . With a voice capable of moving from a breathy whisper to a powerful belter as on the tender acoustic to fiery " Grow " or " Midnight " ( laced with triumphant horns and hip hop beats ) , each of the ten tracks is special . " Tokyo " is a moody groove with heavenly harmonies and a mournful / squealing guitar break , while the dreamy " Wonderful " is aptly titled , adorned with finger - snaps , sprinklings of strings " Never Get Enough " is the surprise on the album , a delicate acoustic affair sporadically interrupted with bursts of fuzzy guitar and disembodied vocals giving an indie rock feel . and folky " Good Goodbye " . Sends pleasant chills running through the blood . Another winner from La Havas .

I was expecting great things when I first bought ` There is Know Place Like Home , ' but the sheer quality of this DVD came as quite a surprise to me . The picture is amazing ; simply brilliant with a really spectacular job in both editing and camera work which makes the DVD just so enjoyable to watch . The sound is unbelievable ; one of the best concert recordings I have come across , the concert boasts one of the greatest live drum sounds ever captured , with a huge ` feel the air particles moving , ' kick drum sound , a clear sharp snare sound and perfectly mixed cymbals . where rock bands play with an orchestra and I honestly believe this concert implemented the idea the best , working to augment the material instead of dominating it . The stage looks fantastic and the lighting is really impressive , giving the whole show a really epic atmosphere , appropriate during material like the ` Howling at the Moon , ' section of ` Magnum Opus , ' or the very grand ` Miracles Out of Nowhere . ' Then on top of all that , the tracklisting is excellent , paying particular focus to the classic era ; all the fan favourites are here from radio legends ` Point of Know Return , ' ` Dust In The Wind , ' and ` Carry On Wayward Son , ' to prog masterpieces like ` Song For America , ' ` Cheyenne Anthem , ' The bands performance throughout is amazing , from the incredibly intricate drumming on the proggier numbers , to the soulful singing on the ballads Steve Walsh 's vocal performance on ` The Wall , ' is pretty breathtaking that before even considering the violin work . that into account then remember there is a top notch symphony orchestra The Bonus Track , an extended version of the classic ` Down The Road , ' recorded in the soundcheck is particularly energetic and impressive . If you enjoy concert DVDs or are a Kansas fan then you can not afford to be without ` There is Know Place Like Home , ' in terms of performance , picture and sound this is simply one of the best DVDs out there .

' 2009 's underwhelming selling Untitled (a solid , Grammy - nominated R&B album ) found Kelly assimilating to new trends and rehashing classic moments . 2010`s Love Letter , on the other hand , finds Kelly on the more ` reserved ' side . That said , Love Letter is a solid , enjoyable R. Kelly album , sexual , profane references No one would cite ` Love Letter ' as Kelly 's best necessarily , but it is certainly one of his stronger effort in recent times . Critics who prefer the more overt , ` over - the - top ' persona will no doubt consider this album ` too tame ' or even ` bland . ' After the typical ` corny ' R. Kelly interlude ( " Love Letter Prelude " ) which finds the singer ascending up a scale in thirds at one point , Kelly breaks into the pleasant , enjoyable " Love Letter , " which is a direct contrast to the ` party - it - up ' themed " Crazy Night " from ` Untitled . ' yet memorable : " Did you get my card / did you read my love letter/ did it touch your heart / when you read my love letter . " Subtle it may be , Kelly sounds solid and " Love Letter " proves an appropriate , enjoyable opener . " Number One Hit " keeps up the feel - good , low - key vibe . Kelly 's vocals sit atop the restrained production well , supported by strings ( pads ) , piano , The dramatic turn of the performance at the end is a very nice touch making " Number One Hit " feel like a genuine ` hit . ' " Not Feeling The Love " is nearly as enjoyable , featuring the archetypical electric - piano laden production not dissimilar from 1980s R&B. Kelly barely breaks a sweat on the verse , but heightens the emotion near the end of the cut . " Lost In Your Love " is solid enough , though it is a cut where you would like for Kelly to ` push himself ' more as a songwriter . Even though it is safe and could stand more direction , it is still enjoyable and by no means ` filler . ' " Just Can not Get Enough " is a better cut , clocking in at an incredibly brief 3:10 . The only quibble would be limited songwriting , but much like " Lost In Your Love , " it still remains a pleasant cut . " Taxi Cab " does a fine job of differentiating itself from anything Kelly has done up to this point . While " Taxi Cab " does fall into the ` hole ' of employing some of modern R&B 's ` bag of gimmicks , ' Kelly makes the end result one that is much more positive than negative . Again working with a narrow scope of songwriting , Kelly makes this cut exciting , if for nothing else than comparing the ` taxi cab ' to the ` hotel room . ' " Radio Message " is one of the album 's best and most dynamic cuts , changing the groove from a straightforward four patter to a six feel , channeling classic R&B ( think 50 's When A Woman Loves " keeps up this ` Kelly transformation , ' finding ` Kells ' achieving some excellent vocal nuances . The biggest quibble is When A Woman Loves " is too lengthy , clocking in at over five minutes . " Love Is " featuring K. Michelle keeps the momentum high , with the only quibble being the questionable vocal mix ( K. Michelle could be mixed a bit closer to the forefront of the mix ) . " Just Like That " lays well , though " Music Must Be A Lady " is most definitely a show stopper ! that he has the most success as a songwriter ? The best line - " Hey sweet soprano , I want you to meet Mr. tenor ... " " A Love Letter Christmas " is appropriately place in a timely manner for the holidays , while closer " How Do I Tell Her " ends the album as strongly as it began . Essentially , Kelly ` knocks it out of the park ' on this effort , albeit more conservative than say his Twelve Play albums or " Trapped in the Closet " with it is millions of chapters . ` Love Letter ' is a must for any R. Kelly fan .

summary: A solid, if mediocre, album from one of country's best.
reviewText: Gary Allan is one of the few saving graces left in country music . and age of auto - tuned superstars , it is nice to see a country rocker who likes it rough and imperfect . Allan has already crafted two of the best country albums of modern times ( SMOKE RINGS IN THE DARK and TOUGH ALL OVER ) , and every album he releases is a reason to rejoice . That being said , for a Gary Allan record , GET OFF ON THE PAIN does not quite stand up . It is good -- note the 4 stars . It is just not as good as it could have been . There is genuine emotion behind such tunes as " She Gets Me , " " Kiss Me but it never quite reaches the level it should . Allan is in fine form throughout , whether he is rocking ( the charging " or dipping into ballad territory ( " Today , " " No Regrets " ) . and Greg Droman lay the strings on a little too thick in spots ; stellar songs such as " I Think I have Had Enough " and " Today " suffer to a degree from this . There is a definite power pop / rock leaning here , which is not as bad a thing as it sounds -- Allan has the heart , voice , It makes you kind of miss the honky - tonk of his first two releases , and the bluesy traditional country of SMOKE RINGS ... but we are really splitting hairs here . GET OFF ON THE PAIN is far from Allan 's best , but damned if it is not a heart - felt country / rock record , far , far superior to what else is out there these days .

summary: Eric Benet gets back to basics on "The One"
reviewText: Although it is hard to fathom , He lended his talents as a background singer on Michael Franks ' 1993 album " Dragonfly Summer " , which lead to him signing with Franks ' label Warner Bros. Records . While recording his debut , he endured the tragedy of his girlfriend dying in a car accident . In 1996 , he released his debut " True To Myself " , which featured the quiet storm favorites " Let us Stay Together " Three years later , he issued his most successful album to date " A Day In The Life " . While he was recording his next album , his career suffered another setback : His album " Better And Better " ended up being shelved . that was mostly produced by soft rock mavens David Foster He got back on track with 2008 's " Love & Life " and released what came to be his final recording for Warner Bros. , 2010 's " Lost In Time " . and George Nash , Jr.- the same producers behind " True To Myself " , " Love & Life " , " Lost In Time " where he pines for the return of a lost love . and celebrates the concept of finding happiness on " Real Love " . He sings about his once neverending search for Mrs. Right on " Runnin ' " and gets help from Lil ' Wayne on the potentially controversial " Redbone Girl " . He experiments with a couple of other genres , such as reggae on the Shaggy featured " Hope That It is You " , jazz on the innuendo laced " Come Together " and country music on the hidden bonus track " Come Home To Me " . Overall , Eric Benet 's " The One " is a strong recording from the neo - soul stalwart . While he does step out of his comfort zone on a few songs , he still sticks to what he does best .

summary: Six Pack: Volume 2 -- a top notch album from Straight No Chaser
reviewText: Straight No Chaser always impresses me with their incredible ability to deliver a cappella renditions of classic songs and ballads -- they put their own stamp on them with their remarkable harmonizing and the members of the group never miss a beat ! They possess a keen sense of timing , excellent diction and sophisticated phrasing and this CD is no exception ! but everything we get here is top notch , high quality control singing " Get Ready " is quite dynamic and Straight No Chaser performs this with lots of energy right from their hearts It all works well , too -- I love the sounds of their version of this song ! " Like a Prayer , " a song I first heard by Madonna , gets the royal treatment from Straight No Chaser and I really like this number . Michael Jackson 's " Billie Jean " ( mixed with " Poison " ) shows their ability to do a two song medley with panache and listen for yet another gem of a two song medley with " Rhythm of Love / Cannot Help Falling in Love . " yet another gem of a two song medley with " Rhythm of Love / Cannot Help Falling in Love . " " Buddy Holly " is most impressive and the album ends strong with " Let us Get It On . " Awesome ! Straight No Chaser again proves they have the vocal chops to remain a fine a cappella group for however long they wish to be performing together -- however long they wish to be performing together -- and hopefully for us I highly recommend this album .

Herman 's Hermits were nearly as successful as The Beatles and also made the American breakthrough . that I saw as a kid ( Ms Brown You have Got A Lovely Daughter was one of those movie hits , the daughter in question being the puppy of a racing dog if I remember correctly ! ) . What set them apart , was the lovely harmony vocals and the British accent ; unlike most , they never affected an American or even mid - Atlantic accent in their catchy music . This excellent collection includes all of their greatest hits , taking the listener down memory lane to revisit the innocence of the 60s with glorious pop songs like I am Into Something Good , Sleepy Joe and humorous ditties like I am Hennery The Eighth I Am . My personal favourites include No Milk Today , There is A Kind Of Hush , My Sentimental Friend , Years May Come , Years May Go and therefore were not taken as seriously as some of their contemporaries , therefore were not taken as seriously as some of their contemporaries , but time has been kind to their music - compared to a lot of today 's chart stuff , this is a classic , timeless sound . This album will appeal to everyone who loves clever , tuneful pop performed with feeling and intelligence .

summary: Don't miss this wonderful--and really unusual--album of Christmas masterworks
reviewText: There are now a whole bunch of classical Christmas mp3s on Amazon or more tracks of Xmas favorites for about a buck . Several of these are pretty good , and one you should not miss . What makes this album special is the rich concentration of important and beautiful choral works found within its nearly 10 hours Many of this pieces are very hard to find , or 1960s , the sound is remarkably good . Performance standard are consistently high , with beautiful solo singing Unfortunately amazon gives us no composer names , so it is not easy to know what you are getting . After some research , I can provide at least a partial list of some of the complete choral works on this album . Marvel not , Joseph ; Johann Walther - Joseph lieber Joseph mein John Attley - Sweet Was The Song The Virgin Sung ; William Byrd - Lullaby 72 - 133 : Bach : Christmas Oratorio ( --that is right , Bach 's complete Christmas Oratorio , covering more the 60 tracks ! ) 154 - 166 : Tchaikovsky : Nutcracker ( Substantial selections ) 192 : Purcell : Behold , I Bring You Glad Tidings ( Anthem , Z 002 ) Both Schtz works are gorgeous , as are the pieces by Buxtehude , Haydn , Caldara , Monteverdi , which were previously unknown to me . I would strongly recommend this for the wonderful and hard to find choral works listed above . And the popular carols are not bad either . and have been listening to it non - stop every since ! summary: Pop be damned, one of the best PUNK albums ever made
reviewText: The punk rock world was in a questionable state by the turn of the millennium . that undoubtedly ruled the ' 90s scene -- Green Day , in October of 2000 , would issue a nearly - all - acoustic record ( " Warning " ) , which , while being okay , seemed to signal a change in direction , that could have been seen as a death - knell for the genre . that emerged around this time to save the day and inject some much - needed youthful vitriol to the sound . Perhaps the first group in this scene to break through to the mainstream during this era was Toronto , Ontario 's Sum 41 , and the album being reviewed , " All Killer , No Filler " , in October of Y2 K , just as Green Day were clearly moving on to pastures anew . Wow ! Talk about this record being a return to form for punk ! After a mood - setting intro , on track number two " Nothing On My Back , " the listener is introduced to the band 's striking , distinctive , and razor - sharp guitar sound , which was equal parts traditional punk - rock reverb and equal parts pure attitude . that is truly raw , inspired , because no one ever did it again like Sum did . yet , on this same opener , it is made clear From vocalist / co - guitarist Deryck Whibley 's ultra - memorable vocal lines and defiant sneer to bassist Cone 's well - placed This cut segues into the 50 - second " Never Wake Up , " which is a fast and furious monster and as good of a take on hardcore punk as any I have heard . The two best songs , though , lie in the disc 's second half . and boy , is it a masterpiece ! but it proves that sometimes the simplest riffing can also be the most effective . No doubt , one of Sum 's signature tunes . Perhaps my all - time favorite , though , is track number ten , " Crazy Amanda Bunkface . " and 16 seconds of pure punk rock bliss , and Deryck 's raging guitar solo , which is somewhat reminiscent of Green Day 's earlier " Haushinka , " will surely have you cranking the sound to maximum levels and basking in the euphoria . Again , a cut virtually unrivalled in the confines of punk . And there you have it -- 32 minutes of great music , with absolutely no boring spots anywhere to be found , that will surely have you putting " All Killer , No Filler " on repeat . or lost its power to enthrall you . I want to add and have been listening to underground punk rock ( Dead Kennedys , Government Issue , the F.YOU . 's , et al ) for decades , that " All Killer , No Filler " is among the best - crafted punk LPs in my collection , with perhaps the highest replay value of them all . A masterpiece If you do not already own this one , well , what are you waiting for ? !

Six years after their last album of original material , Counting Crows are back . Somewhere Under Wonderland is a solid comeback for the band , even if it feels slightly disconnected at the seams . Palisades Park is an ambitious opener , complete with a jazzy intro and shifting dynamics . The band still has the ability to take an eight minute song and make it feel completely effortless . Frontman Adam Duritz can still weave an engrossing story as tracks like John Appleseed 's Lament and the rock - flavored Dislocation clearly demonstrate . The aggressive tones of Dislocation and Elvis Went to Hollywood recall some of the band 's earlier work on records like Recovering the Satellites , yet it is the folk - driven narratives of God of Ocean Tides , Scarecrow that really steal the show . and life on the road , giving the record an undercurrent of dislocation and late nights spent between cities It is an interesting concept and Duritz pulls it off wonderfully , complete with the beautiful closer Possibility Days . While the songs are mostly solid , I can not help feeling that they lack some cohesion . The record features a nice blend of styles but the country tracks are so good that I almost wish the band had just stripped down The individual songs are quite good but there is also nothing quite as poignant as Amy Hit the Atmosphere and lyrics are as strong as ever or three songs would have rounded it out nicely . that are easy to overlook when the strength of the songs themselves is kept in focus . In spite of that , Somewhere Under Wonderland is a refreshing return for one of my favorite bands . Despite a couple of hiccups this is a fun release that gets better with every spin and gives me hope

summary: Halsey releases her formal debut - the dystopian concept album "Badlands"
reviewText: Coming from humble beginnings , the singer watched as her parents struggled to make ends meet , as they were minors at the time of her birth . As a teenager , she became well versed in playing the violin as well as the acoustic guitar . and posting original songs on Soundcloud . which she signed to the Virgin Records ' alternative label Astralwerks Records - the same label responsible for The Chemical Brothers , Fatboy Slim which featured production from the likes of Tim Anderson , Lido , The Futuristics , Swedish producer Yung Gud and the trio Captain Cuts , among others . Thematically , the concept revolves around a fictional dystopian society called The Badlands - a desert wasteland where the survivors and natives were imprisoned . Halsey also tries to keep her head up admist the face of adversity and opposition on " Hold Me Down " . On the first single " New Americana " , she celebrates the diversity of the millennial generation , while working in a reference to Mtume 's 1983 hit " Juicy Fruit " . but are very careful not to make the first move that tells of her brief romance with an older man in her native New York during her teenage years . She finds an escape from her problems and desires to find happiness somewhere else on " Roman Holiday " , while being done with an indifferent lover on " Ghost " . She deals with someone on a path to self - destruction on " Colors " Overall , " Badlands " is a good recording from Halsey . Although the production could have been a little better , in the end the songs are quite catchy and surprisingly upbeat for an indie pop act . Given the success of her debut , there may be a chance to hear more from her .

Their music has endured extraordinarily well for over thirty - five years . There have been a few successful hits collections and this one is just no acception . Chicago 's 2005 Love Songs collection , consists of their most well recieved love songs from thier long - time career . and a couple of live rendidtions of classics never before released on any Chicago album as well . The collection contains a lot of great tracks inclding You are The Inspiration , Will You Still Love Me , Beginnings , as well as classics like Colour My World Hard Habit To Break , and Hard To Say I am Sorry . The album also includes a couple of live recording with Phillip Bailey from Earth , Wind & Fire fame , on versions of If You Leave Me Now , and the Earth , Wind & Fire classic , After The Love Is Gone , which really sounds delightful and lively . While there love songs albums that really do not sell very well , or just miss out on a lot of great songs , Chicago 's Love Songs really displays very , very well within not just its price , but the vast number of classic Chicago tracks here . While many not at all be interested in this collection , it really is a good reflection of Chicago 's best ballads .

summary: As much as I love Johnny Gill...
reviewText: and everyone said he was coming off too cocky . Well , Johnny Gill released a new solo album at the same time New Edition 's Home Again came out , so was not he being a little cocky himself ? Yeah , everyone knows Johnny can do his thing solo , but to be honest , this was not his best album . The song sounds fine until you get to the chorus : " Let us get the mood right / Turn on your heart light . " That is too cheesy , even for Babyface . And " Love In An Elevator " is full of corny lyrics like " They say there is no luck on the thirteenth floor / But I found love and " Like The Staples , I want to take you there . " " Simply Say I Love You " is okay , but the album said Stevie Wonder is featured in this song . that slow Roger Troutman songs are irresistible . that really brings the other slow songs down is The sleepy production does not make things better , either . Another problem on this album are the corny uptempo songs , especially the very last track , " So Gentle " . It features a rap from Ron DeVoe , so you know what the main problem is . that the preceding song " I Know You Want Me " features uninspired rapping from some other guy , and his rapping is actually worse than Ron 's . I still like Johnny Gill , but this album seems like it was rushed . And the strong adlibs he is known for usually adds feeling to the songs , but here it seems like they are trying to hide the questionable material . You are better off getting the solo albums he made before this .

The Black Angels ' debut " Passover " was an exciting surge back to 60s psychedelia , full of mind - bending drones , trippy guitars and a truly inspired vocalist in Alex Maas . " Direction To See A Ghost " continues things in the same vein . Granted there is not much new to TBA 's sound , but this does not bother me . They have such a distinguished sound already The ` drone machine ' saturates everything , the drums are powerful and locked , the guitar tone is perfectly fuzzy and Maas ' piercing , nasally delivery is wonderfully fitting . but there are some real gems here . The one - two punch of " You On The Run " and " Doves " is a grand opening , with the former setting up a brooding , melancholy Velvet Underground atmosphere , only for the latter to cut through with some feel - good , sunshine pop psychedelia . Generally , there is not a bad song to be found here . " Directions " is another great album from The Black Angels that firmly cements them at the forefront of modern psychedelic rock .

summary: The final chapter, the final whispers, of Johnny Cash
reviewText: The final American album from Johnny Cash is not his strongest , but it is one of his most memorable . It is not his strongest because he was not feeling his strongest . His whispers are haunting though , on tracks like " Are not No Grave , " and to be honest , I wish there were more songs here for Johnny to sing . I do not think his version of " Aloha Oe " will be remembered as one of his greatest recordings ever , so the album feels a little too light , If you are a fan of Johnny Cash 's American recordings , I recommend listening to the album , and if you are thrilled by what you hear , then buy the album .

Of course , I do not care for KMFDM or True industrial , so Device 's industrial - lite metal is okay with me . who was singing , I thought the singer was topnotch . that the singer is David Draiman of Disturbed , I am going to go back and give Disturbed 's catalog another listen . I do have one issue with what I consider an otherwise great album . Sadly , Device is seriously lacking in guitar leads . In place of leads , Draiman has inserted a number of melodic bridges into the songs . I am not sure why he chose not to include leads in his songs ; they would only have added to the music , where leads would normally be as an opportunity to highlight his vocal abilities . All in all , the album is an enjoyable listen . I would recommend it to fans of all kinds of heavy music from Sevendust and Drowning Pool to Soilwork and Scar Symmetry .

In the mid-90 's Alanis Morissette 's angry alternative rock struck a chord with many , and " Jagged Little Pill " went on to become the biggest - selling debut album of all time by a female artist . Of course , not all of us were anxious to have a 22 - year - old girl tell us just how ticked off she was about this , And for whatever fans " Pill " did not make , its followup , " Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie , " with its lone hit " Thank YOU , " did not exactly sway the vote either . However her third offering , " Under Rug Swept , " seems poised to expand her fan base . For starters , she is not just asserting honest emotions this time , but a distinct artistry as well . and power pop guru Glen Ballard seems nowhere to be found ; Alanis instantly dispells any notion that will harm things , however , as the irresistible leadoff track " 21 Things I Want in a Lover " proves she is ready to reclaim a spot in radio . The album 's actual first single , " Hands Clean , " is just as sharp and catchy , and , like the equally hit - ready " Precious Illusions , " even though the lyrics tell of a love gone wrong , she is not so much telling the guy off as she is expressing reactions . Through it all , the sound is still a powerful one and co - write , some of Morissette 's influences are coming through stronger , such as Sarah McLachlan But her growth is not found solely in production . " A Man " offers a slow - burning , pulsating rock groove over a compellingly spiritual lyric , while " Utopia " finds her singing sweetly in a Sarah McLachlan - ish register over a chorus of acoustic guitars about her ideas of how to make the world a better place . Both songs are unfortunately uncommercial but also provide irresistible listens . That Particular Time , " with its haunting piano and elegant melody , clearly shows an artist in evolution . But to see how far she has truly come , one has to listen to no more than the achingly gorgeous ballad " Flinch . " Sounding deceptively simple , Alanis uses a beautiful acoustic melody to lament a love affair she just can not get over . In the song , some time has apparently gone by since the breakup , and she mentions her brother running into the ex , singing " I would be paralyzed if I ran into you / my tongue would sieze up if we were to meet again . " Had this been " Jagged Little Pill , " she probably would have asked her brother where he saw the guy so she could be sure to run into him on purpose . But now Alanis opens up her emotional accessibility so far as to let us see a vulnerable , and therefore beautiful , resigned sadness . therefore beautiful , resigned sadness . It is bravery like this , without the need to scream it in our face as she once did , that makes the album so impressive . but what makes " Under Rug Swept " such a compelling listen is the fact that her maturity has clearly already begun .

During my MTV days , Steve Winwood 's big 80 's splash with songs from Back In The High Life did not go unnoticed by me . and Chronicles , I had the good fortune of someone loaning me her tape of Arc Of A Diver , My interest in his second solo album was due to the upbeat " While You See A Chance . " Winwood 's sweeping organ - like synths open his first Top Ten solo hit - it reached # 7 in 1981 - along with the accompanying lively piano that gives it a radio - friendly beat , with some downright introspective lyrics on if one is truly free from the past and ready to take another road one blue morning with a gray wind blowing . I find myself enjoying this song more than " Higher Love . " 

 The title track reached # 48 on the singles chart , a slower midpaced affair . " Spanish Dancer " along the same languid lines , may be an example of what many called " lazy music " to describe Winwood 's early solo stuff . This song was included on the Chronicles compilation made to cash in on the success of Back in The High Life . I wonder why " Second - Hand Woman " was not a chart - topper , as it is a more lively affair with Winwood 's trademark keyboards set to a disco beat . Some racy imagery is present with the title woman being " a slot machine to take my dime " The same holds True for the near eight minute on - the - run opus " Night Train " with its funky beats mixed with guitars , particularly a solo around the six minute mark , A single mix of this could have done well , but alas . Two non - singles in particular strike me and both are slow songs . and something to soothe the balm of yesterday 's pain . which is a toast to whoever can understand this madness of life . The closing track " Dust " is the other song which also deals with memories one wants so bad to go away , in this case meaning time with a woman , yet how to deal with a love but a friendship Indeed , " a feather duster is no substitute for the real thing , " meaning time , " the universal healer . " Who quote " the sands of time wash us all clean . but not " lazy music " as was described by some , Arc Of A Diver shows Considering the turn - of - the - decade changes going on in the music scene , i.e. punk and new wave , it is fortunate And Winwood played all the instruments on the album , much like Prince had done his own debut For You . Despite having only seven songs , Arc benefits from a consistent synth - keyboard style , upbeat dance tunes to reflective ballads .
It is good to own these classics .
Nothing really sticks out as extraordinary .

Slow Train Coming - Bob Dylan * * * * Who saw it coming certainly not me . who his entire career had songs dealing with his faith suddenly converted to Christianity . In 1978 Bob Dylan officialy converted to the Christian faith and has been devout ever since . Slow Train coming would be the last hit Bob Dylan album for almost thirty years that singing about the most contraversial subject ever could be turned into a massive success , only Dylan could make it happen . After Slow Train Coming Dylan would go into a finger pointing faze preeching instead of spreading the word of his lord , but doing so with the threat of hellfire and brimstone and consequently losing a lot of his fan base in the process not that he cared . Slow Train Coming was a rare album because we never saw him this happy , voulnerable , or inspired again in his career 

 With the exception of ' When You Going To Wake Up ' the album is mostly happy and up beat in praise When You Going To Wake Up ' was a sign of things to come in a negative way , becaus earound the corner was nothing But being as this record was recorded with legendary hardcore Jewish producer Jerry Wexler ( Ray Charles , Motown ) , I do not think the man would have stood for finger pointing . ' Got To Serve Somebody ' became Dylans last hit single of the 1970 's as well as his last hit single of his career . It is got a very loose feel and lots of heavy organ , it is easy to see Throughout the album someone other then Bob Dylans musical abilities shine , and that is of Mark Knopfler of Dire Straights , yes the legandary axe slinger plays through out the album that is of Mark Knopfler of Dire Straights , yes the legandary axe slinger plays through out the album and is an asset to the team on tracks like ' Precious Angel ' and ' Slow Train . ' The former is amazing and would have fit well on Dire Straights debut . The later ' Slow Train ' is quite simply one of the best songs Dylans lyrics have always been known for beig nothing short of brilliant , and feel more inspired then usuall . That may be do to his new found faith . The imagery dipicted in his words are amazing and you feel like your there whitnessing Dylan speak to his lord right in front of you . Man Gave Names To All The Animals ' does seem like nothing more then a childhood neursery rhyme but it does at nice texture to the album Slow Train Coming is a must have for all fans of Dlyans work . or miss and even the decent ones are not essential that Dylan did anything worth while . that are among his best , Time Out Of Mind , Love and Modern Times . Make Slow Train Coming apart of your Dylan collection .

summary: The Very Funky Beginnings Of Robert Palmer
reviewText: At the same time at this point in the 70 's one of the more fasionable things for a lot of white rock musicians was to record in the Crescent City with many of the local musicians from Dr. John , Allen Toussaint , Little Feat None of these projects were bad at all but strangly enough many of them were one and funk so it was only fitting he would make his first solo album in New Orleans with of course all the best people in town on board . Two of the most remarkable things about this are related to Palmer himself . and had a very keen understanding of how to create great funk music , from the honeyed nuances ( as opposed to loud bellowing ) of his vocal style . Now he does a great job for sure in interpreting Big Easy styled funk here from the rolling clavinets on Allen Toussaint 's title track and " From A Whisper To A Scream " which Palmer also delivers with his great soulful understatement . and " Blackmail " but some of the most impressive songs on the album are the ones Palmer wrote himself . " Hey Julia " is an excellent song - a great rhythm box percussion led have jive / funk sort of groove with a really deep Carribean rhythm under the service;not so obvious it is emmediately detectable and " How Much Fun " both illustrate an understanding of the elegance of funk and elegance is a quality that Palmer himself always possessed very strong . Of course for a SERIOUS represenation of where Palmer really works a hardcore jam to death with his wonderfully jazzily phrased licks and down from a full band sound back to it is lower key tones from the beginning . that his 70 's sound was built very strongly on the type of music presented on this album and it is a credit to his integrity that maintained a strong connection to this particular element of his sound throughout his career as opposed to totally disgarding them when they were no longer trendy in mass culture .

There is no question that today 's music has mostly been a poor set of singers But for some legends , they can make great music last beyond a lifetime . While it has been more than 20 years since he released his last pop album , River Of Dreams , his songs still stand beyond the test of time . But he also had so many great concerts he had performed in the world . and he became one of the most profiled artists to have ever graced the stage in the former Soviet Union . that set the world on fire . Originally released as Kohuept in the late 80 's , A Matter Of Trust : The Bridge To Russia is a great importance and brilliant concert into what made Billy Joel a distinctive legend . While he was on tour to support his record The Bridge , he made a set of concert in the former Soviet Union to perform in front of Soviet audiences and inspired one of Joel 's most distinctive songs later on Lenningrad . why the Piano Man has been so classic after all this time . While Billy Joel was not the first YOU.S. performer to play the Superpower , but Billy was the most important to deliver . The songs still sound great and remain as important and classic as they were Songs like Piano Man , Uptown Girl and Allentown are very well remastered here , as well as songs but have not been released before like a rehearsal cut of New York State Of Mind , and songs like Allentown The songs sound great , and a great trip back in time to when music really had a thumbprint of changing the world , something today 's artists really have not even scratched the surface on . who have made some great live albums in the 80 's . and Billy Joel 's A Matter Of Trust : The Bridge To Russia is one of those great records . If you have never , ever had heard the classic Piano Man 's classic songs before , than you should get a good listen to this album . when it came out in the 80 's , you will absolutely love A Matter Of Trust : The Bridge To Russia . Billy Joel has always been a fantastic entertainer , and this is a blueprint of what made him so classic for all this time .

yet another step from public renown . Things were not helped by Virgin 's reluctance to reissue the album on CD , nor the time - limited nature of this Wounded Bird 's release . The hard - luck story leaves this great power - pop album once again difficult to find . And rest assured , this is no one - hit wonder of an LP ; Holly Beth Vincent 's other songs were in the same league as " Tell and veteran producer Richard Gottehrer ( Blondie , Go - Gos , Richard Hell & The Voidoids ) deftly mated the verve of new wave and punk with the timeless sound of guitar - driven rock ' n ' roll . that prematurely aged the competition 's work . summary: Let's All Sing Like The Birdies Sing
reviewText: When Glee originally started , I have to admit While I have found each of the discs to be enjoyable , they have often had their share of Karaoke Plus type of moments , and rarely outdid the original versions of the songs they started off covering . " Glee Presents The Warblers " changes For starters , they enlist an actual Glee Club ( the Tufts ' University Beelzebubs ) to perform the bulk of the vocal work . Then they give the lead focus to Darren Criss ( Blaine on the show ) , one lead to Chris Colfer ( Kurt ) Criss has a pleasant , boy - band type of voice , while Colfer sounds like the show - tunes worshiping kid he plays on the show ( He is good on the Lennon - McCartney numbers ; Colfer 's version of " I Want To Hold Your Hand " remains a series standout ) . The selection is a solid representation of any typical " Now I was already partial to The Warblers ' version of Katy Perry 's " Teenage Dream , " then they chart similar courses on Beyonce 's " Bills Bills Bills " and Maroon 5 's " Misery . " They redeem the long reviled McCartney " Silly Love Songs " and manage to make Barbra Streisand 's " What Kind Of Fool " into the kind of song the Bee Gees might have done if Barry Gibb had kept the song for himself . However , I doubt anyone will every be able to sing " Do You Think I am Sexy " and make it anything better than a piffle . ) The constancy of " Glee Presents The Warblers " make it the best of The Glee series . It also may be the first starmaker of the series , propelling Darren Criss into a promising solo career .
