Nine Inch Nails ' Trent Reznor , infamous for long delays between albums , sure has been productive lately . 2007 saw Reznor release the critically acclaimed " Year Zero " In addition , last year Reznor produced Saul Williams ' " The Inevitable Rise and Liberation of Niggy Tardust . " Now , out of nowhere , with no advance notice , Reznor is back with NIN 's sixth album , the instrumental " Ghosts I - IV . " 

 " A soundtrack for daydreams , " is how Reznor sums up the new album ... and that , I feel , is the best way to appreciate the new NIN . that , I feel , is the best way to appreciate the new NIN . or doing housework , " Ghosts I - IV " is best appreciated with relaxed , Lie in bed or on the sofa , relaxed , And as the mood of the album changes , allow your mood to flow with the album ... try to get lost in the music . that " Ghosts I - IV " sounds similar in style to the instrumental music from " The Fragile , " ( 1999 ) that accurate to say While the instrumental music from " the Fragile " sort of held the vocal compositions from that CD together like glue , " Ghosts I - IV " is a little more " out there . " therefore , be seen as a mosaic -- of several different styles -- piano compositions , industrial beats , the avant - garde -- all mixed together , with no real dominant flavor overpowering the rest . And while the album is all - over - the - place , treading many territories , everything works ; " Ghosts I - IV " takes so many twists - and - turns - its always interesting . At the same time , with almost two hours of music to absorb , " Ghosts I - IV " is best appreciated with repeated listens -- to fully appreciate all its ' rich textures

summary: Seriously Stepped Back, But Not Far
reviewText: This past year we have already lost a lot of legends in music whom have died before their time and fell to the waste side before our eyes , from Prince to David Bowie and Maurice White of Earth , Wind & Fire . This year has honestly been a tragic year for legends . But some of them have had so much to celebrate over the years , like this year for Phil Collins , whom had stepped away from the music industry for quite awhile to take care of some health problems . Well , now he is making a return to the industry , and celebrating his music all over . But anyway , he also celebrated some huge milestones this year , celebrating the 35th anniversary of his solo debut Face Value , and the 30th anniversary of him winning Album Of The Year at The Grammy awards for his No Jacket Required album . when he was going to re - release all of his studio albums again , he had a lot of albums being celebrated , The Essential Going Back , is more like a recreation of his 2010 album Going Back , where Phil Collins recorded a lot of classic standards and celebrated the music of soul in the 60 's But fort this re - release of the original 2010 Going Back album , Still , you do get some really good tracks being remastered like ( Love Is Like A ) Heatwave , his rendition of Stevie Wonder 's Uptight , his soulful rendition of Some Of Your Loving which were never released as original recordings on the studio album a soulful cover of The Temptations hit My Girl Yet , the downside to this release for die hard Phil Collins fans that there were a lot of good songs that were cut out of the re - release like In My Lonely Room , a soulful cover of Standing In The Shadows Of Love Still , despite a few songs being overlooked , and even the original version would be a little too much of a hassle being re - released as a album , The Essential Going Back is a good buy for mainly the die hard Phil Collins fans where the live tracks are worth the while , but for newcomers to Phil Collins music , they might want to take the step back and listen to the original album versions , regular and deluxe from 2010 to get a better ear of what Phil had made musically from his soul first , before they sink their teeth into The Essential Going Back . Still , it is a good buy for hard core Phil Collins fans that is nobly worth the dollar .

His combination of lush production values and impeccable harmonies produced an incredibly pleasing sound that proved wildly successful . " Turn Around " was a huge hit for the group and was followed in swift succession by remakes of " My Special Angel " , " Earth Angel " , " Till " , " Moments to Remember " , " Green Fields " In fact , I enjoyed The Vogues so much that I used to even play the flip sides frequently . summary: Ancient and modern styles - and the Messiah!
reviewText: that have been presented in other low price collections of music on the BIS label . who do often complain about the duplication . that if there are enough new tracks then the packages are usually worth buying . In the case of this Handel release there are some gems that are worth the price of this collection alone . and the Bach Collegium of Japan ( using authentic instruments)is one example . And Without Controversy " reading from ( I Timothy 3 : 16)which often precedes the music in performance , It is on the original Suzuki recording though , but I imagine only purists would complain about its absence here when otherwise this is a fine complete performance with both English otherwise this is a fine complete performance with both English and Japanese forces ( leading at times to some quaint stresses from the choir ) that has been reviewed well elsewhere . Although not the top recommendation it does stand up well , and at this price is certainly worth a place in your collection . Other favourites in this collection are the Concerti Grosso played by Arte de Suonatori under Martin Gester , a Polish Baroque Orchestra , who give fine performances of four of these Concerti fronm their well - received collection Handel , G. : These are stylishly played in an authentic manner with authentic instruments . Another " authentic " group are the London Baroque who , apart from a lovely G minor Trio Sonata are joined by top English baroque soprano Dame Emma Kirkby in Handel 's short Salve Regina in G minor from the CD Emma Kirkby - Handel : Sacred Cantatas / London Baroque but not , it seems , otherwise available as a download . These are superb performances , thoroughly enjoyable and in good recordings . She is such an expressive sensitive singer ( hear her Dido in Music for the Royal Fireworks / Cti a Due Cori . This , of course is the original version for Wind Orchestra for outdoors performance with fireworks . and performance more understated than I would like - but well played with verve Handel 's Largo always goes down well and this performance by Yoshikazu Mela with the Japan Philharmonic comes across as a pleasant addition to this collection - Mela is a countertenor with a pure voice that rises above the orchestra with a rare beauty . He is also represented in the Messiah presented here so we are treated to a real talent . Countertenors vary in their tone , some are True countertenors - men with a True vocal range , others rely on a Falsetto style to take their , often tenor , voices into the upper registers - never quite as satisfactory in my opinion . All in all , then , an excellent collection of music played with a mix of authentic and modern instrument bands . At the current price you can not go wrong with this .

And I ended up liking it well enough to purchase a copy . It is no musical masterpiece , but dang is it catchy and fun . It is heavy on the synthesizer , much like a lot of the hits of the ' 80s , and has a fast , almost frantic beat to it . As stated before , Psy talks his way through most of the song , only singing at the chorus ( he does do a decent job of singing , though , so it is not for lack of talent ) . And of course , it is an upbeat number that almost encourages the listener to get up and dance -- I find it almost physically impossible to hold still while listening to this song . And no , I do not understand any of the lyrics aside from the titular " Gangnam style " ( said to refer to a city ) and the occasional belting out of " Hey , sexy lady ! summary: The most shocking transition of Dylan's career...
reviewText: and tossed fans around on a wild sea of change when he picked up an electric guitar in defiance of the folk community 's unwritten rules ) . The year 1979 saw his most shocking transition . that challenged and threatened Dylan 's career like no other . who produced " Slow Train Coming " , told Dylan biographer Clinton Heylin that " I had no idea he was on this born - again Christian trip until he started to evangelize me . " So in the heyday of punk the performer many people associated , fairly or unfairly , with 1960s " radicalism " turned explicitly Christian . that , 1978 's " Street Legal " met with an extremely icy reception . For many fans Dylan 's new " phase " was too much . Dylan 's " Christian phase " ( though arguably not a phase ) now looks somewhat innocuous from a historical perspective . Would his career have survived had he plunged permanently into Christian music ? Hard to say . Regardless , the 1980s were probably the low point of Dylan 's career from many perspectives . " Slow Train Coming " is a Christian album . It makes no apologies for this . Though far less preachy than its successor , " Saved " , the theme of the album remains unmistakable . When He Returns " , the album 's passionate closer , more than demonstrates this with lines such as " He is got plans of his own to set up His throne or not listeners accept this album most likely depends on their attitude towards the lyrics . Because there is nothing wrong with the music on " Slow Train Coming " . " Precious Angel " features Mark Knoplfer 's distinctive guitar style and probably one of the best Dylan drawls ever recorded : " Ya know I just could not make it by myself . I am a little too blind to seeeEEEeeeeee . " " Slow Train " contains an ominous groove . When you Going To Wake Up " lashes out at society 's failings . Whether one agrees with the religious perspective or not , the criticism here seems valid and constructive . Only " Man Gave Names To All The Animals " sounds a little trite . Everything else on " Slow Train Coming " receives passion or not one agrees with the overall message , Dylan 's performance is outstanding on this album ( it even bagged him a Grammy for " Best Rock Vocal " - something his detractors , especially those who find his distinctive voice grating , must have cringed at ) . " Slow Train Coming " just adds proof to the argument that Bob Dylan remains one of the most provocative , controversial , Apart from the music , he is given his fans plenty of challenges , and given future generations an almost insurmountable amount of material to ponder

summary: We've been walking down this road for some time.
reviewText: The problem I have with Stefani 's music is that it is like candy -- sweet and sickly at the same time . Ultimately , her music leaves you with a sugar crash afterward . I have all three of her solo cds , plus all of No Doubt 's cds . I did not enjoy the last No Doubt cd either . " This Is What The Truth Feels Like ... " is Stefani 's first solo work in 10 years . This is probably the best of the three solo albums . It is certainly her most mature . Most of the irritating idiosyncrasies from her first two cds are scrubbed out here to good results . The only clunker here is " Naughty " There is much to like here , that popular music death mark -- age 40 . and now have cracked the Top 40 . This is a shame , I give " This Is What The Truth Feels Like ... " three because it is good , that strips it of having real emotional impact She can not create an album without at least eight different producers on it , which gives all of her albums an uneven quality to them . " Misery " , " You are My Favorite " , " Make Me Like You " , " Truth " , and " Used To Love You " are the best tracks here , and the most likely candidates for a Top 40 hit . Bring on the next No Doubt album . Here is how " This Is What The Truth Feels Like ... " compares to Stefani 's other work : 2004 Love . Angel . During my MTV days , Steve Winwood 's big 80 's splash with songs from Back In The High Life did not go unnoticed by me . and Chronicles , I had the good fortune of someone loaning me her tape of Arc Of A Diver , My interest in his second solo album was due to the upbeat " While You See A Chance . " Winwood 's sweeping organ - like synths open his first Top Ten solo hit - it reached # 7 in 1981 - along with the accompanying lively piano that gives it a radio - friendly beat , with some downright introspective lyrics on if one is truly free from the past and ready to take another road one blue morning with a gray wind blowing . I find myself enjoying this song more than " Higher Love . " 

 The title track reached # 48 on the singles chart , a slower midpaced affair . " Spanish Dancer " along the same languid lines , may be an example of what many called " lazy music " to describe Winwood 's early solo stuff . This song was included on the Chronicles compilation made to cash in on the success of Back in The High Life . I wonder why " Second - Hand Woman " was not a chart - topper , as it is a more lively affair with Winwood 's trademark keyboards set to a disco beat . Some racy imagery is present with the title woman being " a slot machine to take my dime " The same holds True for the near eight minute on - the - run opus " Night Train " with its funky beats mixed with guitars , particularly a solo around the six minute mark , A single mix of this could have done well , but alas . Two non - singles in particular strike me and both are slow songs . and something to soothe the balm of yesterday 's pain . which is a toast to whoever can understand this madness of life . The closing track " Dust " is the other song which also deals with memories one wants so bad to go away , in this case meaning time with a woman , yet how to deal with a love but a friendship Indeed , " a feather duster is no substitute for the real thing , " meaning time , " the universal healer . " Who quote " the sands of time wash us all clean . but not " lazy music " as was described by some , Arc Of A Diver shows Considering the turn - of - the - decade changes going on in the music scene , i.e. punk and new wave , it is fortunate And Winwood played all the instruments on the album , much like Prince had done his own debut For You . Despite having only seven songs , Arc benefits from a consistent synth - keyboard style , upbeat dance tunes to reflective ballads .

which won first place in a competition in 1975 and is still a stunning and moving tribute to the spirit and its people following one of the darkest days of modern history . Despite the title , the music composed for this album is neither a memorial nor a protest against nuclear weapons . It is Suzuki 's imaginary story of someone who died in the event and then journeys through the unknown spiritual world . It is interesting to note that Suzuki composes his music in a similar manner to creating his visual artwork , finishing one piece before moving to the next and allowing the previous work to influence the new work . and continuity Very minimal as well as ambient , the music has a dark , soulful quality that is sometimes mysterious or mournful and sometimes a bit lighter and more hopeful ( but not joyous ) . and the spirit finds its way Created with synths , the instrumentation includes ethereal and rich . " Resonance , " his debut , received the 2011 Best Ambient Album award from Zone Music Reporter , and " Cycle " was nominated as the Best Relaxation / Meditation Album and Best Ambient Album for 2012 by the same organization . I would fully expect similar acclaim for " Voyage , " another extraordinary musical experience from this fascinating artist .

summary: Noise and Beauty, Sex and Cynicism - this was the 80s that was
reviewText: The best of what redeemed the eighties from MTV crap . and still is a dense cacophony of beauty and your classic 80s angst and cynicism with moments of tentative redemption . Everyone is got their favorite 80s icons- Nothing burns into your teenage brain permanently like a great rock group when they are on top of their game , before they are just paying the bills and trying not to punch each other out in the process . " She is Mine " is a standout ; Butler 's seething rasp can have its oddly tender moments . and I just die when he talk - sings " Ha Ha Ha " . Classic Butler - ism . ) . While " Pretty In Pink " tends to give me the Mollyringwalds and it seems a bit sexist , I still love it for what it reminds me of : that great p - furs signature intro . " Into you like a train " is just full - speed searing beauty , guitars sweeping around you . And " No Tears " perfectly captures 80s wariness of political activism and the ensuing apathy /antagonism with the problematic radicals of the day ( " There is demonstrations , While occasionally Butler has his Dylan - ish moments of lyrical nonsense , they do work in their 80s way , like a collage of imagery and emotional impressions , not literal straightforward meanings in lyrics . yet driving , layered noise . I could never go full atonal - the No Wave thing , so this has that kind of energy , in a sense , The layers & textures never get in the way of the lyrical / melodic line- it always sounds like it is just short of all parts crashing together , yet it is sort of a controlled chaos Also , this album has density without all the twinkly , trebly production that " Forever Now " has to make it more radio - friendly . when all this stuff seemed so romantic ! " So run Down " is another great track- reminds me of when even a bad hangover seemed like a new adventure ! and that was not such as a bad thing at a tender age . that was not such as a bad thing at a tender age .

summary: Third Day Lead Us Back: Songs of Worship Album Review
reviewText:
Prime Cuts : Our Deliverer , In Jesus ' Name , The One I Love 

 Though Southern rock has always been the default template of Third Day , there is always discernable threads of worship music in their prodigious portfolio of songs . and sold over 7 million records , Third Day 's best moments are arguably encapsulated in their worship songs . why their former worship albums , namely 2000 's " Offerings " and 2003 's " Offerings II , " are often regarded by avid fans as their catalog treasures . and most satisfying worship album to date . Unlike their former two worship records and covers slapdash together , " Lead Me Home " is a seamless affair of entirely studio recorded tracks freshly penned just for this disc . Hands down , the " wow " factor of " Lead Us Back " is squarely centered on lead singer Mac Powell 's charismatic vocals . With his bright booming voice that calls to mind Casting Crowns ' Mark Hall , Powell brings an air of Godly confidence to " Our Deliverer , " an anthem of faith that awaits the second coming of Jesus Christ . Then hear Powell takes his vocals on a roller coaster ride with the hilly hymn - like " He is Alive , " a worship song who has had a couple of excursions in releasing his solo country albums certainly brings his rustic sound to bare on the folky " Soul on Fire " ( co - written with Matt Maher ) and Daughters can be heard in the backing department . But Third Day are not just interested in just making worship songs . Songs like " Spirit " that create invitations for congregation members to want to sing along . This is particularly True of " Spirit " which has a choral backing tailored for church worship . And the best amongst the congregational - focused song that is destined to be a classic is " In Jesus ' Name . " that features the voices of Christian music 's top artists such as Michael W. Smith , David Crowder , Natalie Grant , and Michael Tait . 

 Fans who yearn for a softer moment without the tight blast of guitars and drums will take delight in the album 's final track " The One I Love . " This song simply is a testament of what a great vocalist Powell is . Even with just his soaring vocals , a backing vocalist , and an acoustic guitar , he can still lead us into God 's throne room with such grace This track by itself speaks volumes of the passion Third Day puts into this record . In sum , this truly is a well - invested album made specifically to lead us back to the woship of the King of kings .

or state characterized by freedom from or oblivion to pain , worry , grunge ( noun ) - dirt , filth , rubbish ; something of inferior quality ; trash . The 1980s were one big , immoral popularity contest . While hard rock had dominated most of the 1970s , the 80s were all about pop : artists like Michael Jackson , Phil Collins , Lionel Ritchie , By 1980 , punk rock , which began in the mid-70s , had evolved into " new wave , " spawning groups like Tears for Fears Meanwhile , rock titans like Neil Young seemed to have lost all the edginess that made them so attractive ; Bob Dylan stumbled through the decade , fashioning a couple great albums and releasing a much greater number of duds . Music aficionados were forced to ponder the direst of ponderings : was rock dead ? Whether rock was dead or alive , Nirvana rejuvenated it and brought it back to the forefront , nearly stopping pop in its place . The world had not heard anything so ferocious and reeling with pained awareness since the days of the Sex Pistols , and for a world still feeling hungover from the superficial craze of the 1980s , it was a welcome wake - up call . Nirvana actually emerged at the end of the 80s , led by lead vocalist that Sub Pop was going to become a subsidiary for a major label , they decided to " cut out the middleman " " Grunge " music , the murky indie - alternative rock played by groups like Soundgarden , Alice in Chains , or , more famously , Pearl Jam , was on the verge of becoming popular . Geffen executives hoped Nirvana could find some fame as one of the better grunge bands . They hoped to sell 250,000 copies of Nirvana 's second effort , 1991 's " Nevermind , " earning a " Gold " certification from the RIAA ( Recording Industry Association of America ) . The band themselves did not really care . When the record was released in late 1991 , MTV 's late night music video showcase " 120 Minutes " began playing " Smells Like Teen Spirit , " the album 's lead single . Soon it became so popular that the network began playing it during the day . and in November of ' 91 it entered the Billboard Top 40 at # 35 .   Half of the initial YOU.S. pressings went to the northwest , and was unavailable for days . Finally , in January of 1992 , Nevermind hit # 1 on the Billboard Top 40 . Critical response to the album was decidedly mixed . and confident spirit to be much more than a reformulation of college radio 's high - octane hits . " On the other hand , Robert Christgau , the so - called " Dean of American Rock Critics , " gave the album an A.   " This is hard rock as the term was understood before metal moved in - the kind of loud , slovenly , tuneful music you think no one will ever work a change on again until the next time it happens , " Christgau wrote . That is exactly what " Nevermind " is : a hard rock , post - punk album picking up where the punk groups of the 1970s left off . When Nevermind was released at the beginning of the 90s , despite its cover art depicting a baby pursuing a dollar bill on a fishing hook underwater , it was like a generation coming up for air after being drowned in commercial , spiritless noise for a decade . Nirvana defined its generation like no other , or the band , one must be familiar with its leader : the legendary , quasi - infamous Kurt Cobain . Most people are very familiar with him , due in no small part to his untimely and much - discussed death in 1994 . that looks like something out of " The Fog . " Friends Cobain hated athletics ( despite his father signing him up for the local wrestling which Cobain did quite well ) and befriended a gay student , leading to taunts and bullying from Cobain 's peers . He focused mostly on drawing , although I wish I were , just to piss off homophobes . " 

 Cobain is a rock god . He was named the greatest rock n ' roll hero of all time by " NME " readers in 2006 , and fascinating personalities in the history of popular music . On the outside , he was a good - looking , hostile , roughly - dressed twenty - something ; on the inside , he was fighting an endless battle against his own inner demons . that separated Cobain from his similarly rude , rebellious peers was this : he cared about the world . and he was not afraid to admit it . Much of the immense pain in his life came from his own terror at the state of the world Rough numbers like the mocking " In Bloom " or the woeful " Lithium " sound angry and reckless on top , but beneath all the anger there is immense sorrow at the state of things . The trademark punk madness , juxtaposed with sincere humanism , was one of the most appealing things about Nirvana . While rival group Pearl Jam sang , " I take a walk outside / I am surrounded by some kids at play / I can feel their laughter , so " , Nirvana grumbled lines like , " or such refrains as , " Give an inch , take a smile / Fashion shifts , fashion style / Throw it out and keep it in / Have to have poison skin . " Cobain seemed to be almost rambling as he spewed out line after line of surreal poetry , that most of the lyrics were written within five minutes of their first performance - there sure appeared to be some sort of deeper meaning . His lyrics would not have been nearly as powerful without the music to back them up . Songs like " On a Plain " were simple enough to catch the public ear , and very appealing depth to them . Despite his aim to wipe the earth clean of the shiny , soulless tunes of the 80s , Cobain loved pop music . In fact , " Nevermind " 's most famous song , the inescapable " Smells Like Teen Spirit " ( voted the 9th best song of all time by " Rolling Stone " ) , was Cobain 's attempt to write the perfect song . While crafting " Nevermind , " he aimed to create the ultimate pop album in the vein of his heroes , the Beatles , one which was modern and catchy enough to obliterate records like Michael Jackson 's " Dangerous " ( number 1 on the charts at but meaningful and spirited enough The result was a manic , pounding , rollicking rush of intense rock music . Bassist Krist Novoselic added an oily murkiness to the tracks , keeping Cobain 's edgy , buzzing guitars from taking off , much like Cobain 's own darkness prevented him from ever soaring as a public figure ( until his death - more on The band 's original drummer , Chad Channing , was fired Where Channing just sort of rolled through each song , Grohl was like a hurricane He did not have the versatility or sheer prowess of drummers like Rush 's Neil Peart and did pound the hell out of those things , much like the but any fan will tell you and Grohl were equally important , the firm , high - velocity support for Cobain 's meandering surrealism . Of Nirvana 's three albums , " Nevermind " is widely regarded as their masterpiece . Each of its 12 tracks are gems . that its lead single , the aforementioned " Smells Like Teen Spirit , " is probably its weakest track . That song , with others like the rambunctious " Breed , " or the purposefully abysmal " Territorial Pissings,"are pure hard - rocking delights . The watery guitar on the almost ethereal " Come As You Are " is irresistible , while the surprisingly melodic chorus of " On a Plain , " or the woeful breeziness of " Something in the Way , " are downright ghostly . While the record may have retained that ghostliness since its release , it is certainly more haunting considering the dark circumstances of Cobain 's death . There is no underlying theme on " Nevermind . " It is not conceptually dense or extraodinarily creative , like " Sgt . Pepper 's Lonely Hearts Club Band . " And all these years later , the abundance of Nirvana - wannabes on popular radio have numbed our ears . But if at first " Nevermind " does not seem particularly amazing , listen to it again , and to your surprise , you will forget about all those other " post - grunge " groups out there What makes " Nevermind " so wonderful is , in part , its story : after all , Cobain and his crew had no intentions of blowing the world away and had a pretty good time saying it too . but aware ( painfully so , at times ) ; visceral , but sophisticated . It is amazing that a genre so inherently ugly , punk , can turn out to be so wise and beautiful . And punk was never more beautiful than Nirvana . Truly , Nirvana could have been the best Although the Beatles ' debut was a piece of pop perfection , it took them five more albums to craft a genuinely brilliant record . Nirvana 's debut , on the other - hand , was a nasty , black snake of a record , far from brilliant , but certainly promising . It took them only one more album to generate a masterpiece , though , and their next album , " In Utero , " was similarly great . and it sounds more like the rough , vomitific rock of " Bleach " than the shiny which the band often expressed their disapproval with ) . But " Nevermind " was their masterpiece , a perfect rock record that all this was done within the course of three albums , it is breathtaking to think what the group may have done had not Cobain been killed . So if the band could have been so great , what happened ? Well , although Nirvana was the pride and joy of American listeners around 1992 , when " In Utero " was released in 1993 , the public was losing interest . that intentionally challenged its listeners , that was a challenge they were not willing to accept . On top of that , the public was getting sick of Cobain 's seemingly incessant depression and disregard for his fans . and more alienated by the band 's sudden popularity , too . 1994 found Cobain seeking a divorce from his wife , Courtney Love ( the public frequently called " Cobain & Love " the new " Lennon & Ono " ) , Then he was killed . The public went mad . Suddenly everyone loved Nirvana again , They were brilliant . Cobain was immortalized , trapped forever as the dark , troubled 27 - year - old lead of one of the greatest bands of all time . A nation grieved for one of its most promising and talented youth . How did he die ? Suicide , officially . The most popular rock music conspiracy is that Cobain did not kill himself : he was murdered . and truthfully , if he had not died such a sudden and shocking death , they might not have been remembered so fondly . Regardless of the history , Nevermind is one hell of an album . " Rolling Stone " ranked it # 17 on their list of the 500 Greatest Albums , commenting , " His [ Cobain 's ] slashing riffs , corrosive singing and deviously oblique writing , rammed home by the Pixies - via - Zeppelin might of bassist Krist Novoselic It was ranked the second best album ever on VH1 's list ( behind the Beatles ' " Revolver " ) , and has ranked toward the top of countless other " all - time best " lists . Deservedly so . This is truly one of the finest records ever cut , so fine that it almost single - handedly murdered our nation 's obsession with pop . Unfortunately , Nirvana ended too soon to complete their mission , and so we remain a nation terrifyingly conscious of trashy pop and sickeningly unaware of the good stuff , the real music - stuff like this .

summary: (4.5 Stars) Say Hello To Real R&B!
reviewText: Jaheim came out on the scene pretty strong , selling double platinum with his debut album Ghetto Love and then platinum with Still Ghetto . when his last album Ghetto Classics only managed to go gold , things looked a little troublesome . This is especially True since Ghetto Classics was just as good as its predecessors , and failed to chalk up the numbers he used to get in his prime . Now with Atlantic Records as his new label home , Jaheim hopes to re - up and capture the attention of his original fan base and slow cuts for the majority of the album . After professing his worth with the intro track " Voice of R&B. " Jaheim lays it down with " Hush , " a song about keeping an affair with a homie 's girl on the low . " Have You Ever " rides out with strong background vocals , simple piano work , " Lonely " is a reworking of Bobby Womack 's " If You Think You are Lonely Now , " using the infamous hook for the song and her man is the one sitting at home all alone ! " Life of a Thug " is a depiction of Jaheim 's life in the form of an autobiographical song , describing all the trials and his ultimate redemption from those trying times . why a lover does not realize a good man when he is right in your face on the song " Just Do not Have A Clue . " and background from The Delphonics ' classic " La La Means I Love You " for another reworking and wishing he could still be with her instead of anyone he is been with since losing her . Jaheim hangs up his player status for the love of his life on the album 's lead - off single " Never . " " I have Changed " features the dynamic rawness of Keyshia Cole alongside his ghetto bravado , but the ridiculously child - like delivery of the chorus ultimately kills the song . where he describes realizing the True essence of a woman who was disrespected and unappreciated by a fool " Make A Wish " is a smooth yet simple song about giving his girl whatever she wants and dreams of having , something every woman wishes were True ! The album closes with the tender cut " Back Together Again , " a tribute to his parents who are now reunited in Heaven . and it truly shows in practically every track . If this does not convince the masses that he is the real thing , then this will certainly prove that people do not know True R&B talent when they see it ... let alone hear it .

summary: Not Just Your Average Sugar-Coated "Gold and Green"
reviewText: With 5 number 1 hits , 3 multi - platinum albums , and a prime time TV special , success certainly has been a close relative of Sugarland . And like many country superstars , they have been lobbied by their record company to cut a seasonal effort as a stop - gap album in lieu of a brand new studio CD this year . Rather , on this hybrid effort , they have invested 5 original tunes , some of which are among their most heartfelt compositions . when they tackle the seasonal chestnuts , they have endorsed their interpretations with innovative creativity . Bursting the seams of genre classifications , these 10 cuts are made so much more interesting with doses of are & b , jazz , pop , country rock as well as even some traces of bluegrass . Jennifer Nettles ' heartfelt delivery emotes in convincing ways the loneliness of being homesick that truly staggers the heart . and Kristian Bush , is a finely honed narrative piece telling the story of how a girl 's life changed since she received a guitar as her only gift one Christmas . Yet not is syrupy sentimental ; Sugarland shows that they know how to have fun with " Nuttin ' for Christmas . " Cute , fun , and definitely catchy -- Nettles truly sounds like she is having fun and easily " Nuttin ' for Christmas " would rock well in the ranks of classics such as " Santa Claus is Coming to Town " that lofty in standard :   " Maybe Baby " sounds like a track from their standard album with " Christmasy " references tagged on . While " Coming Home " is pretty average this time finding the duo in r&b territory with a light touch of Gospel . While most renditions of " O Come O Come Emanuel " are dirge - like slow , Sugarland offers a bluegrassy take of this hymn making it sound like a rootsy Southern Gospel revival number . Never to be restrained by the language barrier , " Silent Night " is sung bilingually in both English This time " Silent Night " finds Jennifer Nettles trading lines with Kristian Bush making one wish they would sing more duets together . Kristian Bush again returns to the microphone to sing lead on " Holly Jolly Christmas " which is quite jovial without being exceptional . Relative to most Christmas CDs out there , " Gold More than just a holiday album , this is very much a Sugarland record . However , like their studio albums , with the originals coming mostly from their own pens , some of them become pretty average pop country efforts . that , " Gold

summary: Chante Moore's Sixth Album Marking A Sixth Comeback
reviewText: One thing to be said about Chante Moore is she is always had the pedigree for huge creative success . A love for jazz and a heavy gospel back round have given her a powerfully rangey vocal instrument that lends itself wonderfully to the highest form of interpretation to both original material Also having been in the glamour profession as a model ala ' Whitney Houston helped in the image department . or these days on YouTube my feelings for her are always the same : being presented with a tremendous vocal talent that is constantly pandering to every cliched hip - hop / soul trend I only had ever bought her debut album Precious before this - hoping the level of musical chutzpah she showcases on her collaborations with other artists would fulfill itself more strongly when she made another of her comebacks - a term I use since her albums always come fairly few " Baby Can I Touch You In The Rain " is not a bad way to open the album at all - delivering a piano driven jazzy - soul number with strong pop craft involved . " Talking In My Sleep " is strong melodically as well as musically - with a vocally appropriate use of the 2 - step dance / hip - hop beat that is ... yes has been more than overused and dull for several years now to me but this song uses it well . " Alone " is a deep , throbbing and bass heavy funk jam of the sort I have never heard from Chante ' before - not to say she is never done them . Combined as it with with more strong song - craft , its impressive enough to be a personal favorite here . The sad " Don ' Make Me Laugh " and " Giving You Always " are nuanced and relaxed ballad type songs instrumentally - Chante 's vocals going from cooing to gospel / soul / jazz fire as the song builds . " Doctor Doctor " references the horn part of Sam Cooke 's " Shake " for a contemporary production of a mid 60 's uptempo gospel / soul workout and is another personal favorite of mine here . " Mrs. Under , Stood " uses some interesting wordplay with a very chunky mid tempo funk / pop groove . And On",the only collaboration here with Da Brat is my least favorite song here . and repetitious electro dance / pop number which , by the way is used to greater effect on the more live jazz instrumental sounding gospel workout " Jesus I Want You " . The album concludes with her interpretation of " Cry Me A River"-a number that lives up to Chante 's vocal talents . Overall this is an excellent album outside of one song which came off like an easy way to get radio airplay when pop music is still trying to resolve an extremely shallow and condescending period . As for Chante ' Moore herself she delivers a consistently strong album for the most part . when few popular artists had developed a well rounded musical back - round for an enduring appeal , she is proven herself more than versatile and talented to weather whatever musical storm she has been caught up in her career .

summary: Charles Bradley Ain't Gonna Give It Up
reviewText: About five years ago , I got seriously into the whole Daptone label music scene . It was not just the instrumental style of the music And was very excited to pick up his third Again , there is no disappointment . The album opens with a partially spoken word , organ / piano based version of " God Bless America " where Bradly discussed the pros and cons of being black in this country . " Good To Be Back Home " is stomping , bluesy funk with phat electric guitar But You",the title song,"Crazy For Your Love " and the closer " Slow Love " are all reverbed guitar heavy ballads while " Are not Going To Give You Up " is a thick , slow deep funk groove with a bee like synthesizer buzzing . " Things We Do For Love " is a brightly melodic uptempo gospel / soul number filled with multiple backup singers " Change For The World " is an brief late 60's / early 70 's Ike Hayes like psychedelic funk message song warning about the revival of segregationist racial behavior . In a lot of ways , this might just be the very best album Charles Bradley has made and arrangements are full of enormous drama as well . Bradley 's voice , especially on his impassioned howls , are echoed intensely throughout nearly every song here .

" Love Gone Wrong " starts with a dazzling vocal by Dallas Green on a melody dipping slightly towards blues joined by Alecia Moore 's strong vocals , " I am gone for good . " " Break the Cycle " has a bigger sound with a stop - start melody as the piano lingers in the air before the vocals interrupt , " Tell me the words you long to hear & I will sing them loud & clear ; Let me heal the wounds you have held on to for all these years . " " Open Door " is stripped down with a lovely melody " Rose Ave . " is obviously a labor of love , performed with passion , well worth your ear . Enjoy !

summary: A wonderfully mellow debut from Swedish duo Kings Of Convenience! Erlend Oye has an amazingly soothing voice!
reviewText: Though " Quiet Is The New Loud " lacks a hit like " I would Rather Dance With You " from their newest album " Riot On An Empty Street " , every song here is wonderfully mellow and good enough to make it a better album overall ( that one had some bad tracks ) . Erlend Oye was clearly blessed with one of the most soothing voices in the music business . Not only are the vocals great , but the lyrics are also very interesting , even if they lack catchiness . That is not really what this album 's about anyway ; it is about relaxing . The instrumentation is also pretty simple - it is basically just acoustic guitars but they are wonderful here - they perfectly encapsulate the mood . " Failure " and " I Do not Know What I Can Save You From " may be the standout tracks , but , really , they are all wonderful . They may not be breaking any new ground here , but they do not really have to - you are going to love it anyway . Practically any music fan will love this , and for that it definitely earns " 5 " stars . that it definitely earns " 5 " stars . You will never get tired of listening to this ! This is highly recommended !

Prime Cuts : Beautiful Offerings , Come Sit Down , Good Good Father When Big Daddy Weave named their much anticipated seventh studio album " Beautiful Offerings , " it is not hyperbole . These songs are truly " beautiful " in the sense that scratches behind the superficial veneer . that they are paeans of our heartfelt struggles and praises offered as worship to the Almighty God . Rather than going the steely EDM gauze route , they have opted to let the acoustics of warmer instruments such as the acoustic guitar , banjos , and the gentle pull of strings pave a more tepid feel for what is Big Daddy Weave 's most reflective record . that this album has no feet moving moments , it is just Big Daddy Weave is one of the top artists in Christian music : they are one of the genre 's biggest headlining artists , the second most played artist at Christian AC - Monitored radio in 2014 and the recipient of multiple industry awards With a brand - new studio album , entitled Beautiful Offerings , coming September 18 , 2015 , the band 's latest and career best - selling album , Love Come To Life , celebrated four consecutive No . 1 singles along with recent news that " Redeemed " has been certified gold by the RIAA . Formed in 2002 , Big Daddy Weave is : Mike Weaver , Jay Weaver , Jeremy Redmon , Joe Shirk , With an orchestrated grandeur of strings leading the way , the title cut " Beautiful Offerings " is worship at its best . Rather than coming to God with a puff - up chest , " Beautiful Offerings " finds a broken protagonist coming with his tatters to God for healing again . and uber songwriter Jason Ingram , is a powerhouse testimony of God 's transformative grace wrapped in the fabric of a True - to - life narrative . It wrestles with the Biblical image of how the Savior is both the lion as well as the lamb ; a thought that can blow our minds to nothing but worship . Mike Weaver gets the most intimate with his emotionally nuanced rasp on the piano - led " Come Sit Down . that some of the songs are easy for our concentration to slide . And deluxe version 's penultimate track " Jesus I Believe " is a not - to - be - missed : it is honest , gripping , and so Christ - focused . " Beautiful Offerings " may have its weak spots , The majority of the songs are beautiful and a pleasing offering to Jesus .

summary: Another strong '80s album from Iron Maiden
reviewText: No heavy metal band was as consistently great in the 1980 's as Iron Maiden and Somewhere in Time is another strong album from the British band . when some of the traditional heavy metal bands ( most notably Judas Priest ) started experimenting with keyboards While this style did not work for Priest ( who overdid the guitar synthesizers to the point of making them sound like a pop band ) , it worked for Iron Maiden " Wasted Years " would be the first single / video and is one of their best as it has a memorable guitar line and dare I say , a very catchy chorus . The mid - tempo " Stranger in a Strange Land " was nearly as good and has become one of their best deep cuts . " Caught Somewhere In Time " was another in a long line of musically challenging opening cuts performed at a frenetic pace ( the band 's opening tracks were the best of the genre , bar none ) . The highlights continue throughout the album as " Sea of Madness " is a riveting track that slows down briefly before coming back harder while " Heaven Can Wait " starts out quite somber with Steve Harris 's bass synth line before becoming a classic metal track Other highlights include the killer epic " The Loneliness of the Long Distance Runner " and the wicked unison guitar lines The last track , " Alexander the Great " , while musically ambitious , does not touch the rest of the album . All told , Somewhere in Time is another strong album from a band that had a ton of them .

summary: Metallica and Thrash metal classic and a must own for metal fans
reviewText: and the follow up , Master Of Puppets , are the albums to get , if you are a metal fan anyways . these 2 are hands down their best . For an , at the time , little known metal band , the production is really good . Everyone is in top form . which adds to the charm of this album . they had some good material , partly thanks to Megadeth frontman Dave Mustaine . And they put together a flawless album worthy of every metal fan 's attention . Fight Fire With Fire 10/10 - starts off with an acoustic intro All this to lead into possibly the fastest Metallica song ever . This is a perfect opener with great guitar work , this is definitely in a long list of favorite songs by Metallica , The Lightning 9/10 is an upper mid tempo song with solid vocals and a nice riff in the verses . Plus a catchy chorus . Overall a very good song . For Whom The Bell Tolls 10/10 might be my favorite Metallica song ever . Whom The Bell Tolls 10/10 might be my favorite Metallica song ever . Granted it has stiff competition , This one has a nice groove to it . This one 's still fairly heavy , There are some good melodies , and the guitar playing is really good . I hate to give credit to Lars , It starts with an acoustic guitar with some electric leads . It does not really have a chorus , just a riff , instrumental based chorus , similar to what Black Sabbath did a lot . And it works fine . The first 2 verses are slow ballad acoustic style , then the song speeds up for the bridge Overall a very good song . Trapped Under Ice 9/10 after a ballad , what do any good metal bands do ? They come back with a fast paced thrasher , This is the second fastest song on the album . The song has a nice pace to it , and is an overall fun listen . Escape 9/10 is kind of the pop song of the album . Odd it gets no recognition . It has a really good chorus , yet another in a long list of great songs on here . Creeping Death 10/10 is another contender for favorite Metallica song . It is a fairly fast paced thrasher with a great horus . It has some slower parts as well and is a great way to close out the album . Then there is an instrumental It is played just fine , so I am sure for fans of them it will do . Overall if you are a metal fan new to Metallica , which would be surprising , this is a good place to start . You will not be disappointed .

At this point in their life Mott acheived some success with Bowie 's All The Young Dudes and went further than the glam - rock posturing of the album with this masterpiece . Ironing out the rough edges of All The Yound Dudes with this well produced sounding batch of songs Mott never strayed from their roots of hard melodic rock that reach a crescendo of guitar fused power . Ian Hunter sneers like a British Dylan and the energy of rockers like Little Richard the temperment of the Velvet Underground , hippie leanings of folkies like Melanie never leaves their music . Mott 's songs remain winners to this day and takes the All The Young Dudes sound further by giving a polish to that rougher sounding diamond Both are essential with the followup The Hoople cd a great listen of great songs but lacks the cohesive feel of Mott nonetheless all 3 cd 's are wonderful .

summary: The Stones Step out of Their Comfort Zone as They Look for Their Next Member
reviewText: To say this is a curious album for the Rolling Stones is a bit of an understatement . Among the hopeful new guitarists were Rory Gallagher , Steve Marriott , Jeff Beck , Harvey Mandel , Wayne Perkins , Peter Frampton , and Ronnie 's work would appear on the subsequent album . Though the majority of the album sticks True to their electric blues roots , there are also elements of reggae ( see " Cherry Oh Baby " ) which were pretty far out of the band 's usual playbook . and bravado . Opening with " Hot Stuff " followed by " Hand Of Fate , " the door gets kicked in pretty heavily before the gears shift for their cover of Eric Donaldson 's " Cherry Oh Baby . " Side 1 closes with the slow blues burn of " Memory Motel " and Keith contributed lead vocals to a love song embedded within a tale of life on the road . Side 2 opens with " Hey Negrita , " another bluesy - rock number , then shifts to the bluesy - jazz " Melody , " which features the piano work of Billy Preston rather prominently . " Fool To Cry , " the album 's second single , follows before closing out with the rockin ' " Crazy Mama . " And Blue is a solid addition to the Stones already stellar catalog , but it does not hold as much reverence as , say , albums like Beggars Banquet , Let It Bleed , Sticky Fingers , or Exile On Main St. when you record some of the all - time greatest rock ' n ' roll records back to back to back , do not you deserve a little time off ? A chance to step back And Blue is all about , a chance for the Stones to step out of their comfort zone If all you know of the Rolling Stones is their greatest hits albums , you will recognize " Hot Stuff " and " Fool To Cry " from Jump Back . In my opinion , the strongest outings on this album are " Hot Stuff , " " Hand Of Fate , " and " Crazy Mama " ; these are what I would consider to be the * essential * tracks on Black and " Hey Negrita " are pretty cool to listen to , and excellent " late night " tracks for relaxin ' at home . I am not a huge fan of " Fool To Cry , " though ; it reminds me too much of " Angie , " But overall , this is an album worth having whether or not you are out to collect the entire Stones catalog ; if nothing else , it makes an excellent bookend ( but in a good way ) .

" Phrazes For the Young " ( 8 tracks ; 40 min . ) is the classic case of a traditional A and somewhat reminiscent of the classic Strokes sound of strumming electric guitars . " Left & Right in the Dark " and " 11th Dimension " also are quite pleasant to the ear . By the time we get to the closing track " Tourist " , a mid - tempo track with gorgeous musical layering that feels like a catharsis . It is my second favorite track on the album and a great way to close out the album . that this was a " Strokes - like " short album . that he has high hopes for mainstream - commercial success for this album , which truly surprised me , I mean , really ? . Now What ? ! is the nineteenth full - length studio album by the legendary British Rock band Deep Purple , it was their third studio album with Don Airy on Keyboards On very first listen , a lot of the album washed over me , leaving a generally positive , but honestly not too impressed or interested impression . but a genuinely good one , with literally no weak tracks . It is a grower for sure . Usually , I really enjoy any Deep Purple album , and have enjoyed most Morse era albums to some extent , however sometimes they can feel like there is a bit of filler , or there is a minor lack of consistency , stopping the albums feeling as great as the old days even when over half the album has some genuinely great songs . is the perfect Morse era album , it all fits perfectly together , there is variety and all the songs are as good as the very best tracks on another Morse era album . Highlights include the symphonic ` Uncommon Man ' dedicated to the late Jon Lord , which feels like a mixture between Close To The Edge era Yes with Works era ELP , the energetic and memorable ` Apres Vous ' which has a very catchy chorus , and the interesting although to be honest its all great . The only real negative thing I can think to say is and variety . and always find it a great and exciting album all the more for having done so , but that is just personal preference , most people have no problems with that is just personal preference , most people have no problems with Seriously , it is a great album ; the rhythm section are tight and steady , Airy and Ian Gillan fits into his older vocal style more comfortably here than ever . Overall ; Now What ? ! is a very good album from the veteran Rock band , easily in the top fifty percent of their catalogue . It is a well produced and well written collection of interesting songs , with a great sense of subtly , musicianship and even a few surprises . Check it out if you like Deep Purple , and especially if you have liked their modern output . And if you do check it out , do not just listen to it once , give it a good few spins and really let it sink in , you will thank yourself for it after a while .

There really is not much to be said about Nirvana 's breakthrough album " Nevermind " and helped set forward the grunge movement . The massive success of the single " Smells Like Teen Spirit " catapaulted Nirvana to a never before imagined status ; and ultimately helped set the stage of lead singer / songwriter Kurt Cobain 's untimely demise . All the hype that still surrounds this album aside , " Nevermind " is one heck of a rock record . " In Bloom " and " Come As You Are " became instant rock radio classics , while other tracks like " Lithium " , " Polly " , " Lounge Act " , and " Something in the Way " are nothing short of amazing pure unadulterated hard rock . and missed out on the impact and band had , now has never been a better time to dig in .

summary: Definitive collection of the Arista years, 1990 to 2010
reviewText: although we hope that he still has some great music to come , whichever label he signs for . The singles from his last Arista album of original recordings , the excellent Freight train , did not do as well as those from his earlier albums . Initially , I wondered if American country radio stations were losing interest , No doubt there will others in the years to come , but they will just recycle the material already released , together with whatever unreleased material lies in the Arista vaults . that 34 of these 37 tracks were number one hits , but they were not all number one of the American Billboard country charts . Most of the others came close , so maybe they were number ones on some other chart such as Cashbox ( I don`t have access to Cashbox charts , so can not check ) . Here in the real world ( the title track of his first Arista album ) , did not make number one on Billboard but was number one on the Canadian country chart , but all of Alan 's other Canadian number ones were also number one on Billboard . Still , whether the title is accurate or not , it is fair to say that every track here is excellent . It would have been easy for Arista to compile a triple CD , but they probably struck the right balance in limiting this compilation to a double CD . Still , the absence of tracks such as Murder on Music Row ( with George Strait ) , When somebody loves you ( a top five country hit ) , I will go on loving you ( a top three country hit ) , Mercury blues ( a number two country hit ) , Everything I love , Pop a top that Alan had plenty of great hits besides what you will find here . The three tracks not claimed as number ones ironically include one track that made it to number one on Billboard - As she is walking away , in Ring of fire , a mellow cover of the old Johnny Cash classic , was a minor country hit but it is a fine song . or not there are 35 number one hits here does not matter ; Alan had almost 50 top ten hits on the Billboard country charts , every one a gem , that did not make the top ten ( especially Murder on Music Row ) are also regarded by many fans as classics . This collection provides a fitting tribute to Alan 's 21 years of great music with Arista , whether this is your first Alan Jackson album or whether ( like me ) you have most of the tracks already .

reviewText: Almost the perfect song by a wonderful artist .

For many , this is the only Yes song they have ever heard - well , this and " Owner Of A Lonely Heart " - but it is arguably the best distillation of everything good about Yes . As was the case with the Doors ' " Light My Fire , " many of us first heard the edited 45 rpm version back in ' 72 , only to find there was a version twice as long on the album . Come to think of it , " Roundabout " dashes through the door " Light My Fire " had opened five years previously . Both employ a prominent Classical - sounding organ riff along with Spanish guitar scales . However , next to " Roundablut , " " Light My Fire " sounds positively earthbound ( not that that is a bad thing ) . that is a bad thing ) . and Yes should have swapped lead singers , just as an experiment . summary: Bentley Makes the Bluegrass "Ridge" Viable Again
reviewText:
Prime Cuts : Love Grows Wild , Draw Me a Map , Fallin ' for You 

 Call it progressive bluegrass or acoustic Americana , Dierks Bentley has indeed taken a chance with this new disc " Up on the Ridge . " Though he has built up a cachet of hits including 7 number i hits and 3 number 1 albums , few with his stature would take such a risky excursion by recording an album worth of bluegrass / acoustic   entries . Patty Loveless , Lorrie Morgan but they were fraught with commercial disappointment at the chagrin of the money - hungry record executives . that lead single and title track " Up on the Ridge " has already made headlines in the top 40 region of the country charts , looks like Bentley will be the exception to the rule . This time round , Bentley has ditched long time friend and co - producer Brett Beavers in favour of former recording artist and songwriter Jon Randall Stewart to warm the co - producer chair . And if you are a fan of old time bluegrass and would not mind a contemporary slant , this disc is choked full of great tunes . With Bentley co - writing only 5 cuts with new tunes coming from Nashville 's top scribes including Shawn Camp , Paul Kennerley , John Scott Sherrill , Verlon Thompson And up the bar on the standard of the songs , he has audaciously turned Bob Dylan 's " Senor ( Tales of Yankee Power ) " and U2 's " Pride " into bluegrass covers . As if to win him some brownie points with bluegrass purists , Chris Tile and the Punch Brothers join Bentley on a sped up version of Dylan 's " Senor ( Tales of Yankee Power ) " where Bentley goes around searching for his missing girl . that lonesome with Chris Tile 's smooth Vince Gill - like tenor that goes so well with Bentley 's more rugged vocals . that goes so well with Bentley 's more rugged vocals . Miranda Lambert adds rawness to " Bad Angel " -a quasi - Gospel romp about a man shrugging off vices at the " crossroads of Salvation and Temptation Streets . " While Jamey Johnson with his world - weary gruffness brings a realistic feel to the man 's battle with the bottle .   Kris Kristofferson , on the other hand , sounds worn out that becomes distracting . While the Alison Krauss ' echoey vocals sounds like she was singing in a well on the progressive bluegrass title cut " Up on the Ridge"--a pretty non - descript song relative to the rest of the album . and Paul Kennerley 's bluesy " Fallin ' for You " is hypnotic with a robust melody made even more delightful with its banjo " Draw Me A Map " finds Bentley on more romantic grounds as he croons with affection to find his way into his lady 's heart . A definite must for those who like to experience the warmer side of Bentley . and Buddy Miller , often earmarked by their eccentric Americana endeavours , have ironically submitted the most commercial viable track here . " Love Grows Wild " sounds like a future hit with its catchy melody and it is endearing lyrics . Bravura is Bentley to taper U2 's " Pride ( In the Name of Love ) " chiming guitar riffs into something more rustic without sacrificing an iota of the song 's spiritual Bentley has indeed taken a chance to go all out to record " Up on the Ridge " with little nod to commerciality . He just let us his respect and love for tradition show . And as a result , this will indeed pay off with dividends of pure pleasures to those who like their country uncluttered .

summary: Nostalgic song, great MP3, but best for those who remember the 70s.
reviewText: Muskrat Love is one of those humorous songs that somehow unintentionally morphed into some kind of deep commentary on shallow love . Initially composed as a whimsical tune about anthropomorphic muskrats under the name Muskrat Candlelight , it was a minor hit for America before The Captain and Tenille turned it into a huge hit in the 1970 's . Now , decades later , this song is a nostalgic reminder of a more innocent time . The MP3 version is far clearer than any 45 record or LP album cut from the 1970 's , so it is far more enjoyable , especially The Captain 's electronic sounds of muskrats kissing For a modern 21st century audience , this song probably will not catch their ear and just wants a reminder of a different time in life , it is worth the download for the gentle smile

summary: Strong Fifth Studio Effort From Cole - 4 stars
reviewText: A superb voice should never have a ' recession . ' Keyshia Cole epitomizes this notion as she possesses an incredible voice 2010's Calling All Hearts was not her best album , but it also was by no means bad , yielding strong cuts the likes of " Long Way Down , " " Tired of Doing Me , " But 2012's Woman To Woman is better and closer to her best work on debut effort Way It Is and the valedictory sophomore effort Just Like You . The parallels unveil themselves throughout the emotional , inspired Woman To Woman , which finds Cole 's brand of contemporary adult R&B at its best . She gets some help from Lil Wayne , Meek Mill , Ashanti , Elijah Blake , That said , none of the overshadow the chanteuse . " Enough of No Love " was the ' big hit ' that Calling All Hearts was missing ( The Nicki Minaj assisted " I Are not Thru " was not quite it ) . Well produced by Harmony She talks a bit of trash , but does not overdo it as so many artists do today for shock value . By the chorus , she is on fire : " Because I - I can not stay here / if there is no love / yeah because I have had enough / enough of no love ... " Lil Wayne delivers a solid enough verse , reigning himself in Excellent start by all means . " Zero , " featuring Meek Mill , is a turn at modern R&B with some minimalist aspects . but easily grows on you as one of the better cuts ( not that any are bad ) on Woman To Woman . " You see it pays to tell the truth , look at what you had to lose , " Cole sings on the chorus " ... should think before you do , did you not know the rules ? " Meek Mill assists on the third verse ; " I lie just to protect you , never to disrespect you / because what we have was so 38 special ... " " Missing You " gives Cole a solid , traditional R&B cut intact with fat , lazy bass line , contrasting the more modern tactics of " Zero . " Guitar - patch intact from The Way It Is 's " Love , " Cole delivers with exemplary class on this Eric Hudson produced cut . " Trust or " Saving All My Love . " It does not reach the classicism of either of the two cuts , but that is the parallel on this big ballad propelled by the tenets of classic soul that is the parallel on this big ballad propelled by the tenets of classic soul Filled with many lyrical highlights , one incredibly memorable line is where ' the money is ' : " Trust and Believe me , you are going to need me / trust and I am so over you , go get lost / boy Cole puts some ' stank ' on the closing note ( you just have to hear it ) . If " Trust And Believe " was not enough of a hit , " Get It Right " ' gets it done ' with old - school dusty drum programming and excellent adult contemporary R&B production by Mel The vocal treatment at the onset is celestial , foreshadowing the strength of the cut . Cole 's vocals continue to captivate throughout , never faltering . Delivering another catchy , emotion chorus , " Get It Right " makes five straight hits . " Woman 2 Woman " features a shocking collaboration with Ashanti . Surprisingly , the collaboration works better than one pre - judges with Ashanti complimenting Cole well . " Woman 2 Woman " is certainly an extension of " Trust " from Cole's A Different Me , a duet with Monica . While " Trust " may have been more notable , " Woman 2 Woman " features all the right nuances Easily one of the stronger title tracks of 2012 . " Wonderland " featuring Elijah Blake is another solid cut . It is not preeminent as say " Enough of No Love " or " Trust but it is not too shabby either . " I Choose You " is better , produced by Jack Splash Cole 's upper register sounds exceptional on this cut , highlight on the chorus : " If it are not you , it is not worth it / no matter what I do , nothing working / baby I know love 's not perfect / even if he can save the world that will never be enough / and If it are not you , then it is just not worth it . " On " Stubborn , " Rodney " Darkchild " Jerkins and Paul " Hollywood Hotsauce " Dawson give Cole more of a modern flair . Being the talented vocalist / artist That said , Cole seems best suited for more refined , lush contemporary R&B cuts " Hey Sexy " provides appropriate atonement , characterized by its 80 's styled R&B groove . Throughout the course of the number , the addictive catch line " I know you are not , not going to sing The chorus is equally catchy : " Sexy ( sexy ) rock me ( rock me ) all night long / Hold me to the break of dawn / I love it when you turn me on ... " " Next Move , " assisted by Robin Thicke 's supporting vocals , loses no steam . Bink ! 's production is superb , notable for the use of flute and hand percussion to create an incredibly lush opening . Thicke simply supports Cole with harmonizing vocals , which is smart for this particular cut . Right up Cole 's alley , Cole ' kills ' " Next Move , " a song or female will make the ' next move ' in the pending relationship , etc . Closing cut " Signature " takes on a mix of pop and R&B sensibility proving to be quite the appropriate closing track . " Signature " caps off an excellent album . Overall , Woman To Woman finds Cole in excellent voice . She is best when she connects with the material as she does here , particularly on soulful , heart wrenching numbers like " Trust or " I Choose You " with its soulful stylings . There are no misses with even the modern tinges of " Stubborn " ultimately not dragging Woman To Woman down , making this one of 2012 's best urban offerings ultimately . It has stiff competition with the alt - R&B movement of Frank Ocean and the best moments of Brandy 's ' Two Eleven , ' Cole shows that R&B is NOT dead . 4 stars ; Enthusiastically recommended .

summary: TOP Knocking Themselves Out Right Off The Bat
reviewText: History is littered with a lot of romantic talk of the bay area music scene of the late 60 's . But there were some important hybrids too . A multi racial band coming out of the same stew as the Santana Band and Sly & The Family Stone this was a band and Sly & The Family Stone this was a band that , especially in the beginning were very much on what you might call the very live garage band type of funk . Right off the bat the album kicks off with " Knock Yourself Out " . This along with the witty " Social Lubrication " And The Fly",with almost goofy lyrical exchanges are TOP before they were even closed to slick . The rhythm section is right out in your face , the horns are blaring right out or other though , there is a mild soulful gentleness to the whole thing . Especially as a number of these songs lead out with some mildly bluesy Hendrix type rock guitar riffs . The real break from the funk tradition this album tends to set is the closer " Sparkling In The Sand " . This is a very slow 9 + minute ballad It is surprising with the amount of funk process activity taking place on both ends of the Bay Area in 1970 - with Sly Stone , Santana , War and Tower Of Power here all making extremely important contributions , And laid the groundwork for what is sometimes called " united funk " .

summary: Career-spanning box with mono singles, rarities and unreleased tracks
reviewText: Sly and the Family Stone 's catalog has never been difficult to find . which , 1970's Greatest Hits , was their first album to top the charts ) , the band 's original albums have been remastered Pulling together pre - Family obscurities , hit singles ( many in their punchy mono single mixes ) , album cuts , live performances and previously unissued material creates an arc of musical discovery or holy ) different picture than hearing the material in separate installments . Stewart served as a staff producer for Autumn , helming sessions for the Beau Brummels , Mojo Men , Great Society and others ( see Precious Stone,Listen to the Voices,The Autumn Records Story and Dance With Me for more of his production work ) , and produced for Bobby Freeman . The B - side , " Scat Swim , " cut a deeper groove than the plug side , and his next single , " Buttermilk ( Part 1 ) , " was a catchy blue - soul instrumental , with Stewart playing all the instruments , including organ and harmonica leads . and his last single for Autumn , " Temptation Walk , " show how early ( and easily ) and jazz into his original stew . After leaving Autumn , Stewart quickly assembled what was to become Sly In the wake of the group 's later success , two of the tracks , the original " I Are not Got Nobody ( For Real ) " and a cover of Otis Redding 's " I Can not Turn You Lose , " were released on the Loadstone label . and topped by the Family Stone 's trademark trumpet - sax combination of Cynthia Robinson The group began recording for Epic ( at the same Golden State Recorders at and the fruits of these initial sessions fill out disc one , starting with their first A - side , " Underdog , " and " Bad Risk . " Despite a fresh sound that crackled with the energy of its multiple roots , neither the single nor the album A Whole New Thing made a commercial impression at the time ; it was not until " Dance to the Music " was recorded in September Launched in January 1968 , " Dance to the Music " quickly established the group 's revolutionary combination of pop , rock , soul , funk The group was sufficiently prolific as to leave fully - finished masters in the vault , including the four Here you will find the band trying out previously unheard original songs , experimental vocal arrangements , The July - August 1967 session tracks continue on disc two , showing the wealth of great material produced before the band finally hit with " Dance to the Music . " and " Only One Way Out of This Mess " ) were previously issued on the expanded edition of A Whole New Thing , but three more are included here for the first time : an inventive cover of the pop - folk song " What is it Got to Do With Me , " an early take on the autobiographical " Future and Fame " All five session tracks are as good as the material that made the original album , but the lack of early commercial success doomed this extra material to a long stay in the vault . The band 's commercial breakthrough is finally heard six tracks into disc two , with the ecstatic three - minute mono single mix of " Dance to the Music . " The song is , quite literally , a brilliantly catchy tutorial on the sound being created before the listener 's very ears . As memorable as are the mono singles , stereo album sides like " Ride the Rhythm " more expansively show off the band 's inventive arrangements and tight musicianship as they explode across the soundstage . Disc two finishes out with album tracks from Dance to the Music , the previously unreleased " We Love All , " the obscure mostly - instrumental French - language single " Danse a la Musique " ( and it is even stranger Chipmunk - voiced B - side , " Small Fries " ) , the unreleased B - side " Chicken , " and exuberant sides from Life , including mono single masters for " Life " ( with a different lead vocal track than the album cut ) and " M'Lady . " Disc three opens with the band 's second smash single , the # 1 " Everyday People " and " I Want to Take You Higher , " powered the commercial success of the band 's third album . As with their debut , the band recorded a lot more material during the album sessions than they could issue , and disc three includes another helping of previously unreleased bonuses , including unused instrumental backings . The group became a hot live act , essayed here with performances from the 1970 Isle of Wight Festival , and scored in 1969 as singles artists with " Hot Fun in the Summertime , " " Everybody is a Star " and " Thank You ( Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin ) , " all heard here as mono singles . The final disc open with the band 's next album, There is a Riot Going On , including album tracks Ironically , though the album yielded the hit " Family Affair , " it was recorded in large part by Stone alone , with overdubs by Family members or joyous mood of the band 's earlier material , The group 's singles ( including " If You Want Me to Stay " and " Time for Livin ' " ) continued to chart in the Top 40 , as did their final two albums Fresh By 1975 Sly had disbanded the Family Stone and begun to record as a solo artist backed by hired musicians . His album High on You , expands beyond the musical boundaries of the Family Stone , adding steel guitar Disc four closes out with selections from Stone 's solo work , from the then - newly formulated Family Stone 's Heard Ya Missed Me , Well I am Back , but that is in balance with the band 's rise to fame , the peaking of their invention , that is in balance with the band 's rise to fame , the peaking of their invention , This is a well thought out anthology , touching on Stewart 's pre - Family solo work , the Family 's rise to fame , their chart domination and fire as a live act , their eventual end and Sly Stone 's return to solo work . and a large helping of original mono single mixes . The only real omission from this set are the studio versions of " Stand " and " I Want to Take You Higher ! , " each of The mono mixes will be greatly appreciated by fans For those without any of the group 's catalog on - hand , your surround sound - trained ears may find the stereo hits more immediately satisfying ; check out the album reissues , or the anthologies Greatest Hits The book includes finely written liner notes , an informative timeline , rare photographs , reproductions of labels , sleeves and revelatory track - by - track comments from the Greg Errico , Larry Graham , Jerry Martini , Cynthia Robinson , Sly Stone In addition to the standard 4 - CD set , there are several variations : an Amazon exclusive CD box and parallel MP3 downloads ) , a vinyl LP edition ( with its own Amazon exclusive variation )

and building on the success of the stripped back " Winter in America " , Gil Scott - Heron Whereas " Winter in America " was largely just Scott - Heron but with a healthy dose of funk overtones . The sound on this record is distinctive and quite unlike much of Scott - Heron 's other work-- in part Brown 's high tenor provides a fantastic offset to Scott - Heron 's lower register , and the two harmonize to great effect . The band supporting them is essentially a sax quartet ( Bilal Sunni Ali on reeds , Jackson on piano , Danny Bowens on electric bass The band whips up a blues / jazz / funk stew , anchored effectively by Bowens , who proves stunningly agile and effective , weaving in and out of the delicate wall of percussion The pieces themselves on the album are staggering in their diversity , from a mournful blues ( " Winter in America " ) to a delicate and serene jazz ballad ( " Offering " ) to deep funk ( " The Liberation Song " ) and spoken word ( " Pardon Our Analysis " ) . As expected , Scott - Heron 's lyrical wit is in full effect , whether discussing the politics of Africa , the Nixon administration , the state of the nation or just reflections on everyday life , he is nothing short of brilliant . This reissue augments the album with a pair of bonus tracks- an extended spoken word piece including a reprise of Scott - Heron 's famed " The Revolution Will Not Be Televised " ( and one of the most brilliant performances on record by him in spoken word ) and sounds superb . It is not quite the masterpiece or its successor ( " From South Africa to South Carolina " ) is , but " The First Minute of a New Day " is a fantastic album , capturing an artist at his peak . Highly recommended .
